For semester 2008B, the TAC awarded our program with 16.5 hrs of GMOS-N time for five galaxies out of a total sample of nine targets. Six galaxies were observed under partly better conditions than Band 3. All spectra have been reduced and for 50% of the data velocity dispersions have been measured.

For semester 2009A, we asked for 21 hours of observing time but the TAC kindly awarded us with 23 hours of Band 2 (see also GS-2009A-Q-44). At GN the non-equatorial targets of this program should be observed. However, due to bad weather during the semster our program was never executed.

The remaining 10 equatorial targets of semester 2009A were observed from GS. 2 hours of longer exposure times resulted in better S/N spectra for two galaxies. The data reduction for this data set is ongoing.

p1_attachment_sets.text:
The Galactic center (GC) is a fascinating environment, containing a multitude of extraordinary phenomena and extraordinary objects, not the least of which are three dense clusters of young and hot stars and a multimillion solar mass black hole. Until recently it was thought that the interstellar gas within the central few hundred parsecs of the Galaxy consisted of three major components: an ultra high temperature X-ray-emitting plasma; ionized gas at T~10^4K responsible for the well-studied fine structure and radio recombination line emission; and cool and dense molecular clouds, which have also been observed in great detail at radio wavelengths. However, our infrared spectroscopy of H3+ and CO, and in particular of a key absorption line from a metastable state of that H3+ (Goto et al 2002, Oka et al. 2005), has clearly revealed the presence of a fourth component, which in terms of density (50-200 cm-3) has the characteristics of Galactic diffuse cloud material, but which is considerably warmer (200-300 K). This warm and diffuse environment appears to be unique to the Galactic center; it has not been found in any other Galactic clouds surveyed in H3+ to date.
Spectroscopy of H3+ is difficult because its lines are weak owing to its low abundance. Until recently we have had available as probes of the line of sight to the Galactic center only a small number of luminous sources in the central cluster and out to about 30 pc, which are both sufficiently bright for high resolution spectroscopy and have smooth infrared spectra so the H3+ line profiles are uncontaminated. Our spectra of these sources (e.g., Oka et al. 2005; Goto et al. 2008) show that the warm and diffuse component is present on every sightline and thus suggest that the environment in which it is found takes up a large fraction of the volume in the central few hundred parsecs. That would strongly contradict the previous conceptual picture of GC gas (e.g., as illustrated in Lazio & Cordes 1998), in which the warm and diffuse environment was not included at all. However, to truly evaluate the extent and physical nature of this new type of environment, sightlines covering a wider spatial extent of the GC are needed. It is therefore essential to find additional bright sources with featureless (or nearly featureless) spectra - either hot stars or stars encased in dense shells of warm dust - in a more extended region of the Galactic center.
The GC is filled with bright infrared sources, but everywhere except at locations of the clusters of hot stars the overwhelming majority of them are red giants, whose complex photospheric spectra make them totally unsuitable as probes of the interstellar medium. Until very recently no smooth-spectrum objects were know far from those clusters. However, we have begun to use 2MASS and Spitzer (GLIMPSE) photometry to identify bright objects in the GC likely to have opaque dust shells. An oversimplified description of the technique is that the shorter wavelength IR colors are mainly used to weed out foreground (low extinction) sources and "normal" red giants, and the longer wavelength IR colors are mainly used to identify emission from dust shells. However, the situation is far from straightforward, and our initial success rate, although orders of magnitude better than a random sampling, was only ~10%.
The key second step in the process, and the step for which we are requesting time here, is to obtain low-resolution K band spectra, in particular covering the first overtone CO bands, to see if the candidates do indeed have smooth spectra. Once that is verified we proceed to high-resolution spectroscopy of interstellar CO and H3+.
Our initial verification observations used UKIRT to obtain the low-resolution K-band spectra, but that option is no longer available. I. The Rise of Time-Domain Astronomy
A full characterization of the transient sky is one of the key observational frontiers in modern astronomy. It is driven by the fact that transient phenomena generally result from a rapid and violent release of energy and therefore provide a unique window into extreme physical conditions, massive star outbursts and deaths, and the diverse behavior of compact objects (white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes). In the optical regime, the study of transients has been focused for over a century on two primary classes of events - supernova explosions and nova eruptions, of which hundreds have been discovered and studied (e.g. [1,2]). One of the most striking results is that the two classes occupy narrow ranges of luminosities, with <M>~-8(+/-1) mag for novae and <M>~-18(+/-2) mag for SNe; see Figure 1.
This observational result, and the interest in classifying and studying large numbers of events (driven largely by the use of type Ia SNe as standard candles), has led to a plethora of nearby galaxy surveys and pencil-beam blind searches. The surveys are now so efficient that they recover nearly no other type of transient. Moreover, those that are focused on type Ia cosmology are highly efficient at rejecting other SN types, particularly unusual events.
Still, in recent years a combination of serendipitous discoveries (partly by amateurs) and nascent shallow wide-field searches have uncovered a few transients that reside in the broad desert between novae and SNe, as well as at luminosities that exceed normal SNe (M<-20 mag); see Figure 1 (e.g. [3-8]). There is currently intense debate about the nature of these events and their connection to the known classes (this is apparent in the various designations, such as "luminous red novae" and "SN impostors"). Most fundamentally, it is unclear if the intermediate events are eruptive or explosive [9,10], and whether the high-luminosity events result from the standard core-collapse of very massive stars or a new exotic explosion mechanism [5,11]. The identity of the progenitors, and their connection to various SN progenitors is equally shrouded in mystery [6,7].
Since existing surveys are fine-tuned to finding novae and normal SNe, progress in our understanding of the (currently) rare intermediate- and high-luminosity events requires a new approach. The most exciting prospects are provided by the now operational Panoramic Survey Telescope & Rapid Response System (Pan-STARRS), which is uniquely suited for this purpose given its unprecedented areal coverage and depth. Here we propose target-of-opportunity GMOS spectroscopy of Pan-STARRS transients in the nova-SN desert (-10 to -16 mag) and at high luminosity (<-20 mag) designed to classify and delineate their origin. We filter out novae and normal SNe since hundreds of these events are already found and studied through other surveys. Below we summarize the main types of events whose origin is controversial and that our program will begin to systematically address.
II. Intermediate-Luminosity Transients.
The triple outburst of the mundane star V838 Mon [3] established a possible new class of eruptions, with explanations ranging from the eruption of a common envelope white dwarf to planet capture. Three subsequent extragalactic events with similar luminosities have been associated with massive stars, suggesting that they represent an evolutionary stage on the path to SN explosions [4,6,7,9,10]. We recently studied the nearest of these events (NGC300 OT2008-1) and showed that its spectrum is clearly distinct from those of SNe, that it requires an energy of >10^47 erg, and that the circumstellar environment is suggestive of previous outbursts [7]. At present, it is unclear if the few known examples indeed share a common origin.
Potentially associated are "SN impostors" - several objects initially classified as SNe, which turned out to be photometrically and spectroscopically abnormal. These events likely include Luminous Blue Variable eruptions [11]. However, the most recent potential impostor (SN2008S) is nearly identical to NGC300 OT2008-1 [7], but has still been argued to be a faint SN [12] or an LBV outburst [9]. Similarly, there is an on-going debate about an emerging group of transients argued to represent extremely low-luminosity type Ia-like events, possibly as a result of deficient thermonuclear explosions [8]. An alternative explanation of core-collapse to a black hole with significant fall-back has also been proposed [14].
Although only a few intermediate-luminosity events are known, rough estimates of their intrinsic rates from current surveys are ~10-50% of the SN rate [7,8,10].
III. High-Luminosity Transients.
Most type Ia SNe peak at -19 mag with little dispersion (Figure 1). This has been attributed to a scenario in which a white dwarf accretes material from a companion until it nears the Chandrasekhar mass, thereby creating a standard luminosity explosion (the single-degenerate scenario). However, type Ia SNe may also result from the merger of two white dwarfs (the double-degenerate scenario). In this case the combined mass may be super-Chandrasekhar, leading to a more luminous explosion. The best potential example to date is SNLS-03D3bb, which peaked at -20 mag and generated about 1.3 solar masses of nickel-56 [13]. Finding events with a nickel mass in excess of the Chandrasekhar mass (~1.4 M_sun) will confirm the double-degenerate scenario.
Even more luminous events have been found, approaching -23 mag and requiring kinetic energies >10^52 erg (e.g. [5,14,15]). Spectroscopically, the few known events appear diverse, but they bear some similarity to "naked" core-collapse SNe of types IIn and Ib/c (objects whose massive progenitors lost most of their hydrogen and helium envelope before exploding). This possible connection, and the role of mass or binarity in producing the extreme luminosities, remain hotly debated [14,15]. Spectroscopy provides a clear test since naked SNe are powered by interaction of the blastwave with the ejected envelope, and are thus dominated by H and He lines from photoionized and/or shock-accelerated circumstellar material. These optical features will allow us to measure the mass loss history and composition of the envelope, direct clues to the nature of the progenitors.
The high-luminosity events are rare, representing only a few percent of the SN rate, but at the Pan-STARRS depth they can be found to z~1.

Pan-STARRS is a 1.8-m survey telescope with a 7 deg^2 camera. It provides the first deep optical all-sky time-domain survey, using two primary modes: the 3pi and the medium-deep surveys (MDS). The former covers 3pi steradians with a cadence of weeks to months, and a depth of 22.5 AB mag per image. The MDS consists of 10 fields (each 7 deg^2) uniformly spread in RA and ranging in declination from -30 to +60 deg. It has a much faster cadence of 4 days (cycling between the grizy filters), and reaches a depth of 23.5 AB mag. Six MDS fields are observed at any time, accounting for 25% of the survey. Pan-STARRS is now in regular operations and we have already found and classified events using our 2009B Gemini program (e.g. Narayan et al. ATEL 2214).
Our Harvard/CfA group is a member of the Pan-STARRS consortium and therefore has access to all proprietary Pan-STARRS data. This is essential for host galaxy identifications/redshifts, and for tracing the evolution/colors of transients (see below).
For this proposal, which requires a robust rejection of novae, normal SNe, and variable AGN, a high cadence of observations is essential. This will also allow exotic intermediate- and high-luminosity events to be found within days of occurrence, providing a full characterization of their behavior. Therefore, we focus only on the MDS events; the 3pi survey will include similar events, but the much higher contamination rate will be extremely wasteful of Gemini time.
To estimate the expected event rates we use as a baseline the Pan-STARRS project estimated MDS discovery rate of about 350 type Ia SNe and 65 core-collapse SNe per month at <22.5 mag (well-matched to our signal-to-noise needs for GMOS; see below). Accounting for the smaller volume accessible for intermediate-luminosity events, we find an expected rate of ~10 per month. The intrinsic rate of these events is not well known due to the small number of events to date, but it is roughly 10-50% of the SN rate. Thus, Pan-STARRS will find about 2 intermediate-luminosity events per month. Similarly, taking into account the volume for the high-luminosity events, and an intrinsic fraction of a few percent of the SN rate, we find an expected rate of ~2 per month. Our total rate is therefore ~4 events per month, of which half can be accessed at each Gemini telescope (to spread the load between Gemini-N and Gemini-S).
To separate out the events of interest we need to impose a strict set of criteria to eliminate novae, normal SNe, and AGN variability (as well as Galactic foreground). The decision tree leading from Pan-STARRS transient discovery to triggering of a Gemini spectrum is shown in Figure 2. First, we require a non-detection within 4 days prior to discovery (equal to the MDS cadence to ensure a young age). Second, to remove AGN we require events to brighten by >0.5 mag at discovery (AGN rarely vary by >0.5 mag in <4 days), and we also impose an astrometric offset of >5-sigma from the host galaxy nucleus. At the signal-to-noise ratio corresponding to <22.5 mag and the typical Pan-STARRS FWHM (~1 arcsec), this corresponds to about 1.5 pixels (0.256 arcsec/pixel). From our experience with ESSENCE this was sufficient to separate SNe from AGN. Clearly, this cut will result in the loss of real events, but at the expected redshifts typical galaxies have radii >2 arcsec, leading to a minor event loss of <5%. Finally, as the MDS data accumulate we will eliminate AGN based on long-term variability.
Next, we cut on the intrinsic luminosity (-10 to -16 mag for intermediate-luminosity and <-20 mag for high-luminosity). This requires coincidence with a galaxy, which will also eliminate Galactic foreground events. The luminosity will be inferred from existing galaxy redshifts (many of the MDS fields include large redshift surveys such as SDSS) or from photometric redshifts based on the Pan-STARRS data. Robust photo-z values will be available at z<0.5, sufficient for our targets. To remove dust-extincted normal SNe we also use a cut on the colors. For our luminosity cut, an extinction of A_V>2 mag is required to move normal SNe into our selection window (g-r>0.7 mag and r-i>0.4 mag for the Galactic extinction curve). Using the intrinsic colors of SNe at z<0.1 (the distance limit for our intermediate-luminosity events) we find that cuts of g-r<0.4 mag and r-i<0.3 mag will eliminate reddened normal SNe. Finally, we use an apparent magnitude range of 18-22 mag (brighter events can be observed with smaller telescopes).
We stress that the rates and efficacy of the cuts are estimated from existing knowledge. As expected for a new parameter space, some contamination and a revision in rates will occur. Our selection criteria at present are conservative, as appropriate for the first round of Pan-STARRS follow-up observations.
For the Gemini observations we request "Standard TOO triggers" (activation of >1 day) with GMOS. In practice, the delay can be several days given the modest evolution of these events near peak, thereby reducing the stress on Gemini operations. The primary purpose of our proposed observations is to classify the events and determine their properties (velocities, chemical composition, environment); see Figure 3. Clearly, the various types of events can be cleanly separated and studied spectroscopically. Each trigger will be a single spectrum designed to achieve S/N>1 per resolution element (R<22mag), and cover about 5000-9000A (e.g. SiII, H-beta, H-alpha, HeI, [CaII]). The spectral features are broad (>10^3 km/s; Figure 3), so the spectra can be further binned in post-processing to achieve higher S/N. Using the GMOS ITC we find that for the R400 grating this requires an exposure time of 2400 sec with 2x2 binning, a 1" slit, and observing conditions of 80%-ile (appropriate for slow TOOs). Including calibrations, acquisitions, and overheads, this corresponds to 1 hour per object, or a total request of 12 HOURS OF GEMINI-NORTH.
We request half the allocation from NOAO and half from Gemini-Staff and note that we can accomplish our scientific goals even with allocation from only one partner.

The Galactic center (GC) is a fascinating environment, containing a multitude of extraordinary phenomena and extraordinary objects, not the least of which are three dense clusters of young and hot stars and a multimillion solar mass black hole. Until recently it was thought that the interstellar gas within the central few hundred parsecs of the Galaxy consisted of three major components: an ultra high temperature X-ray-emitting plasma; ionized gas at T~10^4K responsible for the well-studied fine structure and radio recombination line emission; and cool and dense molecular clouds, which have also been observed in great detail at radio wavelengths. However, our infrared spectroscopy of H3+ and CO, and in particular of a key absorption line from a metastable state of that H3+ (Goto et al 2002, Oka et al. 2005), has clearly revealed the presence of a fourth component, which in terms of density (50-200 cm-3) has the characteristics of Galactic diffuse cloud material, but which is considerably warmer (200-300 K). This warm and diffuse environment appears to be unique to the Galactic center; it has not been found in any other Galactic clouds surveyed in H3+ to date.
Spectroscopy of H3+ is difficult because its lines are weak owing to its low abundance. Until recently we have had available as probes of the line of sight to the Galactic center only a small number of luminous sources in the central cluster and out to about 30 pc, which are both sufficiently bright for high resolution spectroscopy and have smooth infrared spectra so the H3+ line profiles are uncontaminated. However, to truly evaluate the extent and physical nature of this new type of environment, sightlines covering a wider spatial extent of the GC are needed. It is therefore essential to find additional bright sources with featureless (or nearly featureless) spectra - either hot stars or stars encased in dense shells of warm dust - in a more extended region of the Galactic center.

An oversimplified description of the technique is that the shorter wavelength IR colors are mainly used to weed out foreground (low extinction) sources and "normal" red giants, and the longer wavelength IR colors are mainly used to identify emission from dust shells. Including calibrations, acquisitions, and overheads, this corresponds to 1 hour per object, or a total request of 12 HOURS OF GEMINI-NORTH.
We request half the allocation from NOAO and half from Gemini-Staff and note that we can accomplish our scientific goals even with allocation from only one partner.

I. The Rise of Time-Domain Astronomy
A full characterization of the transient sky is one of the key observational frontiers in modern astronomy. It is driven by the fact that transient phenomena generally result from a rapid and violent release of energy and therefore provide a unique window into extreme physical conditions, massive star outbursts and deaths, and the diverse behavior of compact objects (white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes). In the optical regime, the study of transients has been focused for over a century on two primary classes of events - supernova explosions and nova eruptions, of which hundreds have been discovered and studied (e.g. [1,2]). One of the most striking results is that the two classes occupy narrow ranges of luminosities, with <M>~-8(+/-1) mag for novae and <M>~-18(+/-2) mag for SNe; see Figure 1.
This observational result, and the interest in classifying and studying large numbers of events (driven largely by the use of type Ia SNe as standard candles), has led to a plethora of nearby galaxy surveys and pencil-beam blind searches. The surveys are now so efficient that they recover nearly no other type of transient. Moreover, those that are focused on type Ia cosmology are highly efficient at rejecting other SN types, particularly unusual events.
Still, in recent years a combination of serendipitous discoveries (partly by amateurs) and nascent shallow wide-field searches have uncovered a few transients that reside in the broad desert between novae and SNe, as well as at luminosities that exceed normal SNe (M<-20 mag); see Figure 1 (e.g. [3-8]). There is currently intense debate about the nature of these events and their connection to the known classes (this is apparent in the various designations, such as "luminous red novae" and "SN impostors"). Most fundamentally, it is unclear if the intermediate events are eruptive or explosive [9,10], and whether the high-luminosity events result from the standard core-collapse of very massive stars or a new exotic explosion mechanism [5,11]. The identity of the progenitors, and their connection to various SN progenitors is equally shrouded in mystery [6,7].
Since existing surveys are fine-tuned to finding novae and normal SNe, progress in our understanding of the (currently) rare intermediate- and high-luminosity events requires a new approach. The most exciting prospects are provided by the now operational Panoramic Survey Telescope & Rapid Response System (Pan-STARRS), which is uniquely suited for this purpose given its unprecedented areal coverage and depth. Here we propose target-of-opportunity GMOS spectroscopy of Pan-STARRS transients in the nova-SN desert (-10 to -16 mag) and at high luminosity (<-20 mag) designed to classify and delineate their origin. We filter out novae and normal SNe since hundreds of these events are already found and studied through other surveys. Below we summarize the main types of events whose origin is controversial and that our program will begin to systematically address.
II. Intermediate-Luminosity Transients.
The triple outburst of the mundane star V838 Mon [3] established a possible new class of eruptions, with explanations ranging from the eruption of a common envelope white dwarf to planet capture. Three subsequent extragalactic events with similar luminosities have been associated with massive stars, suggesting that they represent an evolutionary stage on the path to SN explosions [4,6,7,9,10]. We recently studied the nearest of these events (NGC300 OT2008-1) and showed that its spectrum is clearly distinct from those of SNe, that it requires an energy of >10^47 erg, and that the circumstellar environment is suggestive of previous outbursts [7]. At present, it is unclear if the few known examples indeed share a common origin.
Potentially associated are "SN impostors" - several objects initially classified as SNe, which turned out to be photometrically and spectroscopically abnormal. These events likely include Luminous Blue Variable eruptions [11]. However, the most recent potential impostor (SN2008S) is nearly identical to NGC300 OT2008-1 [7], but has still been argued to be a faint SN [12] or an LBV outburst [9]. Similarly, there is an on-going debate about an emerging group of transients argued to represent extremely low-luminosity type Ia-like events, possibly as a result of deficient thermonuclear explosions [8]. An alternative explanation of core-collapse to a black hole with significant fall-back has also been proposed [14].
Although only a few intermediate-luminosity events are known, rough estimates of their intrinsic rates from current surveys are ~10-50% of the SN rate [7,8,10].
III. High-Luminosity Transients.
Most type Ia SNe peak at -19 mag with little dispersion (Figure 1). This has been attributed to a scenario in which a white dwarf accretes material from a companion until it nears the Chandrasekhar mass, thereby creating a standard luminosity explosion (the single-degenerate scenario). However, type Ia SNe may also result from the merger of two white dwarfs (the double-degenerate scenario). In this case the combined mass may be super-Chandrasekhar, leading to a more luminous explosion. The best potential example to date is SNLS-03D3bb, which peaked at -20 mag and generated about 1.3 solar masses of nickel-56 [13]. Finding events with a nickel mass in excess of the Chandrasekhar mass (~1.4 M_sun) will confirm the double-degenerate scenario.
Even more luminous events have been found, approaching -23 mag and requiring kinetic energies >10^52 erg (e.g. [5,14,15]). Spectroscopically, the few known events appear diverse, but they bear some similarity to "naked" core-collapse SNe of types IIn and Ib/c (objects whose massive progenitors lost most of their hydrogen and helium envelope before exploding). This possible connection, and the role of mass or binarity in producing the extreme luminosities, remain hotly debated [14,15]. Spectroscopy provides a clear test since naked SNe are powered by interaction of the blastwave with the ejected envelope, and are thus dominated by H and He lines from photoionized and/or shock-accelerated circumstellar material. These optical features will allow us to measure the mass loss history and composition of the envelope, direct clues to the nature of the progenitors.
The high-luminosity events are rare, representing only a few percent of the SN rate, but at the Pan-STARRS depth they can be found to z~1.

Pan-STARRS is a 1.8-m survey telescope with a 7 deg^2 camera. It provides the first deep optical all-sky time-domain survey, using two primary modes: the 3pi and the medium-deep surveys (MDS). The former covers 3pi steradians with a cadence of weeks to months, and a depth of 22.5 AB mag per image. The MDS consists of 10 fields (each 7 deg^2) uniformly spread in RA and ranging in declination from -30 to +60 deg. It has a much faster cadence of 4 days (cycling between the grizy filters), and reaches a depth of 23.5 AB mag. Six MDS fields are observed at any time, accounting for 25% of the survey. Pan-STARRS is now in regular operations and we have already found and classified events using our 2009B Gemini program (e.g. Narayan et al. ATEL 2214).
Our Harvard/CfA group is a member of the Pan-STARRS consortium and therefore has access to all proprietary Pan-STARRS data. This is essential for host galaxy identifications/redshifts, and for tracing the evolution/colors of transients (see below).
For this proposal, which requires a robust rejection of novae, normal SNe, and variable AGN, a high cadence of observations is essential. This will also allow exotic intermediate- and high-luminosity events to be found within days of occurrence, providing a full characterization of their behavior. Therefore, we focus only on the MDS events; the 3pi survey will include similar events, but the much higher contamination rate will be extremely wasteful of Gemini time.
To estimate the expected event rates we use as a baseline the Pan-STARRS project estimated MDS discovery rate of about 350 type Ia SNe and 65 core-collapse SNe per month at <22.5 mag (well-matched to our signal-to-noise needs for GMOS; see below). Accounting for the smaller volume accessible for intermediate-luminosity events, we find an expected rate of ~10 per month. The intrinsic rate of these events is not well known due to the small number of events to date, but it is roughly 10-50% of the SN rate. Thus, Pan-STARRS will find about 2 intermediate-luminosity events per month. Similarly, taking into account the volume for the high-luminosity events, and an intrinsic fraction of a few percent of the SN rate, we find an expected rate of ~2 per month. Our total rate is therefore ~4 events per month, of which half can be accessed at each Gemini telescope (to spread the load between Gemini-N and Gemini-S).
To separate out the events of interest we need to impose a strict set of criteria to eliminate novae, normal SNe, and AGN variability (as well as Galactic foreground). The decision tree leading from Pan-STARRS transient discovery to triggering of a Gemini spectrum is shown in Figure 2. First, we require a non-detection within 4 days prior to discovery (equal to the MDS cadence to ensure a young age). Second, to remove AGN we require events to brighten by >0.5 mag at discovery (AGN rarely vary by >0.5 mag in <4 days), and we also impose an astrometric offset of >5-sigma from the host galaxy nucleus. At the signal-to-noise ratio corresponding to <22.5 mag and the typical Pan-STARRS FWHM (~1 arcsec), this corresponds to about 1.5 pixels (0.256 arcsec/pixel). From our experience with ESSENCE this was sufficient to separate SNe from AGN. Clearly, this cut will result in the loss of real events, but at the expected redshifts typical galaxies have radii >2 arcsec, leading to a minor event loss of <5%. Finally, as the MDS data accumulate we will eliminate AGN based on long-term variability.
Next, we cut on the intrinsic luminosity (-10 to -16 mag for intermediate-luminosity and <-20 mag for high-luminosity). This requires coincidence with a galaxy, which will also eliminate Galactic foreground events. The luminosity will be inferred from existing galaxy redshifts (many of the MDS fields include large redshift surveys such as SDSS) or from photometric redshifts based on the Pan-STARRS data. Robust photo-z values will be available at z<0.5, sufficient for our targets. To remove dust-extincted normal SNe we also use a cut on the colors. For our luminosity cut, an extinction of A_V>2 mag is required to move normal SNe into our selection window (g-r>0.7 mag and r-i>0.4 mag for the Galactic extinction curve). Using the intrinsic colors of SNe at z<0.1 (the distance limit for our intermediate-luminosity events) we find that cuts of g-r<0.4 mag and r-i<0.3 mag will eliminate reddened normal SNe. Finally, we use an apparent magnitude range of 18-22 mag (brighter events can be observed with smaller telescopes).
We stress that the rates and efficacy of the cuts are estimated from existing knowledge. As expected for a new parameter space, some contamination and a revision in rates will occur. Our selection criteria at present are conservative, as appropriate for the first round of Pan-STARRS follow-up observations.
For the Gemini observations we request "Standard TOO triggers" (activation of >1 day) with GMOS. In practice, the delay can be several days given the modest evolution of these events near peak, thereby reducing the stress on Gemini operations. The primary purpose of our proposed observations is to classify the events and determine their properties (velocities, chemical composition, environment); see Figure 3. Clearly, the various types of events can be cleanly separated and studied spectroscopically. Each trigger will be a single spectrum designed to achieve S/N>1 per resolution element (R<22mag), and cover about 5000-9000A (e.g. SiII, H-beta, H-alpha, HeI, [CaII]). The spectral features are broad (>10^3 km/s; Figure 3), so the spectra can be further binned in post-processing to achieve higher S/N. Using the GMOS ITC we find that for the R400 grating this requires an exposure time of 2400 sec with 2x2 binning, a 1" slit, and observing conditions of 80%-ile (appropriate for slow TOOs). Including calibrations, acquisitions, and overheads, this corresponds to 1 hour per object, or a total request of 12 HOURS OF GEMINI-NORTH.
We request half the allocation from NOAO and half from Gemini-Staff and note that we can accomplish our scientific goals even with allocation from only one partner.

INTRODUCTION
A decade of primarily space-based observations of bright nearby early-type galaxies has revealed the ubiquitous presence of massive dark objects in their nuclei. Detailed dynamical studies showed that the gravitational influence such objects exert on the surrounding matter is consistent with the presence of supermassive black holes (SMBHs). Striking relations have been found between the mass of SMBHs (Mbh) and different properties of their host galaxies, such as the bulge luminosity (Kormendy&Richstone 1995,ARA&A,35,581), mass (Magorrian et al. 1998,AJ,115,2285), stellar velocity dispersion sig_* (Ferrarese&Merritt 2000,ApJ,539,9; Gebhardt et al. 2000,ApJ,539,13), the degree of light concentration (Graham et al. 2002,ApJ,563,11) and mass deficit in galaxies with core light profiles (Kormendy&Bender,2009,ApJ,691,142). The importance of these relations is that they connect two quantities on vastly different scales, namely the SMBH on 10^(-5) pc scales, with the bulge potential on 1 kpc scales, suggesting a strong link between the formation and evolution of SMBH and their hosts. These relations therefore provide a powerful constraint on models of galaxy assembly (e.g. Haehnelt&Kauffmann 2000,MNRAS,318,35; Bower et al. 2006,MNRAS,370,645).
OBSERVATIONAL BIAS:
A key recent realisation is that the observed Mbh-bulge relations are derived from a biased galaxy sample, and therefore are not representative of the entire galaxy population (Bernardi et al. 2007,ApJ,660,276; Lauer et al. 2007,ApJ,670,249). The measured Mbh reside in a collection of ~50 nearby galaxies (Gultekin et al.2009ApJ,698,198), strongly biased to cuspy light profiles and in a very restricted mass range (luminosity or sig_* selected), a consequence of being mostly measured by the 2.4m Hubble Space Telescope. Neither the shape, tightness nor the universality of the Mbh-Bulge relationships are yet established (e.g. Wyithe 2006,MNRAS,365,1082; Novak et al. 2006,ApJ,637,96). Specifically, crucially important for the shape and slope of the relation, the low-mass end remains underpopulated, uncertain and poorly constrained. However, the assumed empirical single power-law of Mbh-bulge relationships is considered universal across all mass regimes and widely used to constrain the theoretical models of galaxy evolution.
ATLAS3D SURVEY
We have completed the observations of the volume-limited Atlas3D survey (http://www-astro.physics.ox.ac.uk/atlas3d/), observing all early-type galaxies down to K=-21.3 with the SAURON-IFS visible from the William Herschel Telescope (WHT). This unique survey provides, among other products, spatially-resolved maps of stellar kinematics. These maps enable robust measurements of luminosity weighted velocity dispersion within 1 Re (sigma_e) for, essentially, all early-type galaxies within the local 40Mpc. The observed sigma_e is a formal approximation to the second velocity moment, and is a superior estimator of the host galaxy mass than the typically-used sigma_* derived from a long-slit, providing a robust quantity for comparing with models or other observations (see Technical Justification).
NIFS LGS ON GEMINI NORTH
A combination of our extensive experience with NIFS and the fact that all Atlas3D galaxies can be observed from Gemini North, makes this facility unique for exploiting the unprecedented Atlas3D data set. Figs1,2,3 present our results on four galaxies observed in springs of 2008 and 2009, based likely on the highest-quality data available for this work to date. They confirm the feasibility of nuclear guiding and the so-called 'open loop' focus model technique (http://www.gemini.edu/sciops/instruments/altair/use-with-lgs#NoSFO), and show our ability to measure PSF of the LGS observations (Fig.1).
It is often assumed that to determine Mbh the observations need to be on spatial scales of R=(GMbh)/sig_e^2. Thanks to the unprecedented amount of kinematic information provided by high quality IFS data (such as those proposed here), the extended influence of the SMBH can be measured and constrained, even when the PSF is a few times larger than R (Technical Justifications and Fig.2a). In that respect, the availability of the laser-guide star (LGS) facility coupled with NIFS on Gemini North, provides a solution to extend the scaling relations to lower-mass galaxies than previously accessible to stellar-dynamics-based methods.
The high-spatial resolution of the NIFS LGS-AO data enable us to determine the nuclear orbital structure and test scenarios of SMBH formation. One prediction is that tangentially biased orbits should occur in the nuclei of core galaxies as a consequence of dry mergers and formation of BH-binaries which eject stars that cross their path (e.g. Milosavljevic&Merritt2001,ApJ,563,34). In Fig.2b, we show that this is the case (NGC524), but surprisingly also that galaxies with cuspy light profiles (NGC2549), which could have been created in a variety of formation processes, have also a tendency for mildly tangentially isotropic orbits.
We have the expertise to reduce the data and extract reliable kinematics (Fig.3) including the higher order Gauss-Hermite moments (important constraints of dynamical models). We are also able to combine the high-resolution NIFS data and large-scale kinematics from the Atlas3D Project, construct state-of-art dynamical models, determine orbital structure and robustly measure masses of SMBHs. We are fully in position to apply our end-to-end machinery to deal with a large sample efficiently.
STATUS OF PREVIOUS GEMINI PROGRAMS
We have so far obtained NIFS-LGS observations for four objects, obtained in 2008A (2007B roll-over) and 2009A. Our band-2 ranking proposals have fallen foul of poor winter weather which has hampered LGS completion rates in particular for 08B. For 2009A only 2 of 5 galaxies were completed. The data of 2008A, however, were published in the very first paper using LGS for Mbh determination (Krajnovic et al. 2009,MNRAS.tmp.1306), which shows the feasibility and power of the proposed observations and the capability of our group to successfully constrain SMBH masses and test their formation scenarios. The recent 2009A data are now fully reduced (Fig.3) and are being analysed. NIFS and LGS at Gemini offer a unique opportunity to make a significant contribution to the understanding of the physical processes responsible for the interplay between the SMBH and host galaxies.
OBJECTIVE
Combining the available large-scale kinematics of Atlas3D sample with high-resolution NIFS observations, focusing here on the low-mass end of Mbh-sigma_e relation, we aim to substantially improve the accuracy of the local SMBH scaling relationships, to understand the SMBH demography, nuclear orbital structure and constrain the SMBH formation scenarios.
We propose to continue our project (GN-2008A-Q-21,GN-2008B-Q-62,GN-2009A-Q-54,GN-2009B-Q-54) and observe 4 suitable galaxies observable in this semester. We ask in total 38h evenly split between GEMINI Staff and UK contributions for semester 2009B.

OPTIMAL OBSERVATION TECHNIQUE
LGS observations still require a natural guide star (NGS) to correct for tip-tilt motions and focus variations caused by changes in the sodium layer height and/or thickness. Unfortunately, even though these stars can be fainter than for non-LGS AO, such stars are rarely found near most local early-type galaxies. Galaxy nuclei are extended, and often only suitable for tip-tilt correction, leaving the focus unconstrained, undermining the AO performance. With assistance from GEMINI staff, we have pioneered a novel procedure to observe these objects with LGS-AO. The first step is to tune the full LGS-AO system on a sufficiently bright nearby star. The loops are then opened, and the object is acquired. The observations commence while the correction is made using only the LGS and tip-tilt (from the galaxy). The focus loop is left 'open', but adapts to the gradual change of airmass via a system model. After about 1h of object-sky-object observations, the focus star is re-observed, also with the focus loop open, in order to monitor the degradation of the AO correction. The AO system can be re-optimized at this stage for further observations (Krajnovic et al.2009).
The above procedure, however, cannot be used to determine the actual PSF of the science observation. For that purpose we developed a method which compares an HST image with the reconstructed image of NIFS observations. Fig.1 shows that it is possible to determine the PSF by convolving the HST image with a double Gaussian. In both cases the resulting PSF has narrow components with expected correction for LGS AO of 0".1-0".2, while the broad component depends somewhat on the steepness of the light profiles: steeper profiles usually found in low mass galaxies yield a better correction. In both cases, however, within 0."2 there is between 40% to 60% of the PSF flux and in that respect enables further analysis and the construction of dynamical models to determine the Mbhs. Preliminary analysis for new data show even better corrections of ~0."1.
AO INTEGRAL-FIELD KINEMATICS
Until recently, the high-resolution data for measuring Mbhs could only be obtained with space-based or AO assisted long-slits and typically along only one position angle (e.g. HST/STIS in Gebhardt et al. 2003,ApJ,583,92). However, we have shown (Cappellari & McDermid 2005,Class.&Quant.Grav.,22,S347) that single-slit kinematics are grossly insufficient to constrain the underlying orbital structure, even imposing the constraint of axisymmetry, but that these limitations can be overcome using IFS data and that the stellar distribution function can be accurately recovered in the axisymmetric geometry (Krajnovic et al. 2005,MNRAS,357,1113) using our stellar dynamical modelling (Cappellari et al. 2006,MNRAS,366,1126).
Furthermore, although most studies focus on Mbh only, our own tests have shown that an accurate sigma_e is equally important to define the slope and scatter of the Mbh-sigma relation. Our aim is to substitute the heterogeneous determination of sig_* with robust and theoretically motivated sigma_e. In this respect, IFS data of Atlas3D form an ideal parent catalogue providing sigma_e for almost all nearby early-type objects relevant for SMBH studies.
In Fig.2a we demonstrate that in addition to constraining the global orbital structure with large-scale IFS data, they are important for the measurement of Mbh. If only NIFS data are used there is a clear evidence for a degeneracy between mass-to-light ratio (M/L) and Mbh, due to the small spatial coverage of NIFS observations. Only the combination with the large scale kinematics (Atlas3D data) can constrain the Mbhs and M/L robustly, reflecting the need to establish the importance of stars on radial orbits, which may pass close to the SMBH whilst spending most of their time at much larger radii (Shapiro et al. 2006,MNRAS,370,559). Moreover, this example shows our ability to determine the Mbh in a case where R < FWHM_psf at 3 sigma confidence level. The implications are clear: to accurately measure the central orbital structure and gravitational potential in galaxy nuclei requires integral-field kinematics on both small (~10pc) and large (~1kpc) scales.
SAMPLE: Atlas3D+NIFS
We propose to observe 4 galaxies which fall in the underpopulated region of the Mbh-sigma diagram (sigma_e<130km/s), have R> 0".05, have HST imaging and do not show obvious non-axisymmetric features (bars,warps). We verified that these galaxies meet the 1.5 magnitude drop within 1" recommendation for tip/tilt guiding with Altair, which is actually typical for galaxies with these low velocity dispersions.
CONFIGURATION
The proposed NIFS+LGS observations will measure the LOSVD in the galaxy over the nuclear region. We propose to observe both targets with one central field (3"x3" with 0".103x0".042 pixels), complementing the large scale SAURON observations. The NIFS observations will be in K and in order to achieve the highest possible Strehl ratio, and will use the strong CO bandhead at 2.2 microns as tracers of the stellar kinematics.
EXPOSURE TIME
To compute the exposure times we used the 2MASS image to derive the central K-band surface brightness. The central surface brightness of our galaxies ranges between 13.2 and 14.3 mag/arcsec^2. We will achieve signal-to-noise of at least 40 at 2.3microns by observing the brightest galaxy for 3h, 2 galaxies for 5h and the dimmest galaxy for 6h on source. These values were obtained using the NIFS integration time calculator (ITC), by selecting extended source with uniform surface brightness (in K band). We also used typical observing conditions for AO+LGS in NIR and we binned the NIFS elements by 1x2 resulting with final spaxels of 0.103"x0.084", still sampling the LGS PSF adequately.
To increase efficiency, we will use an object-sky-object sequence which allows adequate sky subtraction accuracy. From our experience 50% overheads are typical for NIFS LGS observations using the open-loop model, and we therefore request in total 38h, evenly split between the UK (19 hours) and Gemini Staff (19 hours) partners.
DATA REDUCTION AND ANALYSIS:
We have experience with large scale projects, integral-field data, AO-assisted near-IR observations, and with the construction of dynamical models (please see list of publications). We will extract the kinematics from the spectra using our penalised pixel-fitting technique (Cappellari&Emsellem 2004,PASP,116,138). We will construct dynamical models for the extracted stellar kinematics using our standard machinery, which consists of an axisymmetric Schwarzschild orbital-superposition method (e.g.Rix, et al. 1997,ApJ,488,702) optimized for 2D-binned integral-field data (Krajnovic et al. 2005; Cappellari et al. 2006,MNRAS,366,1126).

SUMMARY: We propose to use NIFS with adaptive optics to answer one of the most fundamental questions in galaxy formation: Does the high-redshift star formation in forming galaxies occur in turbulent disks?
BACKGROUND: Our knowledge of high-redshift galaxy assembly is being revolutionized by the recent availability of AO-fed Integral-Field Spectrographs (IFS) on large telescopes. These offer the resolution to probe sub-kpc scale kinematic structures of star-forming galaxies at z>1.5 during the epoch of peak mass assembly. Lambda-dominated Cold Dark Matter (LCDM) models for galaxy assembly have typically modeled the majority of star formation in the Universe as taking place in rotating disks embedded in dark matter haloes. This is certainly the case in the local Universe, but as we will describe below, high-redshift observations at this point are divided, and even the models themselves suggest that disks at high redshift may not resemble those seen locally e.g. LCDM models have long had an important 'Angular-Momentum Problem' (Sommer-Larsen & Dolgov 2001, ApJ, 551, 608) that makes model disks too small compared to the local Tully-Fisher relation. This problem is typically solved by adding feedback (e.g. supernova heating), but whether this works (and the exact nature of the feedback) is the hotly-debated subject of many papers and hydrodynamical simulations (e.g., Dutton 2009, MNRAS, 396, 121).
WHAT OBSERVATIONS ARE NEEDED? Integral-field spectroscopy is crucial for understanding the formation of massive disks, since slit spectroscopy has given contradictory results as kinematic and morphological axes are not necessarily correlated (Erb et al. 2006 ApJ 646 107) . Even at intermediate redshift (z~0.6), it has been demonstrated that galaxies are already kinematically complex and that 3D IFS spectroscopy is essential to physical understanding and kinematic modeling (Rix et al., 1997, MNRAS, 285, 779; Flores et al. 2006, A&A, 455, 107). To date, the IFS march to high redshift has been led by VLT (SINFONI, Forster-Schreiber et al. 2009, arXiv:0903.1872) and Keck (OSIRIS, Law et al. 2009, ApJ, 697, 2057) with allocations of order 200-300 hours being invested on each telescope.
THE RUB:At present, the state-of-the-art IFS data obtained by Keck and VLT have resulted in contradictory findings. The Keck team targeted 13 z=2-3 UV-selected galaxies using Laser Guide Star (LGS) AO to obtain sub-kpc resolution (1 kpc ~ 0.1" at z > 2.0). While all objects show high intrinsic velocity dispersions (~ 60 - 100 km/s, a factor ~ 10 higher than typically found in z=0 disks) throughout the galaxy, very few showed evidence of significant rotational gradients about a preferred kinematic axis. In contrast, the VLT group (the SINS survey) assembled a very large sample of 63 galaxies (a mixture of UV, sub-mm, and K-band selection) and found similarly high velocity dispersions but a greater incidence of rotation (especially towards higher-mass K-selected galaxies). This suggests one possible explanation in which gas is first accreted at high rates via cold flows along cosmic filaments, and underlying rotational structures are masked by dynamical instabilities within these extremely gas-rich systems (e.g. Bournaud et al. 2007, ApJ, 670, 237). However, an equally possible explanation is that the kinematic results of the two surveys simply reflect their respective observational limitations. The OSIRIS data have severely restrictive surface-brightness limits (due to a combination of short integration times and low instrumental throughput; see Fig.1), and detect flux out to much smaller radii than SINFONI. In turn, the overwhelming majority of the SINFONI sample was obtained without AO (i.e., at natural-seeing resolution, ~0.7"=7 kpc) because of limitations of the VLT LGS system, and are thus unable to conclusively constrain the kpc-scale structure of the bright central regions. It is therefore possible that the 'typical' galaxy consists of a dispersion-dominated core ~4-5 kpc in size surrounded by a low surface-brightness region of star formation in which rotational signatures are more evident, and the OSIRIS and SINS surveys have simply been observing two different regions of the same beast.
THIS PROPOSAL: Our team has been observing z~1.5 star-forming galaxies with NIFS+LGS-AO. These are K-band selected from the Gemini Deep Deep Survey (GDDS, Abraham et al. 2004). Our initial aims were to target a fairer sample than Keck and VLT, and also to investigate NIFS performance. We were impeded by setting-accuracy issues with the Field Steering Mirror that is vital for accurate blind offsetting on to faint targets. With our assistance, this has been definitively fixed in August 2009. Our team then committed all remaining time to a single 10-hour observation on one GDDS target (GDDS SA22-2172).
The data quality is by far the best obtained on any high-redshift target. Furthermore, we also obtained OSIRIS IFS data on the same object, allowing a DIRECT comparison to be made (Fig.1). This comparison shows that (i) NIFS has twice the throughput, and (ii) NIFS has significantly better detector performance and noise properties.
WHAT HAVE WE LEARNED? GDDS-SA22-2172 is tantalizingly suggestive of a possible resolution to the conflicting picture being painted by Keck and VLT observations. The core of this galaxy shows a kpc-resolution dispersion-dominated region of star-formation with no sign of a velocity gradient, very similar to the OSIRIS results for this object. However, when spatially smoothed (0.2-0.5 arcsec FWHM) our NIFS data (Fig.2) show a large-scale velocity shear at low surface brightness, suggestive of a rotating disk and generally similar to the VLT results. Is it possible that all these objects fall into the same class, and the differences claimed are due to instrumental effects? Or is it due to a difference in redshift? (z=1.5 vs z>2).
We propose to observe a benchmark set of 8 galaxies with NIFS, similar to the OSIRIS and SINFONI samples. Unlike OSIRIS on Keck, NIFS offers superior low-surface-brightness sensitivity. Unlike SINFONI, NIFS allows us to use AO resolution for this sample. We focus on a set of high-redshift 'dispersion-dominated' galaxies. Our central aim is to test whether using the greater NIFS sensitivity allows us to uncover hidden rotation at low-surface-brightness levels, as it did for our GDDS target.

We plan to measure the internal dynamics of distant galaxies from redshifted Halpha spectroscopy in the H and K bands using NIFS+ALTAIR-LGS. The ~60 km/s spectral resolution of NIFS is ideal to measure galaxy rotational velocities (~+/-100 km/s) and velocity dispersions (~100 km/s). The 0.10x0.04 arcsec pixels suit the clump sizes encountered (~0.1-0.2 arcsec diameter), while the field size of 3.0x3.0 arcsec allows in-field nodding of ~1.0x1.0 arcsec galaxies for accurate sky subtraction while maximizing on-source exposure time.
For galaxies with complex Halpha morphologies exposure times are best set by practical experience. The total Halpha emission-line fluxes are faint, typically ~ 5e-17 erg/s/cm2, and we aim to reach low surface brightness structures in the outer parts of these galaxies while still resolving compact features. We therefore require 10 hr total exposure time per galaxy. Our recent NIFS+ALTAIR-LGS H-band observation of this duration on the Gemini Deep Deep Survey galaxy, GDDS-12-2127, reached an Halpha 3-sigma limit of ~ 2 e-17 erg/s/cm2/arcsec2. After light smoothing, this revealed velocity shear in the outer parts of the galaxy (Fig. 2). We plan to obtain similar observations for our other targets.
The observations will be performed in sequences of 900 s exposures in the "Faint Object Spectroscopy" mode. This maximum is set by the detected cosmic ray flux. The object is nodded between the upper and lower halves of the field of view in an ABBA pattern to permit sky subtraction. A small dither pattern is imposed on this basic theme to cancel coherent noise structure. Hence, the "B" exposures are median-combined to form the sky frame for each "A" exposure, and vice-versa for the "B' exposures. The sky-subtracted cubes are then spatially registered using the blind offsets in the file header and median-combined to form the final datacube. The ALTAIR Field Steering Mirror is the fundamental position reference for this blind offsetting. Recent improvements in its probe mapping and our recent data have given us confidence that it now performs these blind offsets reliably.
The observations are broken up into multiple "visits" with 1.5 hr on-source exposure per visit to aid queue scheduling. This necessitates reacquisition and recalibration at each visit and fewer visits are preferred.
The galaxies will be acquired in the 3.0" x 3.0" NIFS field by centering a brighter reference star in the NIFS field and then performing a blind offset of the telescope to the galaxy position. We will not see the target in either a dispersed NIFS data cube or in undispersed images obtained with the acquisition mirror in place.
Arcs and telluric standard star exposures accompany each 1.5-hr on-source exposure set. Telluric correction does not need to be precise at the signal-to-noise levels we are expecting. The standard stars will be selected from A0V spectral type stars in the Hipparcos catalog located 1 hr east and west of the target galaxy so that the standard star measurement is done at the mean zenith distance of the corresponding galaxy observations. The JHK magnitudes for these stars taken from the 2MASS catalog will provide our flux calibration.
The usual set of daytime calibrations (arcs, lamp on/lamp off flats, calibration mask, and darks) will be required to complete the reduction.
Tip-tilt guide star availability limits object selection. We have searched the Gemini Deep Deep Survey, DEEP-2 survey, and the target lists of Law et al. (2009, ApJ, 697, 2057), Wright et al. (2009, ApJ, 699, 421), Forster-Schreiber et al. (2009, arXiv:0903.1872), and Erb et al. (2006, ApJ, 647, 128) for high-redshift galaxies with R<17.5 mag guide stars within 25 arcsec of the galaxy. We reject objects for which Halpha is closer than 150 km/s to an airglow emission line, and for which our estimate of the total Halpha flux (obtained directly from published slit or inferred from [O II] 3727 optical spectra) is < 4e-17 erg/s/cm2. This resulted in a sample of 8 targets; 3 at z~1.5 with Halpha in the H band, and 5 at z~2 with Halpha in the K-band. 2 targets are K-selected and the rest are UV-selected. These cover a range of stellar mass and redshift.
We have requested standard ALTAIR LGS observing conditions. We have modified this to BG=50% conditions for our faintest tip-tilt guide star objects.
With overheads, we require ~ 11 hr per target, so a total allocation of 88 hr to complete these observations. Depth is the key to transforming this science question so if we were awarded a reduced allocation we would do fewer targets at the same depth. 8 targets is a minimum required to explore the dependence of kinematics on mass and redshift, a smaller sample would result in more limited tests of 'dispersion dominance' vs 'rotation' in only 2-3 key objects.

The vast majority of currently known active galactic nuclei (AGN) in the local Universe reside in host galaxies with prominent bulges (e.g. Heckman 1980; Ho et al. 1997). This result, together with the finding that the black hole mass and the host galaxy stellar velocity dispersion (Gebhardt et al. 2000;Ferrarese & Merritt 2000) are strongly correlated, has led to the general consensus that black hole formation and growth is fundamentally connected to the build-up of galaxy bulges. However, an important outstanding question remains unresolved: *Is a bulge in general necessary for a black hole to form and grow?*If not, how are the black hole properties related to the properties of the host galaxy in the complete absence of a bulge? This is an important question since it impacts our understanding of the origin, efficiency of formation, and mass scale of black hole seeds.
Until recently, the only known case of a truly bulgeless disk galaxy (Hubble type Sd) with an accreting black hole was the well-studied galaxy NGC 4395, which displays a classical Seyfert 1 optical spectrum (Filippenko & Ho 2003). In a recent Spitzer study (Satyapal et al. 2009), we discovered signatures of accretion activity in the nearby (d=16.8 Mpc) bulgeless disk galaxy NGC 4178 which is optically classified as a normal galaxy but has been recently discovered by Spitzer to show prominent high ionization [NeV] emission thus far exclusively associated in extragalactic sources with AGNs (Fig. 1). Our analysis of archival VLA observations shows a tentative detection of a nuclear radio point source, also consistent with an AGN (Fig. 3). If the AGN is confirmed in this object, NGC 4178 will be an exceptional source, since it will be one of only 3 known completely bulgeless disk (Hubble type Sd) galaxies with a supermassive black hole. The bolometric luminosity of NGC 4178 inferred from our Spitzer observations is almost two orders of magnitude greater than the luminosity of NGC 4395. If confirmed, NGC 4178 will be the most luminous AGN known in a purely bulgeless disk galaxy. Based on HST NICMOS H-band imaging, it contains a prominent nuclear star cluster (NSC;Boeker et al. 1999; Fig 2.), providing us the unique opportunity to study the connection between nuclear star clusters and black holes in the absence of any bulge.
While the detection of a [NeV] line strongly suggests that NGC 4178 harbors an AGN, [NeV] emission can in principle also originate in shock-heated gas produced by starburst-driven winds. Moreover, the large aperture size of the Spitzer IRS slit (4.7"x11.3" at 14 microns) precludes us from confirming the nuclear origin of the [NeV] emission. Indeed, as can be seen from Figure 1, the Spitzer slit encompasses a significant portion of the galaxy which can contain multiple star forming regions in addition to the putative AGN. High spatial resolution spectroscopic observations are critical to confirm the AGN and to constrain its location, which is necessary to determine whether or not it resides in the NSC.
This Proposal: We propose to observe NGC 4178 using the GMOS-N IFU. We note that this galaxy was classifed as an "HII" galaxy in the Palomar Survey (Ho et al. 1997). However, the original optical spectrum was not centered at the location of the putative NSC and moreover was obtained from a 2"x4" aperture. It is very likely that emission in larger apertures is dominated by star formation, hiding the AGN. Indeed, a recent Keck high resolution optical spectrum of NGC 3621 (Barth et al. 2009), one of the other pure disk galaxies showing evidence for an AGN by Spitzer (Satyapal et al. 2007) does show a low power Seyfert which becomes inconspicuous at larger apertures due to contamination from star formation in the host galaxy (Dale et al. 2007). The combination of good seeing attainable from Mauna Kea and the high sensitivity of GMOS will allow us to map the standard optical diagnostic line ratios in the central ~ 400x540 pc region, allowing us to search for the AGN and to constrain its location on sub-arcsecond scales. In addition, once the AGN is located, we propose follow-up observations to: 1) search for the kinematic center of the galaxy to confirm the nuclear location of the putative NSC and the AGN, and 2) model the stellar population of the NSC and study any potential connection it has with the AGN.

We intend to apply a two-step approach to detecting and characterising the putative AGN in NGC4178. The first step is to obtain detailed emission-line diagnostics (Hbeta, [OIII], [OI], Halpha [NII] and [SII]) using the central ionized gas and determine the ionisation mechanisms present. Due to the uncertain nature of the location of the AGN, the GMOS-N IFU will be used to map the galaxy centre, allowing precise locations of any sub-structure in the emission line ratios, and hopefully locating evidence for the AGN and determining its association with the nuclear star cluster. The GMOS-N IFU is the ideal instrument for this, thanks to its excellent spatial sampling (0.2") and spectral grasp (can obtain complete ionization diagnostics in a single spectrum). IFU capabilities are required due to the uncertain location of the AGN. The excellent seeing achievable from Mauna Kea, combined with the light-gathering capabilities of the Gemini telescope, uniquely allow the high-spatial resolution map of the central ionized gas to be obtained, necessary to pin-point the putative AGN. Furthermore, it is possible that we will detect broad emission lines as were recently found for the first time in the LINER galaxy M94 using the GMOS-IFU (Steiner et al 2009). The broad emission lines would provide definitive evidence of an AGN and enable estimation of the black hole mass (Greene & Ho 2005).
We will analyze the IFU data within a month of it being taken. If the AGN is detected and indeed associated with the nuclear star cluster, the second step will be to obtain deep GMOS long-slit spectroscopy centered on the AGN/cluster with a narrow slit, using high spectral resolution to measure stellar absorption lines from the nuclear cluster. This will provide a dynamical mass determination for both the cluster and possibly also the black hole. From these deep spectra, it should also be possible to trace the stellar kinematics over a significant radial range in this nearly edge-on galaxy, allowing a determination of the dynamical centre, putting further constraints on the origins of the central star cluster and possible black hole. The galaxy has quite a low surface brightness, and obtaining detailed stellar kinematics with adequate resolution to also constrain random motions (the velocity dispersion) is challenging. This requires the power of the Gemini 8m telescope, coupled to the sensitive and stable GMOS-N spectrograph and its excellent image quality.
For the GMOS IFU observations, we request 2 hours of integration with the B600 filter using the single-slit mode to image a 5x3.5" FOV at the center of NGC4178 including the nuclear star cluster. The Palomar survey observations find a total Halpha line flux in their 2"x4" slit (which is slightly offset from our IFU position) of 5e-15 ergs/sec/cm2. However this emission is likely patchy and only a fraction will fall in any given IFU pixel. Using the GMOS ITC, we find that we can detect (3-sigma) line fluxes in a single IFU element down to 1e-16 ergs/sec/cm2 in two hours, a factor of 50x lower than the Palomar Halpha line flux. The B600 grating provides sufficient resolution to resolve any broad lines, if present, and covers all the lines necessary to diagnose AGN emission. We also request an additional 10 minutes to obtain imaging during acquisition for astrometric purposes. Including acquisition and readout overheads we request 2.6 hours of time for the IFU observations. Seeing and cloud cover in the 70th percentile are adequate for the IFU data.
The goal of the long-slit observations is to measure the dispersion of the nuclear star cluster and the galaxy kinematics. The nuclear star cluster has an H band magnitude of 18.2, and thus has an expected I band magnitude of ~20.0 based on single stellar population models for an old population (a young population would be brighter). Using the R831 grating to obtain spectra of the CaT with an 0.5" slit, we find a S/N in 6 hours of ~16 per pixel under IQ 70% conditions, increasing to 25 per pixel under IQ 20% conditions. The instrumental dispersion of the observations is about 30 km/sec. We expect the cluster dispersion to be ~40 km/sec based on observations of a similar target (e.g. Barth et al 2009). We also request one hour of time to observe velocity standards with an identical observing setup. Including two acquisitions and readout overheads, we ask for 7.7 hours of time for the long-slit observations.

Super star clusters (SSCs) --- objects as compact and massive as globular clusters (GCs), but young and associated with the star-bursting regions, are thought to be progenitors of GCs. However, the apparent lack of clusters of intermediate ages has put a question mark on this possibility. Though SSCs are found in large numbers on the HST images of starburst galaxies, very few of them have well-determined spectroscopic ages. Hence, it is not yet clear whether the apparent lack is due to the absence of clusters of intermediate ages or due to the lack of accurate age measurements. The best way to understand the evolutionary connection between these two compact classes of objects is by determining spectroscopic ages for both types cluster candidates.
Galaxies that contain a statistically significant population of both the SSCs and GCs are very rare, and to our knowledge there is no detailed age determinations of both these populations in a single galaxy. In the Local Group, Milky Way and M31 are rich in GCs, but contain very few SSCs. On the other hand, starburst galaxies such as M82 and Antennae have a rich population of SSCs, but contain very few GCs (Mayya et al. 2008; Bastian et al. 2009).
The nearby galaxy M81 offers a great opportunity to address the evolutionay connection, as this galaxy contains both the SSCs and GCs in large numbers (Chandar et al. 2001). A recent search by Santiago-Cortes et al. (2009) for compact clusters using the newly available HST/ACS images have yielded more than 100 cluster candidates brighter than B=21 mag. The color-magnitude diagram of these clusters is shown in Figure 1, where we can see that both the SSCs and GCs lie in the part of the color-magnitude diagram where color is not very sensitive to age, and hence the estimated ages are degenerate with the assumed masses. Objects in each group cover a range of more than 3 magnitude in brightness, which could be due to a spread in age or mass or both. Multi-object spectroscopy is the logical first step to follow to break this degeneracy.
Age-sensitive absorption features in the optical spectrum provide the most reliable ages of integrated populations such as SSCs and GCs. Current Observations are aimed at obtaining the best possible ages of SSCs and GCs in the sample of M81 defined by Santiago-Cortes et al. (2009). Intermediate resolution spectra (resolution ~ 5 Ang) covering the 3600 to 5500 range is good enough to obtain the objectives. Given that the compact clusters in our sample have FWHM less than 0.5 arcsec, the slit width should be ideally sub-arcsec. The PI has already established the use of Gemini/GMOS spectra for carrying out the project of this kind (eg. Trancho et al 2007). The spectra will also provide us data on the metallicity and radial velocities.
Sample: Our sample contains 117 objects (43 GCs and 74 SSCs) brighter than B=21 mag. The positions of these objects on the GALEX image of M81 are shown in Figure 2. The clusters are distributed over a field of view (FoV) which is several times the FoV of the GMOS. However, with 3 pointings we can cover a good fraction of the clusters in our sample. In Figure 3, we show a part of the HST/ACS image, where the GCs and SSCs are identified. Notice that the GCs in M81 that were studied spectroscopically in the pre-HST era (eg. Brodie & Huchra 1991) are located in the halo of the galaxy and is outside the area of interest shown in Figure 2. Through this proposal, we would be doubling the number of GCs with spectroscopic data, with emphasis on the GCs in the central part of the galaxy. This is the first spectroscopic study of SSCs in M81.

We aim to use the relative strengths of selected absorption lines in the blue part of the spectrum to infer the age of the clusters. Cluster sample constitutes M81 objects with B < 21 mag. Some of these are candidates for globular clusters, while the rest are relatively younger super star clusters. Spectra with prominent Balmer lines in absorption suggest clusters of a intermediate age (around 100 Myr) and will be age dated using the method described in Konstantopoulos et al. (2009) and in Trancho et al 2007a,b, Bastian et al 2009 Rest of the clusters showing absorption lines will be age dated using the well-known Lick indices. The Lick/IDS absorption-line system has been employed to infer age and metallicity of stars and star aggregates right from the work of Worthey (1994). In that study, it was pointed out that some of the indices e.g. Fe4668, Fe5015, Fe5782 are sensitive to abundance, whereas other indices such as G4300, Hbeta are sensitive to age. The chosen indices are sensitive to cluster ages between 50 Myr to several giga years. We will use the MOS mode of GMOS along with B600 grating in order to measure the spectral indices between 3600 and 5600 A. The data will also permit us measure reliable radial velocities and metallicities.
According to the GMOS ITC a signal-to-noise of ~12.5 per pixel can be reached for a point source of V=21.0 with an exposure time of 2.0 hours (3600 sec x 2) using the following parameters: A0III spectrum, 70%-ile image quality (about 0.8"), 50%-ile cloud cover (photometric), and 80%-ile sky brightness (grey), airmass 1.5, B600 grating, 0.75" slit width, slow read mode, and binned 4x2 to critically sample the expected image quality. Higher S/N can be obtained against lower backgrounds. With this exposure time a cluster with V=20 gives S/N~27.5 per pixel at 500nm. Our data on NGC3256 and NGC4038 confirm these sensitivities and have shown that we can determine useful radial velocities from spectra of this quality. For line index analyses, the spectra of several faint clusters will have to be averaged together for comparison with brighter clusters and the nucleus. We need pre-imaging in only one filter g (2X3X100 s) in each MOS field. Assuming 75% efficiency (typical for 2008A observing) each of the two MOS fields will require about 2.5 hours. Therefore, we request 7.5 hours.

What are the factors that affect star cluster formation? While star clusters have been seen forming in many different environments, particularly in the centers of gas-rich mergers (Miller et al 1997; Whitmore et al. 1999), they do not always form in tidal debris. In a previous study of major mergers, Knierman et al. (2003) found that star clusters were forming along the tidal tails of the major merger NGC 3256, but were only confined to large concentrations at the tips of tidal tails in 3 other mergers. Other tidal tails (UGC 10214 - Tran et al. 2003; NGC 6782 - Bastian et al. 2005) were found to harbor star clusters as well, while some do not (Palma et al. ?). The birth of star clusters in the tidal tails does not seem to follow a clear evolutionary path, and appears to be much more sensitive to the physical properties of the tidal tail environment. A number of variables are likely to affect the nature of star formation in merging systems: the environment of the merging system, the stage of the merger, the mass ratio of the individual galaxies, and the gas content, size and surface brightness of the tails.
In this study we examine the effects of mass ratio of the galaxies and gas properties of the tails on star cluster formation. The peculiar spiral, NGC 2782, is the result of a merger between two disk galaxies with a mass ratio of 0.25 occurring $\sim200$ Myr ago. This merger produced two tidal tails with different properties: an HI-rich, optically faint Western tail and an Eastern tail which has a concentration of HI and CO at its base, but a gas-poor optical knot at the tip (see Figure 1; Smith 1994). Non-detection of CO at the location of HI knots in the Western tail led Braine et al. (2001) to argue that the HI is not gravitationally bound and "has presumably not had time to condense into $H_2$ and for star formation to begin." However, deep UBVR images from the 1.8m VATT reveal the the presence of blue ($B-V \sim 0.0$) clusters along both tails (Knierman et al. 2006), suggesting that they are young ($<100$ Myr) and possibly formed within the tail. In particular, there are 45 star cluster candidates in the Western tail having colors consistent with ages < 1 Gyr (Charlot et al. 1996). Even though the gas properties of the tails are different, both tails have similar star cluster populations. These results suggest that star cluster formation is a common outcome of minor mergers regardless of gas content in the tidal debris. Though, the lack of CO in the Western tail may be due to low metallicity affecting the conversion factor of CO to $H_2$.
Spectroscopy with GMOS-N will enable us to confirm the presence of star clusters in the Western tidal tail of NGC 2782 and to examine properties of these star clusters including line of sight velocities, ages, and metallicities. Using the residual line of sight velocity, we can determine the membership to interacting system. Having accurate cluster membership will allow better determination of star formation in the tidal tail. By examining spectral features sensitive to age and metallicity (e.g. Mgb, Fe5270, Fe5335, Hdelta), we measure more precise ages and metallicities than using only broad band colors. One cluster is known to have H-alpha emission associated with it from narrow band imaging (Knierman & Knezek 2006). This cluster will provide good determinations of ages and metallicities based on its emission lines. Previous work by Trancho et al. 2007a,b and Bastian et al 2009 using GMOS-N and GMOS-S spectroscopy of star clusters in the tidal debris of NGC 3256 and NGC4038 shows that determinations of star cluster membership, as well as age and metallicity information are easily obtained. The age and metallicity measurements will also give insight into this particular mode of star formation. If the lack of CO in the Western tail is due to low metallicity and a different conversion factor of CO to $H_2$, the star clusters will show this trend in metallicity. The metallicity measurement will also be used to determine from where the debris in the Western tail originated. Duc et al. (2000) showed that tidal dwarf galaxies in the debris of major mergers have similar metallicity to the outer regions of spiral galaxies, indicating that they formed from gas pulled from the outer regions of spiral galaxies. By comparing the metallicity of star clusters in the tail to the metallicity measured by previous observations of HII regions in the inner and outer regions of the main spiral galaxy (Knierman & Knezek 2006), we can constrain how the dwarf and spiral galaxy interacted and from where the debris originated.
By determining cluster membership, ages and metallicity for the star clusters in the Western tail of NGC 2782, we will be able to gain insight into the effects of mass and gas content for star cluster formation.
