The goals are to obtain absorption line indices (e.g. Hdelta, Hbeta, Hgamma, Mgb, Fe5270, and Fe 5335..etc) and radial velocities for globular clusters with 18< V < 23 using the MOS mode of GMOS. We will use the B600 grating in order to measure the spectral indices between 4000 and 5600 A.
According to the GMOS ITC a signal-to-noise of ~10 per pixel can be reached for a point source of V=22.0 with an exposure time of 8 hours (3600 sec x 8) using the following parameters: A0III spectrum, 70%-ile image quality (about 0.8"), 50%-ile cloud cover (photometric), and 80%-ile sky brightness (grey), airmass 1.5, B600 grating, 0.75" slit width, slow read mode, and binned 4x2 to critically sample the expected image quality. Grey sky brightness was used to simulate the effects of the galaxy background under the clusters, but the observations should be done under 50%-ile (dark) conditions because sky brightness severely reduces S/N in the blue. Higher S/N can be obtained against lower backgrounds. With this exposure time a cluster with V=23 gives S/N~6.2 per pixel at 500nm. Our data on NGC3256 and NGC4038 (Trancho et al 2007a,b and Bastian et el 2009) confirm these sensitivities and have shown that we can determine useful radial velocities from spectra of this quality. For line index analyses, the spectra of several faint clusters will have to be averaged together for comparison with brighter clusters and the nucleus. We need pre-imaging in only one filter g (2X300 s) Assuming 15 minutes efficiency per setup (typical for 2008A observing) each of the two MOS fields will require about 8 hours. Therefore, we request 18 hours.

Substellar objects, encompassing brown dwarfs (<0.075Mo) and giant planets, play a key role in a number of critical areas of astrophysics. The form of the substellar initial mass function (IMF) is central to understanding the complete picture of star and planet formation. In addition, the coolest brown dwarfs provide ideal laboratories to study processes such as non-equilibrium chemistry and vertical mixing, which must be properly constrained if they are to be incorporated into the next generation of exoplanetary model atmospheres.
Figure 1 shows monte-carlo simulations by Burgasser (2004) of the Teff distribution of field brown dwarfs for a number of alternative IMFs of power law and log-normal forms (see also Chabrier 2001). It can be seen that the distribution below 1000K is most sensitive to the underlying form of the substellar IMF, with the sub-700K region offering the most powerful diagnostic. Extending the current sample of late-T dwarfs to the low-Teff extremes will thus yield the critical measure of the substellar IMF (see Figure 1 caption for final sample size). In Burningham et al. (in prep) we present 46 new LAS T~dwarfs (the largest single contribution yet to the late T~dwarf sample), and the improved constraints on the form of the substellar IMF derived from this work suggest a declining mass function for the lowest masses, ruling out both flat and positive slopes at the > 2 sigma level. This is in contrast to results from young clusters where the IMF has typically been found to be rising.
At the same time, our detailed studies of the coolest substellar atmospheres are providing essential tests for the latest generation of model atmospheres in hitherto unexplored Teff and pressure regimes. Our program has successfully identified 85+ T dwarfs within the LAS (Burningham et al 2009, 2008; Pinfield et al 2008; Lodieu et al 2007; Warren et al 2007), 15 of which have spectral types T7.5 or later (to date 8 objects in this regime have been found by 2MASS and SDSS), whilst six are later in type than the latest T dwarfs known prior to UKIDSS. The new extremely late-type T dwarfs have necessitated the extension of the spectral sequence beyond T8 to the class T9, and have been shown to have Teff<600K (Burningham et al 2008, 2009), and in the case of ULAS J1335+1130 as cool as 500K (Leggett et al 2009). In addition, we recently discovered a rare "benchmark object", Wolf 940B, the cooler component of a T8.5+M4 binary. With age and compositional constraints (from the primary) and a robust luminosity and Teff=570+/-25K, this object is now highlighting specific shortcomings in the current generation of model atmospheres (Burningham et al 2009).
Spectroscopic study of our objects has been vital for revealing their record breaking low Teff and allowing their other properties to be constrained. Their near-infrared spectral indices lead to classification beyond T8. In particular, their J- and H-band peaks are somewhat narrower than those of T8 dwarfs, in agreement with predicted trends for Teff<700K. Also, their H-[4.49] colour (from Spitzer follow-up) is extremely red, offering a natural extension of the previously measured T-dwarf colour-Teff sequence into a new Teff regime. In addition, there appears to be a broad absorption feature on the blue side of the H-band flux peak that may be due to ammonia (see Delorme et al. 2008; Burningham et al. 2008). A proper understanding of these features and their sensitivity to atmospheric conditions will be forthcoming as (i) the T8+ population grows, (ii) our parallax programmes yield distance and robust luminosity/Teff constraints, and (iii) new "benchmark systems" provide additional anchor points to inform/improve the atmospheric models.
Our ongoing program is also providing the sample from which targets for a variety of parallel projects are drawn including studies of very low-mass binary systems (Keck AO project PI Liu); studies of metal poor T dwarfs (PhD project D Murray); mid-infrared characterisation of very cold brown dwarfs (Warm Spitzer program PI Leggett).
We base our candidate selection on synthesised colours of Deacon & Hambly (2006), and experience gained in previous semesters. Late T dwarfs are red in z-J (<3) and Y-J (~0.6-1.5); and blue in J-H and J-K (<0). We have found that the sub-600K T dwarfs found to date tend to be slightly bluer in Y-J than the warmer T dwarfs (e.g. Burningham et al. 2008, Warren et al. 2007), and models currently disagree on the colours of even cooler objects (see Figure~2). Follow-up photometry of initial candidates using WHT, UKIRT and the NTT removes contamination and we measure accurate zYJHK to prioritise candidates for spectroscopy. Our photometric programmes have so far facilitated a ~95% T-dwarf success rate for our NIRI programme.
In 2010A we expect to identify ~44 T and T8+ dwarfs in our search of ~400 sq degs of new LAS sky (using our established WSA flat-file search methods), and our follow-up of outstanding targets from 2009A. Based on our previous discovery rate, we expect 3-4 of these to be T8+ with Teff <700K.
We request 19.9 hrs for "short trigger" J band spectra, which will be used to measure spectral types via J-band spectral ratios and comparison with "standard" T-type templates (following Burgasser et al 2006; B06). These techniques provide an accuracy of +/-0.5 sub-types, sufficient to identify T8+ dwarfs and more generally determine accurate spectral types of LAS T dwarfs. We also request 13.9 hrs to obtain "long trigger" JHK spectra (with higher signal-to-noise), to study the new T8+ objects. This will allow us to assess their atmospheric properties, in particular Teff, from the width of the J-band flux peak combined with a number of flux peak ratios (e.g. K/J; Fig 7 of Warren et al. 2007). With well constrained Teff, and good signal-to-noise measurement of the H-band (and possibly additional) absorption features, our 10A programme has the capability to significantly increase the size of the new T8+ population, and the likelihood of probing still cooler populations in this new Teff regime.
(References at the end of the technical section).

Candidates
The UKIDSS survey scientist expects that 600 sq degs of new LAS sky to become available via flatfile access during 2010A (Warren priv. comm.), of which we expect 400 sq degs to have appropriate RAs for immediate observation. In previous semesters, our photometric follow-up campaign has resulted in 7.5 spectroscopic targets per 100 sq degs. In addition to this we expect to be completing follow-up of a remaining 16 candidates from semester 2009A, which we were unable to follow-up due to poor weather hampering our photometric campaign on UKIRT. We thus expect to obtain spectroscopy for ~46 targets during 2010A.
About half of these will be YJH candidates (typically H~18.8), and half will be fainter, often YJ-only detections in the LAS (typically H~19.3). Note that by the time we trigger, all these candidates will have good SNR multi-band followup photometry (from our UKIRT, WHT and NTT programmes). Using our knowledge of late-T colours (see Figure 2) we will prioritise candidates that are unusually blue in Y-J, and/or those that have confirmed late T-like J-H colour combined with very blue J-K (which could potentially be the coolest T8+ objects, according to the models). We will also search for common proper motion companions that could be prioritised via independent distance constraints. In this way we will ensure that the best candidates are sent to NIRI as soon as possible.
We request NIRI time to measure spectra of the 30 highest priority candidates, and are also applying for time on Subaru in May/June with which we aim to measuring the remaining candidates.
NIRI configuration
We will use the f/6 camera and the J-, H- and K-band grisms with a 0.75 arcsecond 6-pixel slit, to provide R=460 1.05-1.41 micron spectra. Our full spectra will comprise multiple 4 min exposures nodded up and down the slit, to allow for background variation.
The short triggers
In the first instance we trigger relatively short integrations. Based on brightness, we require 16 min or 40 min exposure times for J=H=18.8 and J=H=19.3 respectively. We bin-up by 18 pixels to obtain lower resolution (R~190) higher SNR spectra. Using the ITC (with the T8 dwarf 2M0415-0935 as an input spectrum, and assuming PWFS WFS, 85%-IQ, 70%-transparency, and any-BG/WV for an airmass=1.5) we will obtain SNR=25 (per binned element) in the J-band flux peak.
In semester 2009A the TAC queried our requirement for SNR=25 spectra. B06 demonstrate that this is the minimum SNR required for measuring spectral types accurate to ~+/-0.5 sub-types using the J band spectral ratios (B06). Figure 3 demonstrates this minimum requirement.
The long triggers
Scaling from our previous followup we expect ~3 of our 10A candidates to have Teff in the <700 K range with spectral type T8+, with possibly including a new T8+ in a common proper motion binary system. Having identified these objects from our short trigger spectra, we obtain higher signal-to-noise multi-band spectra to properly constrain properties and accurately assess spectroscopic features. We propose to measure J-, H- and K-band spectra for the three brighter T8+ objects (60 mins exposure per band), and J- and H-band spectra for one fainter T8+ objects (2hr exposure per band).
Using the ITC, we expect SNR=50 (per 18 pixel binned element) in the peak of the J- and H-bands, and SNR=30 in the peak of the K-band. These spectra will be flux calibrated with our accurate JHK photometry. We will place Teff constraints on our T8+ dwarfs by accurately measuring the shape and relative strength of the YJHK flux peaks and comparing theoretical models calibrated using benchmark late T dwarfs such as 2MASS 0415 (e.g. Warren et al 2007; Burningham et al. 2008), as well as the new T8+ benchmarks we are discovering in the LAS.
We will obtain a SNR of ~10-20 in the continuum from 1.50-1.55 microns, which will allow us to accurately measure the H-band absorption feature that may be associated with ammonia. For our brighter T8+ objects we will also obtain a SNR of ~10 from 2.00-2.05 microns, which will provide an accurate measure of the K-band flux peak shape. Inter-band flux calibration will be achieved via our accurate YJHK-band photometry.
Total request
We request time to make 30 short triggers (15 with 16min exposures, and 15 with 40min exposures). We also propose an additional 3 longer triggers (2 with 60min exposures in the J-, H- and K-bands, and 1 with 2hr exposures in the J- and H-bands) for the T8+ objects. Overheads are 15min with an estimated 10min re-acquisition every hour, and 10% of the integration time. Our short triggers will thus take 33mins and 59mins for the brighter and fainter sources respectively. Our brighter long triggers will take 253mins each (1hr each in J- H- and K-bands), and our fainter long triggers will take 329mins (2hrs each in J- and H-bands). We thus require a total of 36.9 hrs of standard ToO NIRI time.
Previous Semesters
In previous we have queued to our allocation, however not all targets have been observed due to RA distributions and weather. Such targets have been rolled onto the next semester, e.g. in 2010A,we will have high priority targets that were queued in 2009A and 2009B, that will be suitable for observation at first opportunity in 2010A.

Comets and asteroids are products of binary accretion in the protoplanetary disk of the Sun. They differ primarily in the heliocentric distance (and temperature) at which they formed. By conventional definitions, asteroids are inert rocky or metallic bodies, while comets are ice-rich objects. The vast majority of asteroids are assumed to have formed at high temperatures (500 K - 1000 K) between Mars and Jupiter where they are found today. In contrast, due to their icy composition, all comets are assumed to have originated in the frigid (<50K) outer regions of the solar system. Scientifically, then, the asteroids and comets are interesting as probes of the physical conditions in the protoplanetary disk at two distinct locations. Dynamically, the Tisserand parameter (T_J) is used to discriminate the populations. This is a constant of motion in the circular, restricted three-body (Sun, Jupiter and object) problem. Asteroids have T_J > 3, Jupiter has T_J = 3 and the comets have T_J < 3 (Kresak 1982; Kosai 1992).
Recently, we discovered objects having the dynamical properties of main-belt asteroids (T_J > 3) and the physical properties of comets, including comae and tails caused by on-going mass-loss (Figure 1). We call them "main-belt comets'' (MBCs) to highlight the fact that they have properties of both main-belt asteroids and comets. Physical evidence suggests that the MBCs are true comets in the sense that they are icy bodies in which mass loss is driven by ice sublimation induced by the heat of the Sun (e.g. activity in the best characterized MBC is recurrent and long-lived, as expected for a sublimation source).
The MBCs are of scientific interest on several levels.
First, they cannot be captured from the Kuiper belt or Oort cloud comet reservoirs given the architecture of the modern Solar system (Fernandez et al. 2002; Levison et al. 2006). Instead, they were probably formed in place, as products of accretion in the vicinity of the snow-line. In this sense, the main-belt comets constitute the third reservoir of icy bodies (after the Oort cloud and the Kuiper belt) in the Solar system. Their distribution and properties help fix the physical conditions in the protoplanetary disk only 2 to 3 AU from the Sun.
Second, the outer asteroid belt is one of the likely source regions for the Earth's ocean water and other volatiles (Morbidelli et al. 2000). Understanding the distribution of ice in the outer belt may have direct relevance for our understanding of the origin of the oceans.
Third, it has been suggested that some outer belt asteroids might have been captured in a hypothetical, unstable phase in the distant past associated with drastic planetary migration (Gomes et al. 2005). Comparisons of the MBCs with comets from the Kuiper and Oort reservoirs will help test this hypothesis observationally.
Only four MBCs are known, one from Gemini data (Hsieh & Jewitt 2006). The most recent discovery, P/2008 R1 Garradd falls in a different region of the main-belt from the other three (Figure 2). It is distinguished by its small perihelion distance (q = 1.7 AU) and dynamically unstable orbit (lifetime of 20-30Myr) that suggests recent emplacement from the outer asteroid belt (Jewitt et al. 2009). Its small perihelion suggests that increased solar insolation drives the activity. The available evidence is consistent with the hypothesis that a large fraction (potentially *all*) outer-belt asteroids are ice-rich. If so, then other asteroids displaced inwards onto eccentric, P/Garradd-like orbits should be susceptible to thermally-induced outgassing. It is this hypothesis that we propose to test.

Experimental Design:
We propose to target asteroids with P/Garradd-like orbits in search of mass-loss. The discovery of the third known MBC with Gemini in 2005 was made by employing a similar strategy of observing objects with orbits close to a previously-known MBC (133P/Elst-Pizarro). The a vs. e (semimajor axis vs. eccentricity) plane (Figure 2) shows these P/Garradd-like targets as green circles. The observational strategy is based on one that we have employed at Gemini. The scattering cross-section per unit mass of dust is much larger than the corresponding quantity for gas. Hence, the preferred diagnostic for outgassing is the presence of a dust coma or tail about the target asteroids (as in Figure 1). The measurement therefore requires fine angular resolution (to image near-nucleus dust) and large light-grasp (because the dust is faint). These characteristics make the Gemini telescopes of particular value to the science.
We will image each target asteroid using the r' filter, 1x1 binning (0.14 arcsec. pixel size) and an integration time of 2 minutes. This conveys sensitivity to coma surface brightness at the ~ 26 mag/sq arcsec level, corresponding to derived mass production rates ~0.5 kg/s. Thus, we are easily capable of detecting the activity of the weakest of the currently known MBCs, 176P, which had a tail brightness of 25.3 mag/sq arcsec. We need two consecutive integrations in order to identify the targets from their motion and to distinguish activity associated with our moving targets from faint, stationary background galaxies that might masquerade as cometary activity. The nominal slew and guider set-up time for P2 + GMOS is 6 minutes, while the CCD readout time is about 2 minutes. We will select targets near each other in the sky to further minimize the slew time, and can slew while reading out the 2nd CCD image. Therefore, we budget (integration) + (readout) + (slew and guider time) = (2 + 2) + 2 + 6 = 12 minutes per target, allowing a total of 100 targets to be imaged in our requested 20 hours. To ease scheduling concerns, we include a target list larger than our total sample size, and we have submitted this proposal separately to both Gemini North and South with targets split at a declination of -5 degrees. We ask for a total of 20 hours split across both sites, 14.8 hours in the North and 5.2 hours in the South.
In the precursor survey at Gemini (on a different asteroid sample) we detected 1 MBC in about 30 targets. Our new sample could therefore yield several new MBCs, even if the incidence of mass-loss is as low as in the earlier objects (but we expect it to be higher). This would double the population of known MBCs.
Use of Other Facilities:
The use of smaller telescopes is not feasible because of the resulting loss of sensitivity and need for longer integrations. For example, the KPNO 3.8-m would require integrations longer by a factor of 5 (in equal seeing) and by a factor ~10 given the poorer average seeing in Arizona. The corresponding observing request would be in the range 10 to 20 nights, which seems excessive.
Limited time is also available on the Magellan and MMT telescopes through NOAO. Again, we would require a disproportionate fraction of the available nights on these telescopes to reach sensitivity limits comparable to those available at Gemini.
Previous Use of Facilities Available Through NOAO:
Not applicable.

BACKGROUND: The present paradigm for nuclear activity in galaxies is that it is a phase in the evolution of the galaxy in which the supermassive black hole (hereafter SMBH) is being fed. Nevertheless, one long-standing difficulty of this scenario is the lack of observational signatures of gas inflows to the nuclear region. Most observational studies show outflows in the circumnuclear gas, in particular in the narrow-line region (hereafter NLR), usually interpreted as due to the interaction of nuclear radio jets and accretion disk winds with the insterstellar medium of the host galaxy [eg.Crenshaw et al. 2007, ApJ, 659, 250; Das et al. 2005, AJ, 130, 945].
Velocities of 40 km/s have been observed in our optical studies of inflows in ionized gas (Fathi et al. 2006, ApJ, 641L, 25; Storchi-Bergmann et al. 2007, ApJ, 670, 959). As we have pointed out in those studies, the ionized gas is probably only the "tip of the iceberg", and molecular gas is probably the main source of fuel to the SMBH. Thus, the H_2 emiting gas kinematics should be a better tracer of the inflows towards the nucleus of active galaxies. This is also supported by the large amounts of molecular gas in the inner regions of active galaxies observed in recent CO radio observations (e.g. Garcia-Burillo et al. 2003, A&A, 407, 485; 2005, A&A 441, 1011).
In the near-IR, we have been mapping the excitation and kinematics of the NLR emitting gas using GNIRS IFU and NIFS observations (Riffel et al. 2006 - MNRAS, 373, 2; Riffel et al. 2008, MNRAS, 385, 1129 & Riffel et al. 2009, MNRAS, 393, 783). The main result of these studies is that the ionized gas (traced by the [FeII]1.2570 and H recombination lines) is usually dominated by outflows, while the molecular gas (traced by H_2 emission lines in the K-band) is dominated by rotation in the galactic plane plus additional inflowing gas components. The ionized and molecular emitting gas also present distinct flux distributions, with the latter more uniformly distributed in the whole IFU field. In other recent studies (Storchi-Bergmann et al., 2009a, MNRAS, 394, 1148; Storchi-Bergmann et al. 2009b, submitted to MNRAS) the high angular and spectral resolution provided by NIFS+ALTAIR have been fundamental to clearly reveal marked differences between the H_2 kinematics and the [FeII] and Br-gamma kinematics in the galaxy NGC4151. The [FeII] and Br-gamma emitting gas is again dominated by outflows and oriented approximately along the radio axis, while the H_2 emitting gas is rotating in the plane.
Recent NIFS+ALTAIR observations of Mrk1066 confirms the above scenario (Riffel & Storchi-Bergmann 2009a,b, in preparation). The ionized gas presents an important outflowing component as observed in Fig.1, while in the H_2 kinematics we observe inflowing gas components towards the nucleus. The molecular gas seems to be accumulated in the inner region of the galaxy in a small nuclear disk with size of about 200 pc, as observed in Fig. 2.
GOALS OF THE PRESENT WORK: We propose to use the high angular and spectral resolution of NIFS+ALTAIR in order to map the gas kinematics in the [FeII]1.2570 and Pa_beta emission-lines in the J-band and in the H_2 2.1218 and Br-gamma in the K-band. We will also obtain the stellar kinematics from the fitting of the CO absorption bands around 2.3 microns using the pPXF method (Cappellari & Emsellem, 2007, PASP, 431, 465). Our goals are: 1) From fitting and slicing of the emission line profiles in velocity bins we will verify if the scenario which we have proposed is confirmed: that the H_2 maps the feeding (inflowing gas) and the other emission lines map the feedback (outflowing gas), as well as constraint the location of the emitting gas; 2) The simultaneuos observation of the stellar and gaseous kinematics will allow us to isolate and estimate inflows and outflows rates and thus quantify the energy and mass balance between feeding and feedback; 3) From the flux distributions and ratios, as well as from correlations with the kinematics of the H_2 and [FeII] emission lines we will be able to map and investigate the nature of excitation mechanisms of the emitting gas.
We have selected for these observations the nearby Seyfert galaxies Mrk766 and Mrk79 because they present radio continuum and [OIII]5007 extended emission (Nagar et al. 1999, ApJS, 120, 209; Schmitt et al. 2003, ApJS, 148, 327), which will allow us to explore the relation between the radio jet and the NLR kinematics, as well as its effect in the excitation of the near-IR lines.

NIFS + ALTAIR will be used to record J and K 2D spectra of the nuclear region of the active galaxies Mrk766 and Mrk79. The spectral regions include emission lines of [FeII], HI and H_2 as well as the stellar CO 2.3micron absorption bands, with a velocity resolution of ~ 60 km/s (< 30 km/s per spectral pixel) that will easily resolve velocity structure within the lines. A stellar velocity dispersion of 50 km/s (which we aim to be able to measure) corresponds to a Gaussian absorption-line FWHM of 117 km/s. The spatial scale along each NIFS slitlet is 0.04arcsec/pixel with the spatial resolution being set by the performance of ALTAIR. Our previous observations have shown that on average we can expect to obtain spatial resolutions of aproximately 35-50 pc for the two galaxies in this proposal. As there are no available Altair guide stars in the field of the proposed targets, we will use the nucleus of each galaxy as natural guide star for ALTAIR. Both galaxies present Seyfert 1 nuclear activity and HST images of these galaxies obtained through the filter F606W show that the optical nucleus is point-like, with high contrast over the surrounding bulge (Malkan et al. 1998, ApJS, 117, 25).
Adopting an average surface brightness in the J band of 1.8E-15 erg/s/cm2/A/arcsec2 for Mrk766 (Riffel et al. 2006, A&A, 457, 61) a S/N ratio larger than 25 (needed for our kinematic analysis) will be obtained with 1 hr integration in each band. Using the emission line fluxes quoted in Rodriguez-Ardila et al. (2004, A&A, 425, 457) we obtain a similar S/N ratio for the emission lines, which will allow us to map the emission line flux distributions and kinematics. Mrk79 has similar continuum flux and emission line equivalent widhts to those of Mrk766, thus we estimate obtaining a similar S/N ratio in the same exposure time. We therefore propose to obtain a total of 1 hr on-source integration for each band for each galaxy. We propose to obtain six 10-min on source exposures, which can be median-combined, with no SNR penalty, data processing to reject cosmic rays. Off-source sky spectra will be obtained with the same exposure time in a standard object-sky-object-object-sky-object sequence by offsetting the telescope to a sky position.
The full observing sequence for each band for each target is then: 30 min set up on the target; and 90 min on-source and sky observations for each band. The total elapsed time for each target will be 4.0 hr, thus the total time requested in the present proposal is 8.0 hr. The present proposal is a joint proposal between Brasil and Gemini Staff and we thus request 4 hrs from each TAC.
Early-type Hipparcos stars will be selected for telluric correction to be observed before/after each science target. 2MASS fluxes for these stars will provide our flux calibration. An accurate determination of the PSF will be essential in analysing the velocity dispersion data. The telluric correction stars will also provide this information.
Stellar templates are needed to measure the velocity broadening of the stellar absorption features. As for previous works (Riffel et al. 2008, MNRAS, 385, 1129; Riffel et al. 2009, MNRAS, 393, 783), we plan to use the Gemini GNIRS+NIFS library of late type stars (Winge, Riffel & Storchi-Bergmann, submitted to ApJS), thus we do not need to observe separate kinematic standard stars.

The two criteria required for a galaxy group to be classified as a fossil group (FG), i.e. a magnitude gap of 2 (or greater) between the two most luminous galaxies and extended X-ray emission consistent with a galaxy group (Jones et al. 2003), guarantee the existence of a group-size galaxy halo and that there are no L* galaxies inside the radius for orbital decay by dynamical friction.
The first-ranked galaxy in a FG is usually an elliptical that is as bright as a BCG, but has discy rather than boxy isophotes (Khosroshahi et al. 2006). This hints that the first-ranked galaxy results from the merger of late-type galaxies possibly accompanied by a burst of star formation (for a contrary view see Diaz-Gimenez et al. 2008). Simulations have shown that FGs form earlier than non-FGs (D'Onghia et al. 2005; Dariush et al. 2007; von Benda-Beckmann et al. 2008), and that the first-ranked galaxy in FGs formed later than those in non-FGs, having undergone a major merger more recently (Diaz-Gimenez et al. 2008). The X-ray contours indicate well-relaxed virialised systems (Khosroshahi et al. 2004). D'Onghia et al. (2005) found a correlation between the magnitude gap and the FG formation time, i.e. the earlier a group forms the larger the magnitude gap at z=0.
It appears that FGs form early and evolve in isolation over a ~4 Gyr timescale. During this time the first-ranked galaxy is built up by mergers of L>=L* galaxies while the dwarf galaxies evolve passively because their timescale for orbital decay by dynamical friction exceeds the Hubble time.
Most studies of FGs have been in the X-ray (Khosroshahi et al. 2004; Sun et al. 2004; Yoshioka et al. 2004; Ulmer et al. 2005; Khosroshahi et al. 2007). Photometric studies of FGs have looked at the C-M relation (Adami et al. 2007) and the luminosity function (Jones et al. 2000; Mendes de Oliveira et al. 2006; Zibetti et al. 2009). Few spectroscopic studies have been undertaken (Mendes de Oliveira et al. 2006; Adami et al. 2007), and none have examined the stellar populations in any detail.
As shown in von Benda-Beckmann et al. (2008), FGs are a well-defined phase in the dynamical evolution of groups. Prior to the fossil phase, insufficient time has passed to allow all the L* galaxies to merger via dynamical friction. The fossil group phase could cease via the infall of luminous nearby galaxies. Also, just before the FG develops the magnitude gap, the system could appear as a compact group before collapsing down to a FG (e.g., Eigenthaler & Zeilinger (2009), but see Mendes de Oliveira & Carrasco (2008) for a counter argument).
So while the dynamical process for the formation of FGs remains highly uncertain, we propose that the key to deciphering the puzzle lies in understanding the stellar evolutionary histories of the dwarf galaxies in FGs. For instance, the stellar populations of Hickson compact groups indicate that they are old, red and dead with no evidence of recent SF or mergers (Mendes de Oliveira et al. 2005). This is different from the equivalent population found in clusters, where galaxies are younger and bluer than expected from simulations (Baldry et al. 2006; Weinmann et al. 2006). By studying the stellar populations of the dwarfs within FGs, we can easily differentiate when compared to what is seen in compact groups (old and dead) versus clusters (younger and more active). This in turn will help us pin down the dynamical evolution history of FGs.
We propose here observations with GMOS-N to investigate the stellar populations of galaxies down to m*_{R}+3 in three FGs, J133129.65+110757.0 at z=0.081, J165943.94+323655.1 at z=0.1, and J144512.41+292532.6 at z=0.1234 (see Fig. 1 for color-magnitude diagrams and optical images overlaid with X-ray contours of each FG). These FGs contain plenty of targets down to our magnitude limit, and we should have no problem using all the available slits on a mask. With these observations we will measure velocity dispersions and index strengths for the entire set of Lick indices and then compare these strengths to the predictions from the Thomas et al. (2004) stellar population models to estimate ages, metallicities, and alpha-element abundance ratios. With these data we will then be able to examine the stellar populations of the FG galaxies and to determine if there is any difference between the first-ranked galaxy and the others. If these observations prove sucessful, we have a larger sample of FGs with which to repeat the process carried out here. With a larger sample of FGs we could examine the predicted correlation between the formation time and the size of the magnitude gap.

We propose to use GMOS-N to obtain accurate velocity dispersions and the entire set of Lick indices for galaxies as faint as m*_{R}+3 (i.e. m_{R}~20.1) in three FGs, in order to estimate their ages, metallicities, and alpha-element abundance ratios. The field of each fossil group in Fig. 1 is a fixed aperture of 200 kpc around the central galaxy, this equates to 2.2' for J133129.65+110757.0, 1.8' for J165943.94+323655.1, and 1.5' for J144512.41+292532.6. Thus, given the 5.5' FOV of GMOS-N, it will be possible for us to target many more galaxies than are shown in the colour-magnitude diagrams in Fig. 2, and to use all the available slits on a mask.
We will use the B600 grating, centred at 461 nm, to observe the FGs. The use of this grating will allow us to measure the strengths of the entire set of Lick indices. This set of indices contain a number of good indicators which, along with being sensitive to age effects, can also help us to recreate the SFH of each galaxy, as they give the SFR integrated over different timescales, i.e. [OII]3727, Hdelta, Hgamma, Hbeta and [OIII]. It also contains widely used indicators for determining metallicity and alpha-element abundance ratio, e.g. Mgb, Fe5270 and Fe5335, and for breaking the age/metallicity degeneracy.
The use of the B600 grating with 0.5" slitlets will give us a velocity resolution of ~180 km s^{-1}, sufficient to measure accurate velocity dispersion for our objects. The SDSS spectra are not of a high enough resolution nor quality to measure velocity dispersions for each galaxy.
The ages, metallicities, and alpha-element abundance ratios will be estimated by comparison of the measured line-strengths, properly calibrated to the Lick system using the Lick standards database recently set up by Bryan Miller at Gemini South, with the predictions from the Thomas et al. (2004) stellar population models. It is difficult to calibrate spectral indices measured from SDSS spectra to the Lick system because there are no objects (with spectra) in common. Very crudely, in these models at ages of 4 Gyr, with solar metallicity and [alpha/Fe]=0.3, an error of 0.5 angstroms in Hdelta corresponds to a 1 Gyr age error. However, this error will be smaller when Hdelta is used in combination with many other indices to estimate the stellar population parameters. This 0.5 angstrom error requires a S/N~12, or ~65 over the 28.75 angstrom bandpass. Given the pixel scale of 0.47 angstrom/pixel this results in a S/N requirement of ~6. Since this is the bluest and most difficult index to measure we tailor our exposure time calculations on this feature.
Our objective can be obtained with 5 hours of integration time per FG with the above setup and assuming an extended source (elliptical galaxy) with a Gaussian profile of 1" FWHM, binning 4 pixels in the spatial direction, 70% image quality, 50% cloud cover and sky background, and a typical airmass of 1.5. With overheads of 2 hours per FG we require 21 hours in total. Note, pre-imaging should only require 5 minutes of integration per field and, therefore, will only require 20 minutes per field including overheads.

Recently, deep Chandra observations of the Galactic Center (GC) revealed a large, new population of low luminosity X-ray sources. Spectroscopic follow-up of these sources have identified a plethora of new, rare binaries, including several Colliding Wind Binary (CWB) systems containing Wolf-Rayet (WR) stars [6,10]. CWBs are defined as binaries where both massive components produce supersonic stellar winds which interact in a zone of collision producing hard X-ray emission and dust.
In 2005, we identified the first spectroscopically confirmed NIR counterpart to the low luminosity Chandra source CXOGC J174536.1-285638 (hereafter Edd-1; [7]). Based on the X-ray and NIR spectra, the X-ray to NIR luminosity ratio, and the X-ray light-curve, we showed that the source is most likely a massive star in a binary system with a period of 189 +/- 6 days [7,8]. Based on line ratios, P-Cygni profiles in HeII lines, the significant hydrogen emission, and the morphological match of the IR spectrum to WR 108, we tentatively classify Edd-1 as WN9h+O binary, however, because the secondary star leaves no trace in the NIR spectrum, we cannot rule out a compact object companion [3,4]. Other examples of WN7-9h stars have recently been identified in the Arches cluster through NIR spectroscopy, and strong X-ray emission comparable to that seen in Edd-1, suggests that three of these sources are physically identical to Edd-1 [3].
The discovery of these candidate WN9h+ binary systems could represent a ground-breaking advance in our understanding of these types of stars. WN9h stars are believed to form from massive (>60Mo) stars as they evolve off the main sequence, are postulated as LBV progenitors. Additionally, relatively few WN9 stars are known to occur in binary systems. Of 127 known WN stars, 49 are in binary systems, and only two of those contain WN9h stars. Confirmation of these candidates as binary could help constrain models regarding their formation and evolution, as well as the evolutionary tracks of other rare massive stars.
One method to confirm the binarity of these candidates is to directly image the dusty MIR "bubbles" around these object, since dust formation is driven by strong shock layers in the wind collision zones. Previous surveys with Spitzer examining the GC and Galactic plane have revealed warm dust structures, likely heated and sculpted by winds and radiation from young hot stars [2]. These bubbles have been studied around massive stars and range in size from 0.1 - 16.9pc, depending on the mass-loss rate of the star and the density of the ISM [2]. Spitzer studies have shown that 8 microns is ideal for studying the shell of these bubbles. Interestingly, studies at ~20 microns have shown the interior of these bubbles glowing at longer wavelengths [2].
While both single and binary WR stars are known to have circumstellar bubbles, CWBs have an additional hot-spot in the wind-collision zone which is the source of the X-ray radiation. This zone also produces MIR radiation consistent with free-free emission from the ionized wind, creating a unique signature not present in single star systems. We expect to see asymmetries in the wind structure indicative of a wind collision zone and the presence of a second, windy star. Analysis of the morphology and the construction of an SED will allow us to model the winds from and constrain the nature of the companion star. Imaging and modeling bubbles in the N and Qa-bands around evolved massive binary stars would be a significant breakthrough, yielding 1) a method to apply to recent wide-scale MIR surveys to hunt for more of these rare binaries 2) a potential way to study the colliding wind zone, and 3) a potentially valuable tool for determining properties of the components and the strengths and extents of their winds. Careful examination of warm dust structures can lead to a better understanding of the environments of massive stars, and the discovery of additional massive stars.
If no bubble is directly imaged, the fluxes derived from the N- and Qa- band imaging may still be used to prove the presence of dust. One method, recently used to help confirm a new WC9+OB system [12], is to compare the NIR and MIR SED of a potential binary to that of a lone WC9 star. The shape of the SED clearly shows a significant increase in longer wavelengths not seen in the single WR which is indicative of dust production around the colliding wind binary. Thus, even without directly imaging the dust around the WR, the binarity of the system was confirmed. While this would not offer us the ability to directly study the morphology of the bubble or the impact around the ISM, it would confirm the binary nature of the WN7-9+ candidates.
Thus we propose to look at Edd-1 and the three Arches stars,in the MIR with T-ReCS and compare them to WR 108, a known WN9h+O binary. The presence of dust has recently been presented in close vicinity to single WN stars [1], however, our study represents a pioneering attempt to target WN9h stars in binary systems, and the first recorded images of these systems at 17-19 microns. By combining MIR photometry with our X-ray and NIR data, we can construct an SED and constrain the nature of the counterpart. Studying the morphology of the nebula at MIR wavelengths is important as well, as asymmetries in the circumstellar nebula will yield confirmation of the binary nature of these sources, and allow us to study the motion of the system through the local ISM. This last point is particularly important for Edd-1 which has no known cluster association. Although Edd-1 appears close in age to the Arches stars, it is not likely associated with that cluster [3]. Finally, as the dust formation events may be periodic in these systems, studying these candidates as a group will reveal different phases of the process.
