Our primary goal for this project is to image mid-ir (MIR) "bubbles" surrounding one bona fide and four candidate Wolf Rayet (WR) Colliding Wind Binaries (CWB). Further, we propose to observe these five objects in the N-and Qa- bands, combine this with previously attained NIR observations, and construct an SED. We can then compare these SEDs to those for non-binary WN and WC stars to search for an extra MIR component typical of thermal emission from hot dust. If such an excess is discovered we can confirm their WN7-9h+OB classification of our candidates. Although this technique has been used before for WC+OB stars [12], it has not been attempted for WN+OB binaries; thus we will use the known WN9h+O binary, WR 108, as a control.
T-ReCS on Gemini South is the ideal instrument for this project. As these sources are all located in very crowded regions with a plethora of potential MIR sources, the superb MIR resolution of T-ReCS is absolutely crucial to tie the correct MIR excess to each candidate. Also, the field-of-view of T-ReCS allows us to capture all three potential WN+OB candidates in the Arches in one snapshot greatly improving our efficiency.
While the sources themselves may be very bright (10 Jy), the extended MIR bubbles we hope to image may be quite faint. Given the brightness of other MIR bubbles around hot stars, we expect a flux of 10-20 mJy for each source in the N-band. We would like to obtain SNR = 25; this will allow us to both construct the SED mentioned above and study the morphology and structure of the emission. Using the T-ReCS listed T-ReCS sensitivities and the ETC we expect a SNR = 25 in N-band in an on-source time of 15 minutes in BG = ANY, WV = 85, IQ = 70, CC = 50 conditions. A reasonable IQ is required to limit confusion, especially in the Arches cluster; WV = 85 is acceptable for N-band observations, which are less sensitive to water vapor.
We expect fluxes of approximately 150-200 mJy for each source in Qa-band. For a SNR = 25 in Qa-band we find an on-source time of 15 minutes in BG = ANY, WV = 50, IQ = 85, CC = 50 conditions. We request WV = 50 since this band is very sensitive to water vapor, but only IQ = 85 as this is the diffraction limit in Qa.
Give the ~25% efficiency of T-ReCS we estimate a total wall clock time of 1 hour for each of the three fields (Edd-1, Arches, WR 108) in the N-band and Qa-band. Thus we would like to request a total of 6 hours of Gemini time for this program.

The discovery (Daddi et al. 2005; Trujillo et al. 2006) that most massive galaxies (M* > 10^11 M_sun), independently of their star formation rate (Perez-Gonzalez et al. 2008), were much more compact in the past (a factor of aproximately 4 at z> 1.5) than their equally massive local counterparts (Trujillo et al. 2007, Longhetti et al. 2007, Conselice et al. 2009) represents a major challenge for current galaxy formation scenarios. It is therefore crucial to adress the question of how these high-z galaxies have evolved into present-day massive population. Most of the current theoretical work in this area suggests "dry'' mergers as the dominant mechanism for size and stellar mass growth of these very dense galaxies (Khochfar & Silk 2006; Hopkins et al. 2009). As cosmic time evolves, the high-z compact galaxies are thought to end into present-day cores of the brightest cluster galaxies. However, a fraction of these objects migth survive intact from early formation having stellar population with old ages. In fact, in some model renditions the fraction of massive objects that could last without having any significant transformation since z >2 could reach 1-10% (with a space density of aproximately 10^-4 Mpc^-3). On the other hand, assuming a radically different point of view, Fan et al (2008) have suggested a puffing-up scenario where the superdense massive galaxies in the early universe can grow in size without suffering merging. This mechanism argues that the observed strong evolution in size is related to the quasar feedback, which removes huge amounts of cold gas from the central regions quenching the star formation. A unique opportunity to adress the conundrum of the superdense massive galaxies in the high-z universe is to explore the presence of similar objects in the local universe. Such superdense massive objects in our vicinity allow us to explore the problem of the growth of these puzzling galaxies. Using the NYU Value-Added Galaxy Catalog from the SDSS Data Release 6 (Blanton et al. 2005a), we have investigated whether there are objects in the nearby universe (z< 0.2) with sizes (as parameterized by the effective radius) of r_e aproximately 1 kpc and stellar masses of M* aproximately 10^11 M_sun (see Fig.1). We only have found (Trujillo et al. 2009) a tiny fraction of local galaxies (0.03%) with r_e<1.5 kpc and M*> 8x10^10 M_sun. These galaxies have large values of Sersic index <n> = 4.7 and their stellar mass densities are close to the values found in the present day globular clusters. We also have conducted a stellar population analysis of these galaxies using SDSS spectra (with S/N=20). The analysis of relevant absorption line-strength indices allowed us to unambiguously conclude that their luminosity-weighted ages are clearly younger (~2 Gyr) than a control sample of galaxies of similar masses but normal sizes (4-6 kpc; see Fig.1 and Fig.3). The extraordinary similarity in age and structural parameters between the local superdense galaxies and the most massive systems at high-z opens a unique window to have a ``close look'' that will allow us to investigate with unprecedented detail the early evolutionary stages of the most massive high-z galaxies. In Trujillo et al. (2009) we already have compiled a large amount of information about these superdense massive local objects including ground-based imaging (at 1 arcsec resolution from the SDSS imaging; see Fig.2) and SDSS spectra (see Fig.3). However, we lack a detailed sub-kpc view of these superdense nearby massive objects to address key questions related to the structural properties of these galaxies, which should provide clues on how the most massive galaxies have evolved. High spatial resolution with Gemini + NIRI/ALTAIR camera will allow us to answer questions such as: are these compact galaxies composed of a disk plus an inner massive bulge or are they well described by a single spheroid component? Is there any signature in these galaxies that could be related to an ongoing merger activity (such as tidal tails, clumps of star formation, etc) that allow us to decide between the two competing evolutionary scenarios sketched above. This nearby superdense galaxy sample will allow us to provide a unique insight into the nature of the most massive high-z galaxies, in particular into the early stages of their evolutionary story.
THE SAMPLE We propose observing a subsample from the sample of nearby massive superdense galaxies compiled in Trujillo et al. (2009). The original sample contains 29 bona-fide superdense massive galaxies (with no detected signatures of AGN activity in their spectra which migth affect the size determination). The mean redshift for our galaxies is 0.16. These objects have a mean effective radius of aproximately 1.3 kpc and a mean stellar mass of aproximately 9.2x10^10M_sun. Part of the sample is being observed in the William Herschel Telescope for high signal-to-noise spectroscopy. We request time in order to complement the subsample and to get high-resolution imaging for those targets. For this, we have found 4 objects that can be observed during the proposed period (specially between April-May) with NIRI/ALTAIR and the laser guide star system. That means that our objects have a natural guide star (for the tip-tilt correction) no further than 18 arcsec from the science target and with a magnitud R< 17. We propose to observe our objects in the K-band. With a natural seeing < 0.5 arcsec this implies that we will reach 0.15-0.2 arcsec resolution at the source. This is almost a factor of 2 better than current performance of the NICMOS camera at the HST. Due to the compacteness of our sources, ground-based resolution (i.e. without adaptive optics) prevent us to explore sub-kpc morphological features related to minor merger activity. For this reason, the superb resolution of the Gemini+NIRI/ALTAIR is mandatory if we want to provide robust clues on the evolutionary mechanism of the superdense massive objects.

Our sample of galaxies has typically V=17 mag (K~15.8 AB mag). The brightness (and vicinity) of our objects (z~0.15) implies that we would be able to explore their surface brigthness profiles down to very low surface brightness limits. Note that the cosmological surface brightness dimming will play a minor role in our observations (around 0.5 mag). We estimate that our mean surface brightness profiles will be reliable (at 3 sigma level) down to aproximatelly 27.5 mag/arcsec^-2 in the K band if we integrate on source 1 hour per object (60x60 sec individual exposures). This means a total of 4 hours on source to complete our program. The above surface brightness limit is enough for our purpouse of finding faint distortion features in our proposed target. Considering the 20 min for NIRI+Altair+LGS imaging setup and the on-source efficiency of ~75% associated with taking NIRI images, telescope offsetting (following) and read-out, the time required per galaxy is 100 minutes of 1.67 hours. In total, then we request for the four galaxies 6.7 hours.
This being a morphologically oriented proposal, we request the best image quality (best 20%) and the lower airmass (<1.2). However, for the rest of the parameters we can be less stringent since we have already our objects photometrically calibrated (cloud cover 50% or less, water vapour and sky background Any). The occurrence of these conditions is ~17% of the time.
According to the GEMINI ITC under 20%-il seeing conditions and using a AO star of R=17 mag at a distance of 20 arcsec from the source, the Strehl that can be achieved is 0.142. Taking into account that the FWHM of an AO-corrected core is 0.063 arcsec, the resulting images will have an effective FHWM of 0.15-0.20 arcsec, almost a factor of 2-3 better than NICMOS at the HST. This exquisite resolution is enough to sucessfully achieve our goals. Because of the size of the galaxies (6-8"), the f/14 camera (pixel scale 0.05") is required.
An extremely important issue is characterizing the PSF under which these observations are taken. We used the observations obtained during 2008A/2009A semesters of a sample of massive galaxies at high-z to characterize the change of the structural parameters of the galaxies as a function of the PSF (Conselice, Trujillo and Carrasco 2009, in preparation. To model the change of the Strehl through the galaxy image we took the AO stars which typically have a FHWM of 0.08 arcsec and convolved them with a gaussian with different FHWM to assure that the final PSF has the FWHM that we wish. We re-analyzed the structural parameters and found very little variation on them. The above exercise demonstrated that we are able to determine the structural parameters of the galaxies very robustly with the proposed configuration.

Identifying the most massive white dwarfs and determining their masses accurately is central to several areas of physics and astrophysics. White dwarf stars are the evolutionary endpoint for nearly 98% of all stars born in our Galaxy, but this percentage depends critically on our knowledge of the lower limit for the mass of main sequence stars destined to explode as SNII, around 7 to 10.5 Msun, depending on metallicity and core overshoot. This problem is exacerbated by the fact that massive white dwarfs are intrinsically rare objects, producing a gap in the determination of the initial vs. final mass relation at the high white dwarf mass end (e.g. Weidemann 2000 A&A, 363, 647; Kalirai et al. 2008, ApJ, 676, 594; Williams, Bolte & Koester 2009, ApJ, 693, 355). The same massive white dwarf stars serve to define the transition mass between neutron stars and white dwarfs, defining the empirical Chandrasekhar limit (1.44Msun to 1.36Msun, if general relativity effects are included). The massive white dwarfs constrain this boundary from below, giving information on the equation-of-state of matter under the most extreme density conditions just prior to neutron-drip. This boundary has important implications for our understanding of type Ia supernovae as well. The most accepted model for type Ia SNe is binary star systems with massive white dwarfs accreting enough material from its companion to drive it over the Chandrasekhar limit and into collapse and explosion. The most massive white dwarf stars give us snapshots of these objects just prior to collapse. The discovery of more than 20000 white dwarfs with the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS) presents the prospect of a corresponding increase in relatively rare varieties of white dwarfs, in particular the massive ones. We combed through the objects determined to be white dwarf stars based on SDSS classification spectra and used the best available SNR spectra - no better than SNR~30 - coupled with the most reliable theoretical line profile calculations available. For the first time, the fits included synthetic spectra from model atmospheres combined with evolutionary models above log g=9.5, thereby improving the estimates for massive white dwarf candidates. Kepler et al. (2007,MNRAS, 375, 1315) and Koester et al. (2009, JPhCS, 172, 12006) show that for DAs cooler than 11000K-12000K and DBs cooler than 16000K there is an still unexplained increase in the surface gravities derived from line profile fitting, not seen when gravities are derived using the observed colors. Because this effect is present in both SDSS fits, using Koester's models, and in the SNR>60 spectra of the PG survey white dwarfs analyzed by Liebert, Bergeron & Holberg (2005,ApJS, 156, 47), using Bergeron's models, we do not include cool stars in our sample. Our analysis of the discovery spectra indicates this sample of relatively young white dwarf stars likely include the most massive white dwarf stars yet found. In Kepler et al. (2007) we fitted the spectra of all white dwarfs from SDSS DR4 with hydrogen and helium dominated atmospheres (DAs and DBs, respectively) published by Eisenstein et al. (2006, ApJS, 167, 40). We used synthetic spectra obtained from model atmospheres up to log g=10 and consistent evolutionary models to estimate the masses for all DAs and DBs in the sample, discovering objects that are potentially the most massive white dwarfs ever detected, a 1.33 +/- 0.01 Msun DA and a 1.32+/- 0.03 Msun DB, but these are internal uncertainties only, unreliable. There are strong correlations between gravity and temperature determinations, and the determinations are based on spectra with SNR<30 around 450 nm and much lower SNR below 400 nm, where the H8 and H9 hydrogen lines in the DA white dwarf stars are located, the most sensitive to gravity. These two factors combined yield an unacceptably large real uncertainty in mass, external plus internal, from the SDSS classification spectra. Kleinman et al. 2009 (in preparation) fitted all 20000 white dwarf spectra in DR7, with Koester (2009) synthetic spectra, from which we selected the most massive candidates that did not exhibit clear Zeeman splitting due to strong magnetic fields, which mascared the surface gravity determinations. We propose to obtain SNR>70 spectra around 390-400 nm for a sample of the most massive of these stars, to accurately constrain their masses. We obtained GMOS-N spectra for a 1.33 DA in 2008A, showing it is indeed high mass, but the SNR achieved was below the requested, due to bad weather, and insuficient to reduce the uncertainty. In Kepler et al. (2006, MNRAS, 372, 1799) we compared SNR>60 Gemini GMOS spectra with SDSS spectra for 4 DAs and found the average external error of 0.05Msun, which together with our Monte Carlo simulations indicate that we will be able to achieve Delta log g=0.05 and Delta T=5%, if SNR>70. Despite the possible large external uncertainties in our SDSS determinations, we may safely conclude that the candidates are massive. J165538.93+253346.00 is a DAV candidate which we will observe with time series photometry to search for variability. Seismology will put independent constrains on its mass, if variable, and it will set the boundary of the massive DAV instability strip. J213103.39+105956.1 is the only DB included.

Although we are submitting this proposal to Gemini North, if it works better for the queue, we would happy to have the program split to be executed at both sites (Gemini North and Gemini South). Many of the targets are observable from GS as well as GN.
All our targets have spectra from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS). The signal to noise ratio (S/N) of the SDSS spectra is adequate for basic spectral characterization, but not sufficient for detailed studies. Among our chosen targets, only two have a SDSS spectrum with a S/N greater than 10. Since we are fitting atmospheric models to these spectra in order to determine each star's surface gravity (log g) and effective temperature (Teff) which will then give us the stellar mass, this low S/N means we end up with large uncertainties in our results, typically on the order of 0.2 in log g. This translates to uncertainties in total stellar mass of 0.06 Msun. Based on previous tests with both SDSS and Gemini data, we find that a S/N>~70 should provide us with Teff uncertainties of order 500K and log g uncertainties of order 0.05.
Our targets have brightnesses ranging from r=17.1 to 19.2 mag. We used the ITC to calculate expected exposure times to reach our desired S/N=70 goal for each of our objects. The resultant individual exposure times vary from about one to two hours. With overhead, we estimate that we will need a total of ~9.6 hr to obtain S/N=70 spectra for all our targets.
We would like to use GD 153 as our spectrophotometric standard star since it is one of the best calibrated standard, with 1A calibration with the HST. Since we use not only the lines but the whole spectrum (including the continuum) to fit the physical parameters, we would like to get as good a flux calibration as possible. We understand that requesting a specific standard for calibration is not part of the basic calibration provided by Gemini and have included in our total requested observing time to include this standard.
We will divide our observations to be able to account for cosmic rays hits and obtain exposures at 450 and 455nm to fill the gaps. We do request the slit be oriented at the parallatic angle to account for atmospheric aberration.

BACKGROUND: The present paradigm for nuclear activity in galaxies is that it is a phase in the evolution of the galaxy in which the supermassive black hole (hereafter SMBH) is being fed. Nevertheless, one long-standing difficulty of this scenario is the lack of observational signatures of gas inflows to the nuclear region. Most observational studies show outflows in the circumnuclear gas, in particular in the narrow-line region (hereafter NLR), usually interpreted as due to the interaction of nuclear radio jets and accretion disk winds with the insterstellar medium of the host galaxy [eg.Crenshaw et al. 2007, ApJ, 659, 250; Das et al. 2005, AJ, 130, 945].
Velocities of 40 km/s have been observed in our optical studies of inflows in ionized gas (Fathi et al. 2006, ApJ, 641L, 25; Storchi-Bergmann et al. 2007, ApJ, 670, 959). As we have pointed out in those studies, the ionized gas is probably only the "tip of the iceberg", and molecular gas is probably the main source of fuel to the SMBH. Thus, the H_2 emiting gas kinematics should be a better tracer of the inflows towards the nucleus of active galaxies. This is also supported by the large amounts of molecular gas in the inner regions of active galaxies observed in recent CO radio observations (e.g. Garcia-Burillo et al. 2003, A&A, 407, 485; 2005, A&A 441, 1011).
In the near-IR, we have been mapping the excitation and kinematics of the NLR emitting gas using GNIRS IFU and NIFS observations (Riffel et al. 2006 - MNRAS, 373, 2; Riffel et al. 2008, MNRAS, 385, 1129 & Riffel et al. 2009, MNRAS, 393, 783). The main result of these studies is that the ionized gas (traced by the [FeII]1.2570 and H recombination lines) is usually dominated by outflows, while the molecular gas (traced by H_2 emission lines in the K-band) is dominated by rotation in the galactic plane plus additional inflowing gas components. The ionized and molecular emitting gas also present distinct flux distributions, with the latter more uniformly distributed in the whole IFU field. In other recent studies (Storchi-Bergmann et al., 2009a, MNRAS, 394, 1148; Storchi-Bergmann et al. 2009b, submitted to MNRAS) the high angular and spectral resolution provided by NIFS+ALTAIR have been fundamental to clearly reveal marked differences between the H_2 kinematics and the [FeII] and Br-gamma kinematics in the galaxy NGC4151. The [FeII] and Br-gamma emitting gas is again dominated by outflows and oriented approximately along the radio axis, while the H_2 emitting gas is rotating in the plane.
Recent NIFS+ALTAIR observations of Mrk1066 confirms the above scenario (Riffel & Storchi-Bergmann 2009a,b, in preparation). The ionized gas presents an important outflowing component as observed in Fig.1, while in the H_2 kinematics we observe inflowing gas components towards the nucleus. The molecular gas seems to be accumulated in the inner region of the galaxy in a small nuclear disk with size of about 200 pc, as observed in Fig. 2.
GOALS OF THE PRESENT WORK: We propose to use the high angular and spectral resolution of NIFS+ALTAIR in order to map the gas kinematics in the [FeII]1.2570 and Pa_beta emission-lines in the J-band and in the H_2 2.1218 and Br-gamma in the K-band. We will also obtain the stellar kinematics from the fitting of the CO absorption bands around 2.3 microns using the pPXF method (Cappellari & Emsellem, 2007, PASP, 431, 465). Our goals are: 1) From fitting and slicing of the emission line profiles in velocity bins we will verify if the scenario which we have proposed is confirmed: that the H_2 maps the feeding (inflowing gas) and the other emission lines map the feedback (outflowing gas), as well as constraint the location of the emitting gas; 2) The simultaneuos observation of the stellar and gaseous kinematics will allow us to isolate and estimate inflows and outflows rates and thus quantify the energy and mass balance between feeding and feedback; 3) From the flux distributions and ratios, as well as from correlations with the kinematics of the H_2 and [FeII] emission lines we will be able to map and investigate the nature of excitation mechanisms of the emitting gas.
We have selected for these observations the nearby Seyfert galaxies Mrk766 and Mrk79 because they present radio continuum and [OIII]5007 extended emission (Nagar et al. 1999, ApJS, 120, 209; Schmitt et al. 2003, ApJS, 148, 327), which will allow us to explore the relation between the radio jet and the NLR kinematics, as well as its effect in the excitation of the near-IR lines.

NIFS + ALTAIR will be used to record J and K 2D spectra of the nuclear region of the active galaxies Mrk766 and Mrk79. The spectral regions include emission lines of [FeII], HI and H_2 as well as the stellar CO 2.3micron absorption bands, with a velocity resolution of ~ 60 km/s (< 30 km/s per spectral pixel) that will easily resolve velocity structure within the lines. A stellar velocity dispersion of 50 km/s (which we aim to be able to measure) corresponds to a Gaussian absorption-line FWHM of 117 km/s. The spatial scale along each NIFS slitlet is 0.04arcsec/pixel with the spatial resolution being set by the performance of ALTAIR. Our previous observations have shown that on average we can expect to obtain spatial resolutions of aproximately 35-50 pc for the two galaxies in this proposal. As there are no available Altair guide stars in the field of the proposed targets, we will use the nucleus of each galaxy as natural guide star for ALTAIR. Both galaxies present Seyfert 1 nuclear activity and HST images of these galaxies obtained through the filter F606W show that the optical nucleus is point-like, with high contrast over the surrounding bulge (Malkan et al. 1998, ApJS, 117, 25).
Adopting an average surface brightness in the J band of 1.8E-15 erg/s/cm2/A/arcsec2 for Mrk766 (Riffel et al. 2006, A&A, 457, 61) a S/N ratio larger than 25 (needed for our kinematic analysis) will be obtained with 1 hr integration in each band. Using the emission line fluxes quoted in Rodriguez-Ardila et al. (2004, A&A, 425, 457) we obtain a similar S/N ratio for the emission lines, which will allow us to map the emission line flux distributions and kinematics. Mrk79 has similar continuum flux and emission line equivalent widhts to those of Mrk766, thus we estimate obtaining a similar S/N ratio in the same exposure time. We therefore propose to obtain a total of 1 hr on-source integration for each band for each galaxy. We propose to obtain six 10-min on source exposures, which can be median-combined, with no SNR penalty, data processing to reject cosmic rays. Off-source sky spectra will be obtained with the same exposure time in a standard object-sky-object-object-sky-object sequence by offsetting the telescope to a sky position.
The full observing sequence for each band for each target is then: 30 min set up on the target; and 90 min on-source and sky observations for each band. The total elapsed time for each target will be 4.0 hr, thus the total time requested in the present proposal is 8.0 hr. The present proposal is a joint proposal between Brasil and Gemini Staff and we thus request 4 hrs from each TAC.
Early-type Hipparcos stars will be selected for telluric correction to be observed before/after each science target. 2MASS fluxes for these stars will provide our flux calibration. An accurate determination of the PSF will be essential in analysing the velocity dispersion data. The telluric correction stars will also provide this information.
Stellar templates are needed to measure the velocity broadening of the stellar absorption features. As for previous works (Riffel et al. 2008, MNRAS, 385, 1129; Riffel et al. 2009, MNRAS, 393, 783), we plan to use the Gemini GNIRS+NIFS library of late type stars (Winge, Riffel & Storchi-Bergmann, submitted to ApJS), thus we do not need to observe separate kinematic standard stars.

We propose to produce (1) a high-resolution image and (2) a high-resolution single-slit pilot observation of [NeII] in the mid-IR (MIR) of M82 using Michelle. The precise sites of star formation (SF) in a starburst galaxy are still unknown, and starburst cannot be understood without observations which reveal SF obscured in molecular clouds. We aim to compare high-resolution [NeII] data with the new CO and H-alpha observations under the same physical and kinematic scale, which allows a unique opportunity to find direct evidence of SF within molecular clouds in M82.
***The Target*** M82 is the most well-studied starburst galaxy which harbors numerous super star clusters (SSCs) in its disk. Its proximity (3.6 Mpc) provides a high linear resolution (1"~17 pc) that is comparable to the size of a typical SSC (5-10 pc). The starburst in M82 is resolved into a diffuse extended component and clumps identified as 197 young SSCs in H-alpha (Melo et al. 2005) (M05). These clusters have masses of 10^4-10^6 Mo and extinction of 2-6 magnitude. The CO (2-1) emission in the center of M82 is resolved into ~300 clumps by Keto et al. (2005) (K05) with resolutions of 1" and 10 km/s. The clouds have sizes of 17-170 pc, masses of 10^3-10^7 Mo, and an average extinction of tens of magnitudes or more. The slope of the cloud mass spectrum agrees with that of young star clusters, suggesting that each cloud may transform into one star cluster. The CO clouds are surrounded by SSCs, and the velocity profile at the cloud peripheral indicates infall motions. K05 therefore further suggested a SSC-induced SF in molecular clouds. However the free-fall timescale of a cloud (~1 Myr) is shorter than the characteristic age of a young SSC (3-7 Myr). SSCs could form in clouds and are only visible optically after they clear their parent cloud. Therefore the outside-in triggering interpretation by K05 is biased by comparing with the visible SSCs only. While the high-resolution CO and H-alpha data provide hints of SF in the molecular clouds in M82, a direct evidence of such SF is missing. The only way to prove SF in clouds is to look for the stars themselves. This requires a bright emission line which directly traces SF and is transparent to the heavily obscured M82 disk and within the optically opaque molecular clouds themselves.
***The [Ne II] line*** The forbidden line [NeII] at 12.814 um is emitted by ionized gas and is a direct indicator of SF, since only massive stars are capable of singly ionizing Neon atoms at 21.6 eV, and the [NeII] intensity is directly proportional to the emission measure of ionized gas in SSC-driven HII regions. While optical and near-IR lines are subject to extinction, the [NeII] line is almost extinction-free in the M82 disk (Av~0.25 magnitude). Furthermore, [NeII] emission is much brighter than any hydrogen recombination lines in the MIR.
***[Ne II] imaging*** The purpose of the [NeII] imaging is to search for SF associated directly with the ~300 molecular clouds found by K05, and to guide future proposals for spectroscopic followup. This is a vital step in understanding where SF is currently active, and whether the infall motions suspected in these clouds is driving SF inside the clouds. A very high resolution image is needed to guide spectroscopic observations. To directly associate SSC-driven ionized gas with molecular clouds, the [NeII] observation requires precisely identical resolution to that of the CO data cube, because the same physical scale is spatially filtered to reveal the same structures. The highest resolution [NeII] image by far (Achtermann & Lacy 1995; AL95) has a spatial resolution of 2", which is too poor to be directly compared with the CO data (1"; K05). Michelle provides a resolution of 0.6" (10.2 pc; typical seeing in the MIR on Mauna Kea), which is comparable to the CO resolution and corresponds to the same physical scale of the typical size of SSCs. In addition, a 0.6" resolution is 3 times higher than that of AL95. The higher resolution will suppress extended emission by a factor of 9, leading to a greatly enhanced chance of detecting clumpy SF associated with newly born clusters within the molecular clouds. We will observe the area that covers the brightest [NeII] emission and most CO clouds and optical SSCs (see Fig. 1), and this observation is sensitive to SSCs with masses >10^5 Mo (see the technical justification).
***[Ne II] single-slit experiment*** Ultimately, the identification of SF associated with molecular clouds in [NeII] will require 2-D spectroscopy in selected regions to provide a direct comparison with the CO data in velocity. The imaging work described here is a first step, and should provide important guidance for a future spectroscopic proposal. However, to demonstrate the potential of spectroscopic work, we propose a pilot single-slit [NeII] observation with high spectral resolution of R=30,000 (10 km/s). This observation provides an exactly identical velocity resolution to that of the CO data cube, therefore we can directly compare the position-velocity maps of the ionized gas and molecular clouds. This will reveal strong evidence of whether there is ongoing SF in the clouds. Our observation provides 3 times higher spectral and spatial resolution than those of AL95 (10 km/s vs. 30 km/s; 0.6" vs. 2"), hence it will deliver 9 (3x3) times more information. We will place one slit across the brightest [NeII] emission seen in AL95 (see Fig. 1).

We will use the [NeII] filter at 12.814 um for the narrow band imaging and the Si-6 filter for the continuum subtraction. The Si-6 filter will also be used in the echelle mode for a single-slit [NeII] observation. It requires 2 pointings for both the narrow and broad band imaging (see Fig. 1).
We estimated the sensitivity to detect compact sources with the aid of the H-alpha data. The optical SSCs that have H-alpha luminosity L_H-alpha >2e39 ergs/s, which corresponds to cluster masses >10^5 Mo (M05), will have [NeII] luminosity L_NeII >4e38 ergs/s, given that L_NeII/L_H-alpha=0.2 (Ho & Keto (2007)). The [NeII] flux will be >4e-13 ergs/s/cm^2 in a 0.6"x0.6" aperture, and this is 4 times brighter than the sensitivity of our [NeII] image (see the next section), which will give a S/N>12 detection. This also implies that we are sensitive to SSCs with masses >10^5 Mo within the most massive molecular clouds. We will statistically correlate the [NeII] with CO emission, and the CO data is available in the OVRO archive.
***[Ne II] imaging*** We adopted the surface brightness reported in AL95 and used Michelle ITC to estimate the required integration time . The SB at the edge of the bright [NeII] emission (the 5th contour in Fig. 1) is 2.88e-13 ergs/s/cm^2/arcsec^2 , which corresponds to a flux of 1.04e-13 ergs/s/cm^2 enclosed in an aperture of 0.6"x0.6" (typical seeing in the MIR on MK). We then input a point source flux of 1.04e-13 ergs/s/cm^2 with a line width of 100 km/s (AL95) and 0 continuum in Michelle ITC. The S/N will be ~3 in a total exposure time of 900*6 sec (50% is on source), since the NeII filter has 40% transmission. Taking into account the 25% observing efficiency and the overhead of 6 min, we will need 6*60+900*6*/0.25=21960 sec=6.1 hr. We need 2 pointings in order to observe the area that covers the brightest [Ne II] emission and most of the CO clouds and optical clusters (see Fig. 1), therefore we require 6.1 hr*2=12.2 hr for the narrow band imaging.
We will need a broad band image to properly subtract the continuum in the [NeII] image. The contribution of the continuum emission in the [NeII] filter is estimated by scaling the 12.4 um continuum (Telesco & Gezari (1992) (TG92)) by the ratio of the filter bandwidth of [NeII] to 12.4 um. TG92 estimated that ~20% of the continuum at 12.4 um is from the [NeII] emission, and the [NeII] to 12.4 um filter bandwidth ratio is 0.15. Therefore the continuum emission measured in the [NeII] filter should be ~60%. An important criterion is that the noise introduced by the continuum subtraction has to be significantly less than the noise measured in the line emission, and we assumed the continuum noise is 50% of the line noise. When the S/N of the line measurement is given, this sets the S/N needed for the continuum measurement. For a S/N=5 line measurement, a S/N=6 continuum measurement is needed. In the ITC we input the 12.4 um SB of 0.12 Jy/arcsec^2 (80% of 66 Jy integrated over a 15"x30" area; TG92) as an extended source profile and a 226K blackbody. It requires ~1 sec total exposure time to reach a continuum measurement S/N=6 per pointing. Considering the 25% observing efficiency and the 6 min overhead, we need 7 min per pointing, and therefore 7*2=14 min for 2 pointings is required.
***[Ne II] single-slit spectroscopy*** The brightest [NeII] SB in AL95 is 1.15e-12 ergs/s/cm^2/arcsec^2, which corresponds to a flux of 1.84e-13 ergs/s/cm^2 enclosed in one resolution unit of 0.4"x0.4". We input this flux with 0 continuum and a 100 km/s line width was assumed. We can reach a S/N=10 with a total integration time of 1800 sec. The background sky emission can be removed by nodding the source along the slit and subtracting adjacent nod positions. Therefore 50% of the total integration time will be on source and another 50% will be on the sky. Considering observing overheads and efficiency in the echelle mode, we will need 1800*1.5=2700 sec=45 min.
***Flux calibration*** The flux calibration of the [NeII] narrow and broad band images will be carried out by observing M giants. Our primary flux calibrator mu UMa is -1.03 magnitude at 12.4 um (TG92) and in the N band (IRTF bright infrared standard list) , and the secondary flux calibrator alpha Her is -3.94 magnitude in the N band (IRTF bright infrared standard list). It will take ~1*6 sec of total exposure time to reach a S/N=5 for each star's [NeII] image, and ~1 sec for each star's broad band image. Taking into account of the observing overhead and efficiency, we need (1*6/0.25)*2+(1/0.25)*2+6*60*2=776 sec=13 min.
***Baseline calibrations*** At the declination of M82, the airmass will not vary much during the 45 min duration of the spectroscopic observation, a single telluric observation should suffice. The wavelength calibration can be done by sky lines in the raw data. Therefore wavelength calibration, telluric standard, flat fields, and dark will be charged to our partner country, and we did not include the time requirement in the proposal.
***Total integration time*** In summary, we need 12.2 hr for the [Ne II] image, 14 min for the broad band continuum image, 45 min for the single-slit observation, and 13 min for observing flux standards. We therefore require 12.2 hr+14 min+45 min+13 min=13.4 hr for this observation.

The low-temperature field brown dwarfs are of interest for many reasons. They are important for studies of star formation and the initial mass function (IMF) at low masses, and of the chemistry and physics of cool atmospheres. Furthermore, they populate the substellar temperature range and can act as proxies for giant exoplanets which have similar temperatures and radii, but which have less well-understood interiors and which are harder to observe than isolated brown dwarfs. The far-red Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS; York et al. 2000) and the Two Micron All Sky Survey (2MASS; Skrutskie et al. 2006), led to the discovery of the field population of very low mass and low temperature stars and brown dwarfs - the L and T dwarfs (e.g. Kirkpatrick et al. 1997, Leggett et al. 2000). The L dwarfs have effective temperatures (T_eff) of 1400-2200 K and the T dwarfs have T_eff < 1400K (e.g. Stephens et al. 2009) with a lower limit not yet defined. Burrows et al. (2003) calculate that several changes will occur near T_eff=400 K which may trigger a new spectral type, including the formation of H_2_O clouds and strengthening of NH_3 features.
The flux from the T dwarfs is emitted in the far-red through mid-infrared(IR), and the classification scheme is based on the strength of the near-IR H_2_O and CH_4 absorption bands (Burgasser et al. 2006). At this time, only 16 T dwarfs are published with spectral type later than T7, i.e. with T_eff < 900K. The near-IR spectra of the three recently discovered T9 dwarfs (Warren et al. 2007; Burningham et al. 2008; Delorme et al. 2008), the latest spectral type currently known, hint at an NH_3 feature at 1.5 um and suggest that we may be at the brink of defining the next spectral class, for which the letter Y has been suggested (Kirkpatrick et al. 1999). These T9 dwarfs have 500 < T_eff K < 600 (Leggett et al. 2009) and are approaching the temperature where H_2_O clouds form.
Significant chemical changes occur in a brown dwarf atmosphere as it cools. Cloud decks of liquid and solid iron and silicate grains exist in the photospheres of L dwarfs, and their grain-reddened spectral energy distributions (SEDs) show strong metal hydride and neutral alkali lines, as well as H_2_O, CO and, in the mid-IR, CH_4 bands. The T dwarf photospheres are too cool for grains, which condense and evaporate in deeper layers of the atmosphere. These clear photospheres have optically red SEDs shaped predominantly by the red wing of the strong K I doublet at 770 nm, and near- and mid-IR SEDs which are sculpted by strong absorption bands of H_2_O, CH_4 and NH_3 (in the mid-IR). Figure 1 shows spectra of a T8 and T9 dwarf with T_eff= 750K and 600K, respectively.
Figure 2 shows an optical spectrum of a T4.5 dwarf with T_eff=1300K which shows K I, Rb I and Cs I absorption. For cooler T dwarfs the Cs is predominantly in the form of CsCl, and the chloride form of K and Rb is calculated to become signficant for T_eff<1000K, or T7 and later types (Lodders 1999, her Figure 2). This loss of K I from the photosphere and weakening of the strong and very broad 770 nm K I doublet leads to a significant change in the optical colors of cold brown dwarfs, which become less red. Figure 3 shows model sequences and observed izYJ colors for T dwarfs, and shows the dramatic turn to the blue in i-z and z-Y that is expected at T_eff<700K. Marley et al. (2002) show that i-z colors are very sensitive to the treatment of the cloud decks and alkali chemistry, and that their models which include grain sedimentation and loss of the alkalis to chloride formation reproduce the data better than models which do not include alkali "rain out". For T dwarfs, the red flux is controlled by the K I feature which depends both on abundance and line broadening. At low T_eff the abundance is low due to condensation and the flux emerges from relatively deep levels and becomes more dependent on pressure broadening. The exceptionally strong broadening is difficult to model, and Marley et al. (2002) calculate that different treatments of the line broadening change the i-z colors by 0.4 magnitudes.
While little flux is emitted in the red for the latest T dwarfs, it is important that we understand the alkali chemistry of T dwarf photospheres throughout the T spectral sequence, which entails getting the behavior at low T_eff to properly understand alkali condensation and removal from the atmosphere. In fact, all the spectral changes from M to L to T to Y dwarf are associated with condensation and so it is important to study this phenomenon in as many ways as possible. Furthermore, as more far-red/very-near-IR surveys continue to search for cold brown dwarfs using the izYJ bands (CFHTBDS, UKIDSS, Pan-Starrs, VISTA, LSST) it is very important that we can accurately identify candidates using these colors. Cold brown dwarfs are still very rare, in fact fewer are known than are exoplanets.
Getting the alkali chemistry right is actually critical for understanding exoplanets. Sudarsky et al. (2000) calculate that some classes of irradiated planets will have strong Na and K spectral features and Fortney (2005) calculate that the optical depth of condensates and hazes in transmission spectra of exoplanets is significant. Sing et al. (2008) have observed the presence of strong Na absorption in HST spectra of a hot Jupiter.
This proposal requests 13.0 hours with GMOS to obtain i and z photometry of a selection of 8 very late type T dwarfs with 800 > T_eff K > 500, to provide the first i-z colors of the coolest brown dwarfs. The sample selection is described in the technical case.

Loss of neutral K I gas from the photosphere of T8 to T9 dwarfs, due to condensation, leads to a dramatic turn to the blue in what are extremely red izYJ colors for warmer brown dwarfs (Figures 2, 3). No i photometry has been published for any dwarf later than T2. Red spectroscopy has been obtained using Keck for the brighter 2MASS T dwarfs to T8 types (Burgasser et al. 2003). However the known dwarfs later than T8 (cooler than ~800K) are so faint that spectroscopy with an 8-m telescope is prohibitive.
We propose to obtain i and z photometry for a sample of T8 to T9 dwarfs. Although z photometry has been published for a subset of the sample, the z passband is defined by the detector red cut-off, and this can lead to strong system dependencies for objects like the T dwarfs with their extremely red optical SEDs. The z observations are short and so we propose to obtain z for the entire sample to provide a homogeneous iz dataset.
The sample includes three well analysed, brighter, T7.5-T8 dwarfs: HD 3651B, Gl 570D and 2MASS 0415-09. The remainder of the sample consists of five fainter T8.5-T9 dwarfs: CFBDS 0059-01, ULAS 0034-00, ULAS 1300+12, ULAS 1335+11 and Wolf 940B. (Two more T8.5 objects are known but they are significantly fainter and so are excluded.) HD 3651B, Gl 570D and Wolf 940B are of special value as their main sequence companions constrain their metallicity and age (and hence gravity). The telescope will be pointed to put the bright primaries on a different GMOS chip from the target to minimise bleeding. Figure 3 shows that photometry accurate to <~10% is required to constrain the models given the inherent dispersion in the iz colors due to metallicity and gravity variations (which impact abundance and line broadening). Some scatter is indeed seen in the zYJ colors of the T8.5-T9 dwarfs (Figure 3) and so we request time to observe several targets.
We have used the ITC for GMOS-N to derive exposure times for our targets. A T8 template spectrum and reference flux levels were used as input. Overheads are estimated at 6 minutes setup time per target plus 2 minutes per exposure for readout, filter change, etc, as described in the GMOS web pages. We initially request GMOS-N as the red fringing is less than in the South, and as there is the possibility of more red sensitive detectors in 10A, in the North. However if the TAC prefers to move the program to the South that is acceptable.
Our default constraints are IQ70 CC50 SB50 WVany; our band 3 are IQ70 CC50 SB80 WVany (impacting i but not z significantly). We will use 2x2 binning. We have assumed an average airmass of 1.5, if the target can be observed at higher elevation then the S/N improves by about one-third. The four faintest targets (0059-01, 0034-00, 1335+11, W940B) have i~27 and z~22. In two hours on-source at i, made up of 8x900s exposures so as not to saturate, we can obtain S/N~15 with the default conditions and ~11 with the band 3 conditions. S/N~30 can be obtained at z with 3x180s exposures. ULAS 1300+12 has an estimated i~26 and z~21; 3x600s in i give S/N~20(15) and 2x60 in z give S/N~30. For 2MASS 0415-09, Gl 570D and HD 3651 with i~23-25 and z~19-20, 2x600s in i give S/N~25-40, and 2x60s in z gives S/N~70-100. The total observation length is 2.6 hrs for each of the four faintest T8.5-T9 dwarfs, 0.8 hrs for the T8.5 1300+12, and 0.6 hrs for each of the T7.5-T8 dwarfs 2MASS 0415-09, Gl 570D, and HD 3651B. The total request is 13.0 hrs.

White dwarfs are the end stage of stellar evolution for the vast majority of stars - all stars less massive than 8 solar masses end their lives as cooling white dwarfs. The coolest white dwarfs can constrain the age of the Galactic disk, or even of the halo. While other methods for dating the ages of the Galactic components exist (cluster isochrone fitting, isotope decay, asteroseismology, space motions, magnetic activity, etc), cold white dwarfs are unambiguously old and their cooling rates are well understood, enabling their use as simple and accurate chronometers.
White dwarf atmospheres are predominantly composed of helium and/or hydrogen. The opacity of helium is much lower than that of hydrogen, and hydrogen-rich white dwarfs of a given effective temperature (Teff) are older than their helium-rich counterparts due to the insulation provided by their atmospheres. Bergeron, Leggett & Ruiz (2001) show that the coolest known white dwarfs with Teff~4000K are ~9.5 Gyr old if hydrogen-rich and 8 Gyr old if helium-rich. These ages are consistent with the age of the local Galactic Disk. Several groups are trying to find even cooler and older white dwarfs - to confirm the age of the disk, and investigate the ages of older Galactic components.
Cool white dwarfs have recently been found in the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS). Kilic et al. (2006) use the SDSS and USNO databases to identify cool white dwarfs using a reduced proper motion (PM) diagram. The reduced PM is defined by: H = mag +5log(PM "/yr) + 5. Here the apparent magnitude and PM are used as a proxy for absolute magnitude for a sample with similar kinematics. Figure 1 shows how faint white dwarfs with significant PM can be separated from stars, subdwarfs and quasars. Kilic et al. have spectroscopically confirmed several white dwarfs this way, including seven with Teff around 4000K. Hall et al. (2008) have also identified a possible 11 Gr-old halo white dwarf in the SDSS by its proper motion. SDSS white dwarfs have also been identified by their colors. Low-temperature hydrogen-rich white dwarf atmospheres are at high pressures, and show strong pressure-induced molecular hydrogen (H2) opacity. This opacity has a broad absorption feature around 2um, which affects the H and K near-infrared bands. When Teff decreases below 4000K, the opacity can also impact the optical colors. Gates et al. (2004) and Harris et al. (2001, 2008) used this to identify and confirm 13 extremely cool white dwarfs by their unusual SDSS colors. Figure 2 shows the location of some of the known ultracool white dwarfs in color-color plots.
Analysis of dwarfs with such cold and high-pressure atmospheres is difficult (e.g. Bergeron & Leggett 2002) but it is clear that there are now a handful of objects known with Teff<4000K and ages 9-12 Gyr (and new opacities for these cool high-pressure atmospheres are being calculated). Our group is searching for cool white dwarfs by combining the SDSS and USNO databases with the UKIRT near-infrared sky survey (UKIDSS, Lawrence et al. 2007), which provides photometry in the YJHK filters, 1.0 to 2.5um. These databases allow us to determine proper motion, as well as optical and near-infrared colors. Our use of three databases allows us to go >~1 magnitude fainter in g than the Kilic et al. sample and also allows us to select for hydrogen-rich dwarfs. Our selection criteria require (1) high proper motion such that the candidates fall in the appropriate area of the reduced PM diagram (2) red gri colors implying low Teff and (3) blue JH colors implying the presence of H2 opacity.
10 hrs of 07B Gemini Christmas Director's time allowed us to followup an initial search of 340 sq. deg. of the Large Area Survey (LAS, Warren et al. 2007) component of the UKIDSS Data Release (DR) 2. All candidates were confirmed to be new white dwarfs, however they were not particularly cool, having Teff = 5500 - 6700K, and so ages of 2 - 5 Gyr (Lodieu et al. 2009). Figure 3 shows the model fits to the photometry and GMOS H-alpha line for one of these dwarfs, demonstrating the high quality both of the data and the model atmosphere analysis. It can be seen that the presence of Halpha rules out a helium-rich composition, and implies an age ~3 Gyr. We refined our search and used the DR3 release of 900 sq. deg. to followup 8 objects in 17 hours of 08B time. Figure 2 shows how we selected for cooler objects in 08B based on g-r color. Reduction of that data is ongoing; preliminary results for 4 objects suggest that one is a 4000K 10 Gyr-old white dwarf, one is a 5000K 5 Gyr-old white dwarf and the other two are cool subdwarfs. Based on their colors, we expect the remaining four to consist of two 4000K and two 5000K white dwarfs (Figure 2).
1200 sq. deg. of sky are now available in DR5. We have identified seven more candidate 4000K white dwarfs all of which are accessible in 10A. Their colors (Figure 2) and their location in the RPM diagram indicate that these are all extremely likely to be 4000K 10 Gyr-old white dwarfs. Hence with these data and the 08B results we expect to add ~10 such objects to the very small known sample of 20. We will also have established selection criteria which the community can use in ongoing and future surveys to identify the elusive population of cold hydrogen-rich degenerate remnants of the disk and halo stellar populations.

The targets were selected from the USNO, SDSS and UKIDSS databases to have: faint RPM magnitudes of Hg>20.5 (cf. Figure 1, this implies both faint magnitudes and high proper motion), and r_AB<20.7 for observing feasability. Detection at J and H was required and color cuts were applied to select for cool H-rich white dwarfs (cf. Figure 2): 0.8<g-r<1.6, 0.2<r-i<0.6, 0.6<i-J<1.4, J-H<0.2. We also searched for objects that were bluer in the optical but were significantly blue in J-H, to identify those very cold or very high pressure dwarfs with CIA H2 opacity in the optical. One such object was found (Figure 2); it is the bluest 10A target in J-H and also the has the faintest reduced PM. The candidates have been checked against published lists of white dwarfs and subdwarfs and have not previously been published (one recovered known cool white dwarf was removed from the sample). The images of the candidates have also been checked to ensure a robust identification (two close double systems were removed from the sample). We have also confirmed that none of these objects are in the Gemini archive.
We will use GMOS with the R400 grating, the 0.75" slit, 2x2 binning and a central wavelength of 700nm. We have requested GMOS-S time as the targets are equatorial and the North is usually heavily oversubscribed at the target RAs. However the TAC may move us to the North if they wish. The GMOS-S ITC was used to calculate exposure times and S/N for our targets, which have r_AB=18.7-20.1. Overheads were estimated at 16 minutes setup and 2 minutes per exposure, as given in the instrument web pages. Total observation times of 0.9 to 2.6 hours in IQ70 SB50 CC70 WVany provides S/N of 15 to 30 across the 525-875 nm spectrum. This S/N and the resolution of R~1300 is necessary and sufficient to (1) rule out any non-white dwarf contaminants (e.g. subdwarfs, see Kilic et al. 2006) and (2) detect any weak Halpha present (e.g. Figure 3). If band 3 time is awarded we will relax the image quality to IQ85 and obtain S/N~10-20. This will still allow confirmation of the white dwarfs although modelling any weak hydrogen lines will be compromised.

One century after the discovery of strong emission lines in the center of NGC1068, galactic nuclei are still mysterious places. The enormous energy output detected in many galactic nuclei is one of the key issues in the study of galaxies and their evolution, several fundamental questions remaining unsolved. Is accretion onto super-massive black holes (SMBH) just a co-evolving phenomenon or a necessary partner of the circumnuclear star formation? What is the relationship of the fueling mechanisms to galaxy evolution? What astrophysics sets the mass ratio of the gas turned into stars compared to the gas accreted by the SMBH at the observed value of ~1000? Once in the galaxy, how is gas transported from the bulge scale to the SMBH's accretion disk? We will focus in addressing the last two questions studying the best resolved AGN.
From the observational point of view, disentangling the kinematical components of galaxies is a major puzzle. Developed stages of nuclear fueling at galactic centers do not provide sufficient clues to their origin, since the morphological signatures of the triggering mechanism are smeared out on the timescale of a few orbital revolutions of the galaxy core. In particular at some active galaxies, off-axis kinematical centers and outflows are not uncommon due to minor mergers, strong barred gravitational potentials and AGN feedback. Representatives of this peculiarity are NGC3227 (Arribas & Mediavilla 1994), NGC1068 (Arribas+,1996), NGC1672 (Diaz+,1999) and M83 (Mast+,2006), among many others. In M83 the investigation of the peculiar kinematics of the central regions, led to the detection of an obscured secondary nucleus (Diaz+,2006).
Cen-A is the nearest active galaxy and the nearest evolved major merger (an elliptical galaxy with a large disk inside). It provides an unique opportunity to investigate observationally the details of the complex kinematics and dynamical evolution of these objects. The importance of measuring CenA's SMBH mass becomes evident if we consider the two present-day modes of black-hole activity: i) one associated with Seyfert galaxies and QSOs -the SMBH radiates strongly, belongs to the lower mass kind (<1E8 Msun), lives in the lower mass galaxies (<1E11 Msun), and is statistically associated with star formation; ii) the second is associated with radio galaxies -the accretion is radiatively inefficient, the mass of the SMBH is very large (>1E8), it resides in elliptical galaxies, and there is little circumnuclear star formation. The nearest active system seems not to clearly fit within any of these families, due to the transition morphology of the host NGC5128 and the apparently low mass of the SMBH. Although emission from a dusty torus around the central radio source was found by Radomski+ (2008), the MIR circumnuclear emission is coincident with the Pa_alpha knots, implying that a star-fomation disk is also present down to a few arcseconds radius (Alexander+,1999). Furthermore, Marconi+(2001) suggest that the H_2 structure shows kinematical evidence consistent with a nuclear bar fueling the AGN. The nucleus has been observed in the NIR by various teams, at low and moderate spectral resolution. The derived values for the SMBH mass have shown a decreasing trend in time: 2.0E8 (Marconi+,2001, ISAAC@VLT, R~9000, H&K-bands); 2.4-1.5E8 (Silge+,2005, GNIRS@Gemini-S, R~1600, K-band); 10-6.7E7 (Marconi+,2006, STIS@HST, R~1000, I-band); 6.1E7 (Haring+,2006, NAOS-CONICA@VLT, R~1500, H-band); 4.5E7 (Neumayer+,2007, SINFONI@VLT, R~4000, K-band). The observation of the innermost gas motion will be the clue towards converging to a definite value for the SMBH mass. The gas motions are extremely complex, as noted in the studies above. A key element towards the determination of the SMBH mass is the ability to discriminate between kinematical components close to the core. Currently the claimed rotating disk at Cen-A's core has major axis closely align with the outflow axis. Therefore any mass determination with medium resolution spectroscopy of the gaseous component seems still unreliable (see Figure 1 below, Neumayer+,2007). We aim to answer whether the gas kinematics are consistent with one or more rotating disks. The technique to achieve this is high spectral resolution. Phoenix at Gemini-S provides an unique opportunity (which might be the last since the instrument is to be removed in 2011), due to its high spectral resolution, perfectly coupled to the light gathering power and IR capabilities of the Gemini 8m telescopes.
Resolving the central kinematics would solve the gaseous disk rotation-orbit anisotropy-outflow degeneracy and greatly improve the knowledge about CenA. The Phoenix data will also allow us to apply state of the art numerical modeling to constrain the core growth and SMBH formation in one of the nearest 'elliptical' galaxies. We have already been successful in studying the dynamics of peculiar galactic nuclei and star forming regions from Gemini NIR imaging (Diaz+,2004, Dottori+,2005) and NIR 3D spectroscopy (Diaz+,2006, Blum+,2009). We are also experienced in the proposed use of long slit sequential mapping (Diaz+,1999; Winge+,1999), state of the art semi-analytical modeling (Gimeno 2007) and n-body numerical modeling (Diaz+,2000, Rodrigues, Dottori, Diaz+2009).

Dust obscuration poses serious constraints for accurate description of the kinematics via optical emission lines specially in the central regions of merging galaxies. NIR observing must be employed to accurately describe the detailed kinematics in these regions. As emphasized in the science case, until now observations of the kinematics of NGC5128 have been done with unsufficient spectral resolution, and the innermost detailed kinematics in the central region remains unresolved. The observation will we done in two central wavelenghts in order to probe the behaviour of different gas species.
Using the Phoenix ITC with the photometric information of NGC5128 (Kmag=10.9, Watson+1996,AJ112,534). With 0".085~1.19pc and 1.46 km/s pixels, resolution R=50000 and S/N~15 (at the continuum level), we expect to map the Pa_beta at 1.2818um and H_2(1-0)_S(1) at 2.1212um line emission (at expected S/N>50/pixel) with an average kinematical uncertainty <1km/s. Fig.1 shows the slit arrangement over a HST K image, with the Pa_alpha contours. The orientation of the slits was chosen to match the most plausible kinematical axis. The kinematic components at the inner 1".25 will be fully mapped achieving unprecedented level of detail of the central kinematics of this galaxy. Another two positions are set along the radio jet position angle and perpendicular to it, respectively. The Pa_beta setting will probe the innermost gas kinematics, crucial for the determination of the SMBH mass, and with the Phoenix kinematical resolution we expect to effectively resolve rotational from nonrotational motion. The other setting, centered on the H_2(1-0)_S(1) emission line, will aim to map the molecular gas kinematics and constrain the existence and strength of a possible barlike structure.
Sky subtraction will be done with sky exposures taken at 150" distance from the base position (well outside the galaxy body), with the PWFS2 set to 'freeze'
The exposure times were computed with Phoenix ITC for continuum S/N~15/pixel which is sufficient for our purposes. All observations will be performed with the 0".25 slit, allowing proper Nyquist sampling of a 0".5 seeing disk (perpendicular to the slit).

These will be some of the first observations of the structure of a galaxy nucleus done with Phoenix, and, as stated above, we expect to achieve the best kinematics measurement to date from a NIR observation for this nucleus. The observation of the inermost gas motion will be critical to converging to a definite value of the central black hole mass.

The HR8799 planetary system discovery (Marois et al. 2008 and Fig. 1) is a significant achievement in the search and study of planets orbiting other stars. While this system brings the first concrete pieces of evidence to the puzzle, many more planets like these need to be found to develop a clear understanding of their formation mechanism and their atmosphere physics.
With currently available instruments, the direct exoplanet imaging technique can find massive planets (> 1 MJup) at separations > 10 AU around stars. The formation mechanism of such distant planets is still debated. Models of planet formation by core accretion seem to be unable to form massive planets at more than a few tens of AU (Dodson-Robinson et al. 2009). The gravitational instability model is currently believed to be able to form massive planets at wide separations more easily, but this process should also result in the formation of browns dwarfs and low mass stars companions (Kratter et al. 2009). Performing dedicated planet surveys that are sensitive to planets/brown dwarfs in wide orbits is thus necessary to constrain the wide orbit planet formation scenario.
The frequency of planets in orbit >2.5 AU around stars is still poorly constrained due to the long orbital periods that limit their detection by radial velocity surveys; direct imaging surveys thus nicely complement radial velocity searches. First generation AO surveys at Gemini (Lafreniere et al. 2007, GDPS 86 GKM stars) and at VLT (Biller et al. 2007, 45 GKM stars and Chauvin et al. 2009, 88 GKM stars), have started constraining the population of wide planets around stars, but have focus mainly on Sun-Like and low-mass stars (only including ~20 AF stars), leaving the planet frequency around massive stars unknown (see Nielsen and Close 2009 for an overview of Sun-like/low mass star statistics). Johnson et al. 2007ab found several massive planets by radial velocity < 2.5 AU around evolved A-stars; they derived a frequency of 9% for >1 MJup planets and < 2.5 AU, this is a factor of 2 higher than for G-stars and a factor of 5 higher than for M-stars (Fig. 2). To compensate for the low stellar mass bias of the first generation imaging surveys, our team has initiated in 2007B the first exoplanet survey targeted at massive stars. Up to now, we have acquired 78 young and close (40 pc) A- and F-type stars at Gemini, Keck and VLT. We are currently finalizing the follow-up candidate confirmations.
A preliminary Monte Carlo/Bayesian analysis of our massive star AO surveys results ?which up to now include 78 A- and F-type stars- indicates that no more than 10% of AF stars have a companion of mass 3-12 MJup between 10-300 AU (Fig. 3). Our statistics are currently not sufficient to estimate if the RV planet frequency is the same at < 2.5 AU than at >10 AU, more stars need to be acquired. To lower our planet frequency upper limit to 5% for massive stars and bring it to the same level as that of the late-type stars (see Fig. 2), we need to acquire 50 new AF stars. From simple binomial statistics, our current planet detection rate of ~1.3% (1/78) for planets >10AU around massive stars suggests that observation of these new 50 stars have a ~50% chance of finding at least one new planetary system.
Using NICI, we propose to acquire 21 new AF stars in 2010A. Each target sequence will last 2h and will be acquired simultaneously in the 6% CH4 on/off bands (SSDI imaging, see technical section for expected detection limits). Proposals have also been sent to Keck and VLT to acquire a total of 50 stars for 2010A. Accounting for the 20 AF stars already observed by other surveys, the total number of AF stars observed at the end of this program will be 148 (comparable to the number of stars acquired by late-type star surveys). Small proposals will be submitted in 2010B and 2011A for follow-ups. Note that we are keeping track of all observations made at each telescope to ensure that no observation is duplicated.
All new stars have been selected for they proximity and from several youth indicators. We need to observe young systems (~100 Myr or less) since planets cool with time, making then harder/impossible to detect in older systems with current instruments. The new star sample was selected mainly based on the stars? locations on a B-V versus Mv diagram using high quality astrometric data. While age determinations are notoriously difficult for isolated stars, the evolution away from the Zero-Age Main Sequence for A stars allows a reliable estimate of their ages.
We stress the fact that this survey is fully complementary to the NICI campaign (our stars are not on their list), thus both surveys can be analyzed as a single one after the data become public). The large field-of-view of our survey (10-300 AU around stars) will also nicely complement the upcoming much smaller field (< 80AU) of the Gemini Planet Imager (GPI) campaign, allowing the study planet formation scenarios on a wider scale. The HR 8799 planets, Fomalhaut b (Kalas et al. 2008) and 1RSX J160929.1-210524 b (Lafreniere et al. 2008) are good examples that planets do exist in wide orbits. The data that will be acquired during this program will serve as a continued resource to the exoplanet research community.

Our experience in high contrast AO-imaging has shown that faint companion detection in the neighborhood of a bright star is limited by quasi-static speckles in the point spread function (PSF) arising from slowly evolving optical aberrations (Marois et al. 2003, 2005). The variance of these speckles introduces a noise that masks the signal of any companion. Once the static PSF structure noise is above the sky and random atmospheric residual speckle noises, little gain is made by longer integration time as the structural noise increases roughly at the same rate as the signal. One way to eliminate the quasi-static speckle noise is to subtract a reference star PSF, but this technique is severely limited by important aberration evolution (due to telescope and instrument flexures, active control, seeing variations) between observation of the target and the reference star (Marois et al. 2005).
To achieve high contrast, we will use NICI and benefit from both the ADI technique and the simultaneous spectral differential imaging (SSDI) method to subtract the star PSF. ADI consists of acquiring a sequence of many ~10-second exposures of the target while keeping the instrument rotator off. This configuration ensures that the camera and telescope optics remain aligned for all exposures, enabling a very good PSF correlation between consecutive exposures. Since the field rotates when the instrument rotator is off, any companion moves angularly with time. For each image in the sequence, a combination of exposures obtained close in time can be used to construct a reference PSF to subtract the PSF structure, sky, dark and ghost artifacts, while leaving intact the signal of the companion. The sequence of residual images are then rotated and co-added to add up the planet signal. The ADI technique, described in detail in Marois et al. (2006), is well proven and yields one of the best high-contrast imaging performance on 8m telescopes (see Fig. 4 for a qualitative comparison).
For each star, we intend to obtain a 2h sequence of mostly 10s 6% CH4 on/off-band exposure images within +/- 60min from transit to obtain an average ~0.4 degree/minute FOV rotation or ~50 degrees total FOV rotation in 2h. To adequately build an ADI reference PSF that does not significantly subtract companion point sources, a minimal 1 lambda/D PSF motion is necessary during the total image sequence. For ~50 degrees FOV rotation and CH4-short images (lambda/D = 41 mas), ADI will thus be useful down to ~0.1 arcsec angular separation. Unsaturated images will be acquired outside the focal plane mask for several objects to properly calibrate the semi-transparent focal plane mask. We expect to reach ~13 magnitudes contrast >1 arcsec for a 1h sequence (including overheads - see Fig. 4). For a 50 Myr A-type star at 40pc, this sensitivity limit corresponds to exoplanets of ~4 Jupiter mass (700K) at 40 AU following the Baraffe et al. 2003 COND03 models. ADI thus brings high-contrast imaging well into the exoplanet regime at small angular offsets. We are asking for more time for earlier type stars (vs our previous GKM GDPS survey) to partially compensate for their bright luminosity compared to lower mass stars (this is lowering our sensitivity to lower mass planets) and for their greater distance.
All interesting detections will be followed by proper motion the following year to confirm companionship (the average proper motion is ~0.1 arcsec/year). All second epoch observations are carefully timed to insure a ~5 sigma detection of the candidate, thus minimizing the amount of telescope time needed for a confirmation. The survey analysis and Monte Carlo simulations will be published as soon as all observations, including follow-ups, are acquired.

Adaptive optics opens a new parameter space for binary star searches not probed by radial velocity (RV) or light-curve studies. This proposal continues my successful 2009A program to measure the incidence of close companions around Be stars and characterize their spectral types and orbits. Binarity is a leading contender for explaining the origins and behavior of classical Be-stars, a unique and fascinating class that exhibit dynamic circumstellar disks and extreme rotation.
As of Sept 29th, 2009 my Gemini Altair+NIRI program has observed 8 nearby Be stars, finding close companions to 4 of them. The binaries have angular separations ranging from 0.13"-0.83", corresponding to physical sizes 19-78 AU. For the tightest binary, assuming low inclination and a circular orbit, the predicted orbital period is of order 20 years. Thus follow-up imaging over the next year or so will be able to astrometrically confirm orbital motion. This proposal is to complete the sample of spectral types and obtain follow-up spectra to characterize the companions.
Be stars are O or B type main-sequence (dwarf-to-subgiant) stars exhibiting balmer lines in emission, accompanied by a strong infrared excess. Extensive spectral studies have shown that Be-stars possess optically thin circumstellar gas disks in their equatorial plane. The rotating disk gives rise to double peaked emission lines via the doppler effect. Line structure frequently evolves on timescales of weeks-to-years, reflecting changes in the density distribution of the disk.
There are 3 leading theories for Be-star equatorial disk formation:
(1) Porter (1996) showed that all Be stars are (and normal B stars are not) rotating at or close to their break-up velocities, thus matter could easily flow from the stellar envelope into the equatorial plane.
(2) Quasi-periodic oscillations have frequently been observed in Be stars, and these have been suggested as a mechanism for coupling the stars' spin (angular momentum) to the outflow.
(3) Companions have been suggested to stimulate disk-formation by lowering the effective gravity at the Be-star surface sufficiently for matter to spill off. Binary evolution can also be invoked to spin-up the Be stars.
In isolation, the above scenarios are insufficient to cause organized acceleration of an equatorial outflow. The evolutionary path leading to such extreme stellar-spin is also not understood. An important clue lies in the spectral-type distribution of classical Be stars (i.e. the isolated variety) which is uniform, and those in high mass X-ray binaries (HMXB) which cluster strongly around spectral type B0 (Negueruela 1998). The presence of the neutron-star companion in HMXB has been shown to affect both the size and density of the disk (e.g. Zamanov 2001).
Be star disks are very dynamic on timescales of months to years, sometimes exhibiting quasi-periodic fluctuations in H-alpha flux and line profile. Occasionaly the disk dissipates and later re-forms. Monitoring of spectral line-profiles reveals long-lived density perturbations that precess, giving rise to the quasi-periodic behavior (e.g. Clark 2001). However the perturbing entity has yet to be identified. In HMXB the neutron star exerts a tidal influence on the circumstellar disk (Okazaki & Negueruela 2001), leading to strings of X-ray outbursts correlated with the binary period (For extensive examples see Galache et al 2008). The tidal interaction would also be present in the "isolated" Be stars if faint companions are present, and is plausibly the driver of quasi-periodic disk behavior. This can be tested by estimating orbital periods from the binary separations and comparing against the disk quasi-periods.
There is compelling observational evidence for binarity in classical Be-stars: Carrier et al (2002) conducted spectroscopic (RV monitoring) of 4 Be stars selected for their periodic photometric variations, finding two spectroscopic binaries. The period of one of these binaries (398d) closely matched its photometric period. No companions were found for the other 2 stars (one of which was found to exhibit non-radial pulsations). Companions to a few Be-stars are known at much larger separations (for example the famous double-star Albireo). With AO we can search the parameter space not explored by natural imaging and RV studies.
VLT/AO observations by Kervella et al (2008) have found a companion to the closest Be star "Achernar". The separation is 0.15" (6.7 AU at D=44pc) and the orbital period is about 15 years, similar to the quasi-periodicity of the circumstellar disk. The spectrum of Achernar-B shows an A1V-A3V star. The two stars differ in brightness by 3.5 mag. The 4 companions found so far with Gemini are also 2-4 magnitudes fainter than their Be 'siblings'
This proposal is designed to sample the closest representatives of each Be spectral type and luminosity class. To control systematics, a volume-limited sample of Be stars is listed in Table 1. These very bright stars have been extensively studied spectroscopically and in the time domain, so that the quasi-periodic behavior of the circumstellar disks is well characterized. Stellar non-radial pulsations do not confuse the picture because they are seen in spectral lines originating on the star's surface, while the disk emits free-free emission from optically thin plasma.
The sample was constructed from the Be-star catalog of Jaseck 1982 (in Vizier), selecting northern (Dec>0) Be-stars with measured rotational velocities and no known (visual or spectroscopic) binary companion. From this list we have identified the nearest exemplars. Our full target list (Table 1) contains 52 Be-stars closer than 1 kpc, and includes all nearby "isolated'' Be-stars across the range of spectral types. Most are brighter than V=7 permitting optimum AO performance in NGS mode.
The closest Be star in the sample has spectral type B6V, and V=4.1, for which we estimate D=66pc, a projected separation of 0.1" at this distance corresponds to a physical separation of 6.5AU, it also the fastest rotator in the sample. The brightest star in the sample is a B6III, V=3.62, the physical scale for this object at 0.1" is of order 10 AU. The brightest early-type is B1V with V=4.6, D=398pc, so that 0.1"=40 AU. Using spectral type B8V to represent the lowest luminosity members of the class, we find a distance of 200pc for V=6, at this distance the projected seperation of 0.1" = 20 AU.
Wider Significance:
The majority of Neutron-star High Mass X-ray Binaries (HMXBs) have a Be star as the mass donor. The circumstellar disk is the fuel-reservoir for the accretion powered X-ray outbursts. Be-systems make up 70% of Milky Way HMXBs and 49-of-50 in the Small Magellanic Cloud. The origin and evolution of Be stars is a critical missing-link in explaining the activity cycles and lifetimes of X-ray binaries; in turn the X-ray luminosity function (XLF) of star-forming galaxies is dominated by HMXBs. Thus discovering the role of binarity in making Be stars will improve our quantitative understanding of the relationship between SFR and XLF.
