The requirement for companion detection is a delivered PSF with core FWHM<0.1". Gemini North with NIRI/Altair operating in Natural Guide Star (NGS) mode at f/32 routinely delivers images of this quality in IQ70/CC70 conditions. Experience suggests stable seeing, a clear sky, low wind-speeds and good airmass (<1.5) are needed. For the extremely bright stars (V=4-6) in my sample, CC90 has proven workable. This is an ideal filler program for the queue, and fully exploits the capabilities of Altair.
Detectability of a companion to a bright star is a function of separation, brightness difference and AO-system contrast. The Be stars in this proposal are very bright (V=4-8) and will be used as the on-axis AOWFS guidestar. The field-lens used with the f/32 camera provides full AO correction over the field, giving a search radius of up-to 11 arcsec. The probability of random interlopers within a few arcseconds is extremely low for the magnitude range being studied.
In the 5 binaries found so far, the angular seperations are 0.13"-0.8" and the brightness differences are 2-3.5 mag in the near IR. We are interested in companions at seperations ranging from <0.1" up to the full f/32 field of view. The CR will be fixed, and field rotation will enable some of the static speckles to be processed out. Observations at transit are not required, field rotation is just a bonus if it occurs.
Images will be taken in the J-cont, H-cont, K-cont filters to suppress the light of the Be star which would otherwise saturate the entire array (some of our stars are 4th magnitude). Photometry relative to the Be star is possible due to the very short exposures used to obtain unsaturated images.
The use of narrow band filters and short exposure time prevents the Be star saturating, providing a clean PSF which will enable a search for very close companions. Total integration for each star will be ~1 minute in each filter 5 dither positions x 20 exposures of 0.5 seconds). We assume a generous 15 min of overhead per target including acquisition time, giving a total time on the sky of about 20 minutes per target.
Spectral classification of binary companions will be performed using NIRI+Altair grism spectroscopy. High S/N (>>100) spectra of the magnitude 7-9 companions are obtained in about 1 minute through J, H and K grisms.
There are 52 Be stars in our target-table, all northern, and covering a wide range in RA, so good airmass targets will be available throughout the semester. Up-to half will be observed in the current 2009B band-3 program
In the requested 8 hours I aim to complete first-epoch imaging of the sample and obtain spectra of all binary companions discovered. Second epoch (>6 month) imaging will also be performed when possible, for binaries discovered in 2009B.

GD362 (WD1729+371) is a metal-rich white dwarf (WD) displaying excess emission in the near-IR (NIR) and mid-IR (MIR) wavelengths (Kilic et al. 2005; Becklin et al. 2005). This excess emission is caused by a cool dust disk with T~600K that lies within the Roche radius of the WD. GD362 was the second WD that was found to have a circumstellar dust disk. The first, G29-38, was identified over 18 years ago (Zuckerman & Becklin 1987). These dust disks likely result from the tidal disruption of asteroids or even Mars-size bodies that have strayed too close to the WD (Zuckerman et al. 2003; Jura 2003; Jura et al. 2009). This is supported by Spitzer MIR spectroscopy, which shows that the dust disks surrounding GD362 and G29-38 are dominated by silicates and carbonites with similar abundances to asteroids in the solar system (Reach et al. 2005). This suggests that G29-38 and GD362 host the remains of complex planetary systems, including giant planets that can perturb asteroids and terrestrial bodies into orbits that take them within the Roche radius of the WD (Debes & Sigurdsson 2002).
It is likely that many planetary systems will survive post-main sequence evolution and persist after the star has become a WD. Burleigh, Clarke & Hodgkin (2002) presented detailed arguments supporting such a scenario and pointed out that the orbits of any outer planets (initially located a few AU from the star) will widen significantly. Combined with the huge gain in contrast between the star and planet offered by observing WDs (factors of up to ~10,000 compared to a main sequence star), WDs are obvious targets for imaging searches for massive planets. Burleigh, Clarke & Hodgkin demonstrated that planets with masses of a few Jupiter masses could be detected around many nearby WDs through deep NIR imaging with 8m telescopes. The discovery of such a companion would allow the spectroscopic investigation of substellar objects much cooler (<500K) and older (>few x10^8 yrs) than previously found and would help provide constraints on models for the evolution of planets and planetary systems during the final stages of stellar evolution. Also, the age of any planetary mass companions discovered in such a system can be estimated using the WD cooling age and the mass and lifetime of the main sequence progenitor, providing a benchmark with which to test evolutionary and atmospheric models. Indeed, Mullally et al. (2008) recently presented strong evidence for the existence of a ~2 Jupiter mass planet with an orbital radius of ~2.4AU around a DAV WD (GD66) from the periodic variation in the precise timing measurements of the star's extremely stable non-radial pulsations. This object must have survived the red giant phase of stellar evolution.
In 2002 we embarked on a long term programme - the Degenerate Objects around Degenerate Objects (DODO) survey - to obtain deep NIR images of 40 nearby (<20pc), young (<3Gyr), high proper motion (>200mas/yr) WDs with the Gemini and VLT telescopes to search for substellar and planetary mass companions in wide orbits. Any companions should share the WDs motion and second epoch observations were obtained ~1-3 years later to verify any faint candidate companions. We have now completed our analysis of these data (Burleigh et al. 2008; Hogan, Burleigh & Clarke 2009) and we tentatively suggest that <~5% of WDs have substellar companions with effective temperatures >~500K between projected physical separations of 60-200AU. Our original sample included the first WD with a dust disk, G29-38, and we can report with a 90% probability that this WD has no resolved companions more massive than ~7 Jupiter masses between a projected physical separation of ~40-400AU.
In 2006A we were awarded additional time to search for common proper motion companions to the recently discovered second WD with a dust disk (GD362) in the same manner as the 40 WDs in our original sample. The presence of the dust disk and the strong implication for the existence of a remnant planetary system makes this an exceptional, one-off additional target to our programme. For GD362 (d~50pc, total age i.e., WD cooling age plus main sequence lifetime, ~2.7Gyr), we predict that with our standard one hour J band imaging with NIRI, we will be sensitive to companions 12 times the mass of Jupiter. The first epoch image of GD362 was obtained in May 2006. We now request a second epoch image to determine whether any common proper motion companions are present.
We also request a third epoch of an original DODO survey target star, WD1633+433. The second epoch image of this WD was degraded by a large streak across the image, which was not present in the first epoch image (Hogan et al. 2009). This has introduced a large scatter in the measured motions of the point sources in the field. As a result, multiple objects appear to have motions similar to the motion of the WD. Therefore, a third epoch image is required to determine if any of these objects are genuine common proper motion companions.

We will use NIRI to obtain deep J band images of the nearby WDs GD362 and WD1633+433 to search for common proper motion substellar and planetary mass companions. The observing strategy described here is the same as that for the original observations of GD362 and the other DODO survey targets.
Choice of instrument, camera and filter:
Any companion that avoids direct contact with the red giant envelope during the evolution of a star-planet system will migrate outwards. For example, a companion originally in a Neptune-like orbit (~30AU) will migrate outwards up to ~180AU. At the distance of GD362 (~50pc), this corresponds to 3.5", resolvable in these observations. Debes & Sigurdsson (2002) have also pointed out that the orbits of outer planets in multi-planetary systems may become mutually unstable as mass is lost from the central star and that some objects may be thrown out into even wider, extremely long-period, eccentric orbits. Indeed, the GD362 system must have become unstable for a terrestrial body to have been injected into an orbit close to the WD to create the dust disk. Therefore, using NIRI combined with the f/6 camera is the optimal choice for our program and will provide a wide field of view (120") ideal for these observations. Despite the extremely red colours of planets, NIRI is most sensitive in the J band and this is the optimal band for these observations.
Integration times:
The targets will require a total integration time of 1 hour, which will be subdivided into a number of smaller exposures with the aim of achieving 50% FWD and avoiding saturation. From our previous extensive experience of deep J band imaging with NIRI (Hogan et al. 2009), rather than from the ITC, a 5-sigma limit of J~22.5mag for a 1 hour exposure can be achieved with the following observing conditions:
(1) 70%-ile image quality (0.55" at J); (2) 50%-ile cloud cover; (3) "any'" water vapour; (4) "any" sky background; (5) airmass < 1.2.
Note that scattered light from the WD does not significantly contribute to the background at separations much greater than 1". We will combine all our target observations to obtain a PSF model. This will be subtracted from the image to improve the sensitivity at small separations.
Justification of requested conditions:
To achieve sensitivity down to the planetary mass level, the completeness limit of the observations should be J~22.5 mag. Therefore, good seeing (0.55"; 70%-ile) is required to prevent faint objects from disappearing into the background. To avoid degrading the PSF, the targets can and should be observed at an airmass less than ~1.2. Additionally, to enable the detection of the faintest companions, a good transparency is required, i.e., no cloud cover (50%-ile). Water vapour does not significantly affect observations in the J band (any).
Time Requested:
We request a total of 95 minutes per target; 60 minutes on source plus 35 minutes for overheads (15 minutes acquisition plus 20 minutes readout, assuming a 75% efficiency factor). We also request queue scheduled observations to guarantee our required conditions are met. These observations are not suitable for Band 3.
Data analysis:
Data analysis will be undertaken in a collaboration between PI Hogan, Co-I Burleigh and Co-I Clarke. Our data analysis pipeline and techniques are now highly refined. Therefore, we expect to be able to rapidly analyse these observations shortly after the data are delivered.

Introduction: One of the primary results from the Infrared Astronomical Satellite All Sky Survey (Neugebauer et al., 1984) was the detection of a large population of luminous infrared galaxies (LIRGs) that emit strongly in the mid- to far-infrared (L_IR [8-1000um] >= 10^11 L_sun). These LIRGs are mostly observed to be gas-rich disk galaxies undergoing interactions or mergers; the dynamical interaction gives rise to prodigious star formation and, sometimes, AGN activity. Given the timescales of merger evolution (~ few x 10^8 yr), the determination of the properties of star formation and AGN as a function of merger state requires a statistically large sample of LIRGs. To this end, we have been undertaking a multi-wavelength campaign of a complete sample of LIRGs from the Revised Bright Galaxy Sample (f_60um > 5.25 Jy: Sanders et al., 2003). This "Great Observatories All-sky LIRGs Survey", or GOALS, consists of 203 LIRGs out to a redshift z~0.088, and makes use of observations with HST, the Spitzer Space Telescope, the Chandra X-ray Observatory, and GALEX.
The Need for GMOS Multi-Object Spectral Data: The focus of this proposal is a study of the properties of SSCs in GOALS LIRGs. The GOALS HST F435W and F140LP images reveal the presence of a large number of luminous (i.e., M_B < -7: see Figure 1). SSCs in both the nuclear regions and extended tidal tails (Vavilkin, in prep). The genesis of these clusters is likely tied to the collision of molecular gas clouds occurring as a result of galaxy passages in the merger process (Schweizer, 1987; e.g.). Thus, estimating the ages in different groups of SSCs will allow us to recreate the timeline of cluster creation and correlate formation events with different passages of the interacting galaxies.
We thus propose GEMINI GMOS-N observations of a sample of GOALS LIRGs known to be rich in luminous optical SSCs. The optical spectral coverage of GMOS-N will allow us to measure H_beta, H_gamma, and H_delta lines used by Schweizer and Seitzer (1998) to estimate the age of older clusters (T_cluster > 10 Myr). Younger clusters can be identified by Wolf-Rayet emission features in the spectra (Sidoli et al., 2006; Chien, 2008; see also fig. 2). We will also implement the Starburst99 model (Leitherer et al., 1999; Vazquez & Leitherer, 2005) as a comparison. The galaxies in our sample span the range of merger/interaction stages, thus allowing us to assess the properties of star clusters in mergers at all stages. With this data, we will:
- Measure the ages of individual star clusters, allowing (a) us to map the ages of clusters as a function of their location in each interacting systems and (b) as a function of the LIRG merger stage. Any spatial and merger stage dependence will help us constrain models of star formation in LIRGs.
- Search for faint circumnuclear star formation, AGN, and/or outflows in the nuclei. The sensitivity achieved by these observations will provide the best dataset for performing an optical search for these signatures.
- Measure the ages of the non-cluster "field" stellar population. This analysis will be difficult because of low surface brightness, but this data can be acquired for "free" through the placement of additional slits in the field where possible.
Such science goals cannot be met with the presently available data. Although age estimates for SSCs in the GOALS samples have been derived using HST 4-color photometry using Bruzual and Charlot (2003) synthesis models, modeled ages can be highly uncertain due effects of dust extinction. Optical Spectroscopy will allow us to derive much more precise SSC ages than possible with broad band photometric.
This proposal is submitted in conjunction with a parallel proposal to Gemini South, allowing us to obtain data on 5 different galaxies in different merger states. This data will be aggregated with 5 similar observations made on other GOALS galaxies (Chien, in press). A larger sample of galaxies and SSC spectra will provide an important complement to the extensive studies of nearby galaxies such as the Antennae (20 Mpc: Bastian, 2009), NGC 7252 (28.8 Mpc: Whitmore, et al 1993), and NGC3256 (36.1 Mpc: Trancho, 2007). Finally, a major advantage of observing with GMOS-N is the inauguration of LUCIFER on the LBT in 2010, which will provide NIR MOS abilities. We will use LUCIFER as part of a parallel NIR MOS study of SSCs in our sample galaxies.

We wish to use GMOS-N to obtain multi-object spectroscopy of super star clusters (SSCs) in a subset of the 203 GOALS objects selected with the constraint that HST optical (ACS/WFC F435W) and far-UV (ACS/SBC F140LP) imaging data is available to identify unobscured SSCs. From the reduced list of galaxies, we identified galaxies with large numbers of bright optical clusters accessible by Gemini North for Semester 2010A. From a list of ~10 galaxies, we identified 3 galaxies in different merger stages and with a SSC spatial distribution conducive to the MOS design (see fig. 1 in Scientific Justification): IIZw96, Arp148, and NGC5257. We already have HST F435W images with ACS, but wish to obtain 5 minute pre-imaging observations with GMOS-N through the G-filter to match the cluster astrometry already derived from the HST to the astrometry of GMOS-N during mask design. The G-filter in GMOS-N best matches the F435W filter from which we have determined cluster astrometry. The use of a custom multi-object mask will allow us to efficiently sample a large number of SSCs across both the nuclear region and the extended tidal regions, allowing us to determine the spatial dependency on the properties of the SSCs (see Scientific Justification) in a single set of observations. The FOV of GMOS-N covers the entire spatial extent of the galaxy interaction thus allowing us to use a single mask during a single set of observations. In order to detect the Balmer lines and Wolf-Rayet(see Scientific Justification), we will be using the B600 grating at a central wavelength of 450nm to increase the sensitivity in the blue end and to provide greater S/N than we would obtain using the higher resolution B1200 filter. Based on analysis of cluster photometry (Vavilkin, in prep), we find 38, 11, and 144 clusters for IIZw96, Arp148, and NGC5257, respectively, with a F435W magnitude m_F435W<24 with a distribution centered ~m_F435W=22. Due resolution necessary to resolve target SSCs, we are requesting IQ=70%, CC=50%, and SB=50% for our MOS observations with 1.0" slits in order to get the S/N required to achieve our science goals. Combining all these conditions into the Gemini ITC, we estimate a S/N of ~12 in the Balmer Absorption lines for 4 one-hour exposures using a m=22 B0V star as a proxy for the spectra of a SSC. Extended slit lengths will allow us to sample nearby galactic spectra to provide background subtraction. With stated overheads, each galaxy will take approximately 5.5 hours to complete. The use of an multi-object mask will also allow us to place additional slits for "free" in unsampled regions with m_F435W>24 SSCs and also in the background field of the galaxy at the cost of S/N and over the nuclei to study the presence of circumnuclear star formation, AGN, and/or outflows. The nuclei are much brighter than the individual SSCs we wish to study, so we expect to have excellent S/N in these areas.
The data will be reduced using the GMOS IRAF package provided by Gemini Observatory. The PI is a former data analyst at Gemini and two of the co-Is are currently part of the instrument team for GMOS at Gemini, so we are intimately familiar with GMOS data reduction. Line strengths will be measured using standard techniques. Since the GOALS team has already conducted a previous study of SSCs and two of the co-Is have extensive SSC analysis experience, we have the expertise necessary to reach our scientific goals. Stellar population models mentioned in the scientific justification will be used to determine the properties of the SSCs. The ages we derive from the GMOS observations will be used in comparison to the photometric ages derived from HST imaging (Vavilkin, in prep). All the data derived from this project will be added to the growing multi-wavelength imaging/spectral catalogs we have available as part of the GOALS sample to study the evolution and properties of SSCs in merging galaxies.

Hb 12 is a young planetary nebula with a bright core and an engraved hourglass nebula with a tight waist, akin to MyCn 18 (Bryce et al. 2004) and He 2-104 (Corradi et al. 2001) where very high speed, collimated outflows have been detected. The two latter objects are in the southern hemisphere whereas Hb 12 is a northern one. The nebular main axis is nearly N-S (PA ~10) with an apparent small tilt (<=15) with respect to the plane of the sky. Collimated, high velocity, projected, outflows are detected from optical lines emerging from the bright core at velocities of ~70 km/s and extending to >60" from the nucleus, reaching >170 km/s (Vaytet et al. 2009) . Ground-based deconvolved, 2.12 mu_m images reveal a complex structure in the nuclear regions and a rich, emission line environment in this nebula (Hora & Latter 1996). The inner lobes are dominated by UV-fluorescent, H_2 emission and shocked excited, [Fe II] polar caps have been detected close to the core (Welch et al. 1999). Recent HST NICMOS images reveal the inner hourglass contains a series of emission loops, each separated by ~3". At the distance to this nebula, this implies a time separation for each loop of ~50 years, given an inner expansion velocity of ~100 km/s (Kwok & Hsia 2007). Photometric and spectroscopic observations taken by Hsia et al. (2006) indicate the presence of a possible binary stellar core, suggesting a G-type companion, though there are doubts on these results and additional information is required to confirm it (De Marco, 2008).
We propose to obtain assisted AO integral field spectroscopy of Hb 12 using NIFS to investigate in detail the close environmental structure of Hb 12 with the aim of obtaining detailed information of the physical processes that occur in young PNe that develop complex structures and fast collimated, bipolar outflows as is the case in Hb 12. The core of Hb 12 is bright enough to act as a natural guide star for the AO system. Since the Fried parameter is a function of air mass (zenith angle), the northern location of Hb 12 (+57 degrees) should facilitate achieving observations with good image quality (high Strehl ratio). Three telescope pointings are requested, one on the core and two more, 3" and 6" N from it (Figure 1). On each pointing individual H and K spectra will be obtained. This strategy will yield 2D spectral maps on each pointing over the field of view of NIFS. Thus, the rich emission line spectrum of Hb 12 over these bands will track the changing physical conditions from the core to the northern lobe, including the emergence of the fast collimated outflow. In addition, the modest velocity resolution of NIFS in the proposed configuration (57 km/s) is enough to detect the Doppler shifts from the core to the lobe, information that will be paired with the changes in relative intensities of the spatially resolved emission line spectra (Figure 2). Image reconstruction from the 3D data cube at selected wavelengths, such as Br gamma, He I, H2, and [Fe II] will be performed to compare the rich, 2D morphology of the nebula (Figure 3) as a function of emission line and the rapidly changing physical conditions in the nebula. Wavelength dependent morphology and velocity information will be used to produce a 3D model of Hb 12. No comparable detailed studies are available on these kind of targets to our knowledge and the results from the present investigation are expected to serve as a reference point for future studies of similar phenomena. These observations may also serve to provide additional information on the putative binary companion presumably embedded in the nebular core, as claimed by Hsia et al. (2006).

We plan to observe the core of the nebula Hb 12 and two additional pointings, 3" and 6" N from the core, using the H and K gratings (JH and HK filters, respectively). The high spatial resolution capability of NIFS with Altair, nominally 0.1", will allow us to map in detail the rich and complex emission spectrum present in the central regions of Hb 12. In addition to line ratios and shifts derived from calibrated 1D extracted spectra, with NIFS we will produce from the 3D data cube, wavelength selected 2-D spectral maps for the most relevant emission lines. Considering the core is considerably brighter than regions outside of it, we computed separate exposure times for each pointing and in the HK and JH filters. Using spectral features taken from Hora & Latter (1996) we selected the brightest lines in the H and K band-passes for both the core and off-core positions, and computed the signal-to-noise (S/N) ratios for each line. These spectral lines are Br_gamma (2.17 mu_m) with S/N = 1046, on-core, in the HK filter, H_2 (2.12 mu_m) with S/N = 31, for both off-core positions, in the HK filter, Br 10 HI (1.74 mu_m) with S/N = 305, on-core, in the JH filter, [Fe II] (1.64 mu_m) with S/N = 58, for both off-core positions, in the JH filter. For the 6" N position, computed flux values were 80% of the line flux values used to compute the exposure for the 3" position. We assumed all lines had typical velocity widths of 25 km/s and were on top of a flat continuum flux density of 1.0x10E-16 erg/fd/lambda. Using the NIFS-ITC, we computed exposure times of 15 s for the on-core, HK pointing (3.14x10E-12 ergs/flux line flux), 135 s for the 3" N (3.41x10E-15 ergs/flux line flux), HK pointing, 160 s for the 6" N (2.78x10E-15 ergs/flux line flux), HK pointing, 50 s for the on-core (9.1374x10E-13 ergs/flux line flux), JH pointing, 400 s for the 3" N (5.81x10E-15 ergs/flux line flux), JH pointing and 540 s for the 6" N (4.648x10E-15 ergs/flux line flux), JH pointing. Thus the total, on-target exposure time is 300 s in HK and 990 s in JH. Using the NIFS-ITC, we found that observations of the bright nucleus won't saturate. Considering we are observing in the NIR, these exposure times are doubled to include sky-background observations. In addition, the NIFS documentation lists an over-head of 11 minutes for NIFS+Altair-NGS per target. Including an additional 3 minutes per target for arc lamp calibration observations, our total clock time is 80 minutes in the JH filter and 60 minutes in the HK filter. Thus, we request 2.5 hours of observations on Gemini-N with NIFS in queue observing mode.

1. Background
Over the past four years we have made great strides in pursuing the physics and progenitors of GRBs (particularly the short-duration bursts, t<2 sec), and in employing long GRBs as probes of the high-z universe, mainly for the study of interstellar medium enrichment at z~2-6. This work is enabled by accurate and rapid positions from the Swift satellite combined with intensive ground-based follow-up, largely from Gemini. Our group's previous programs at Gemini have yielded the best-characterized short GRB optical afterglows [BPC05,FFP05,SBK06], strong constraints on short GRB progenitor ages and energetics [BFP07], and detailed abundance measurements for GRB damped Ly-alpha systems (DLAs) [PSC07]. Most recently, we demonstrated the z>7 nature of GRB 090423, the most distant object known at z=8.26, using NIRI imaging (Fig. 1), which lead directly to the subsequent confirming spectroscopic observations from VLT [TFL09].
Here we propose a comprehensive program to address the most pressing questions in the study of short GRBs - environments, explosion physics, and possible ejection from galaxies - and to expand the use of GRBs as probes of galaxies and the IGM, out to the highest redshifts. The latter objective will be uniquely leveraged with our on-going Large Spitzer program, and supporting Keck/Magellan observations, to delineate the properties of GRB-DLA counterparts. These goals will benefit from our automated Gemini trigger, providing <15 minute response to GRB alerts.
2. GRBs as Probes of the High-Redshift Universe
Swift's combination of sensitivity, accuracy, and rapid alerts brought GRBs to the forefront of galaxy studies at high-z. Using Gemini in conjunction with Keck/Magellan we have obtained spectroscopy of over two dozen GRBs, allowing us to study their host ISM; Fig. 2. We have shown that GRBs probe dense and metal-enriched systems (neutral hydrogen~10^20-10^22 cm^-2 and metallicities~0.01-1 solar), thereby providing a complementary view of DLAs to that from quasars (which mostly probe the gas- and metal-deficient halos of intervening systems) [BPC06,PBF06,1,2]. The metal abundance patterns are indicative of dust depletion, and likely alpha-enhancement as expected for young starburst populations [PBF06,3,4]. GRB-DLAs are also uniquely marked by absorption from SiII and FeII fine-structure states [PBF06,4,5], likely excited by the bursts' UV radiation. The SiII lines can be studied even at low spectral resolution with GMOS, and provide a yardstick for the GRB-absorber separation. This is important for understanding whether the inferred ISM properties relate to the local GRB environment, or other line-of-sight absorbers within the host.
Equally important, GRB-DLAs offer the first opportunity to characterize the DLA counterpart population [BCC07,CBC07]. QSO-DLAs remain elusive due to the background glare of the quasar, but in GRB-DLAs the afterglow fades to obscurity within days. We are currently undertaking a 77-hour Spitzer program to determine the stellar masses, dust content, and obscured star formation in GRB-DLAs. Initial analysis reveals a substantial detection fraction (~30%), with typical rest-frame 1-micron luminosities of ~0.1L*. We are also actively obtaining Keck/Magellan rest-frame UV imaging and spectroscopy, and most detections reveal similar low luminosities and star formation rates of ~1 Msun/yr. Thus, our proposed Gemini rapid spectroscopy will continue to be leveraged with detailed follow-up to delineate for the first time the properties of DLA counterparts, and their relation to star formation.
As of 2009A, the potential of GRBs is now confirmed to extend beyond z>8. Our automated trigger will provides optical multiband imaging to locate bursts from the edge of reionization at z<7.2 through the Lyman break (afterglows are simple power laws so photo-z's can be easily established). The discovery and study of multiple z>6 GRBs promise four crucial ramifications. First and foremost, it will address cosmic re-ionization at currently inaccessible redshifts, allowing a precise measurement of the IGM neutral fraction through the Ly-alpha damping wing, as opposed to just the Gunn-Peterson optical depth from quasars. Second, it will help to measure z>6 star formation and its contribution to re-ionization. Third, it will shed light on the gas content of the first galaxies. Finally, it will pinpoint z>6 galaxies for subsequent follow-up. Admittedly, these highest-redshift GRBs are rare (three confirmed by spectroscopy beyond z=6; [6,7,BCC07]), but our automated strategy offers the best chance to catch such bursts, and follow-up spectroscopy of even one will be a watershed event.
3. The Progenitors of Short GRBs
The discovery of the first short GRB afterglows only two years ago established that they occur in elliptical and spiral galaxies and have no bright underlying supernovae [FFP05,BPC05,8,9]. These properties are consistent with the favored merger models (NS-NS, NS-BH), suggesting appreciable event rates for future gravitational wave detectors [NGF06,BFP07]. Recent observations by our group, predominantly from Gemini, show that at least 1/3 of all short GRBs occur at z~1, stretching their energy budget and requiring younger progenitor ages than initially expected; Fig.3 [BFP07,CBN08].
The key missing ingredient is an actual demonstration of merger-related physics and direct observations of the progenitors; for example, all current redshifts are from host galaxy associations (e.g. [BFP07]). Gravitational waves provide the cleanest test of binary mergers, but their detection awaits Advanced LIGO (a decade away). The next-best tests will come from spectroscopy of the progenitor environment, including the possible detection of the sub-relativistic nucleon-rich ejecta that is predicted to accompany the bursts [13], and a determination of whether some progenitors are ejected from their hosts, as predicted for NS-NS/NS-BH binaries [12]. Direct redshifts can be compared with nearby galaxies to test for progenitor ejection, and will also provide a measurement of the gas and metal properties in the burst environment (distinguishing a star-formation vs. old population origin). Detection of a thermal component will constrain the progenitor and energy extraction mechanism through the brightness and velocity of the sub-relativistic ejecta [13]. Since short GRB afterglows tend to be fainter than those of long GRBs, this program will also benefit from our rapid automated trigger.

The study of short GRB progenitors and the use of long GRBs as probes of the high-redshift universe rely on rapid imaging and spectroscopy response to GRB alerts. Gemini is ideal for this purpose given its large aperture, queue-scheduled operation, and choice of instruments. Our group can best leverage and support the unique advantages of Gemini through access to small and large telescopes in both hemispheres and over a wide range of longitudes (in particular, Las Campanas/Magellan, Palomar, Keck, HET, VLA, SSO). Over the last few semesters our Gemini program led to detailed studies of short GRB afterglows and their host galaxies, and ISM studies of DLAs at z>2 (see list of references and publications).
In addition, having reached the limits of what human-mediated triggers can achieve, we have implemented an automated trigger for use at Gemini. This script composes and submits a Phase 2 file within minutes of a burst's detection by Swift, allowing observations to commence within 15 minutes (including slew). It filters burst alerts based on duration to trigger the appropriate observations (long/short bursts) only when the burst is immediately accessible with Gemini and when it has an accurate position (<5 arcsec) from the Swift X-ray Telescope. For bursts that are not immediately observable (>30 minutes) but are still bright enough for follow-up several hours after discovery (see below for limits) we will use human-modified triggers.
This semester we expect a continued all-sky rate of about 10 GRBs/month from Swift, and one GRB/month from Fermi+LAT.
Our program requires two types of observations - imaging and spectroscopy. Imaging with GMOS is designed for identification of z>~6 GRBs through the Lyman break. GMOS imaging is also used to identify and study short GRB afterglows and their possible associated sub-relativistic ejecta. Spectroscopy is required for ISM and IGM studies (for all z>2), and for the first direct determination of short GRB redshifts and environments.
Our strategy for z>6 bursts is focused on making the crucial spectroscopic observations as soon as possible; although photometric techniques have proven useful in the past, the gains from this approach will be marginal from this point on. We therefore plan to implement a staged acquisition, using r- and z-band imaging with GMOS to distinguish garden-variety afterglows - needing only a short exposure for redshift determination, 42 min - from high-z events, which will require substantial integrations (3 hours) to yield data with cosmological significance. From experience in previous semester, automatic triggering will occur about 8 times in the semester, with one high-z event anticipated. THE TOTAL FOR THESE OBSERVATIONS IS 8.6 HOURS.
For the z>6 three-hour exposures we will use the highest resolution GMOS grating available to resolve the sky lines, using nod & shuffle mode for faint afterglows. These observations will provide S/N~5 per resolution element with GMOS for ~21 mag afterglows, a worst-case scenario given the rapid response.
Bursts at z<6 will be observed with the R400 grating to cover the widest wavelength range. These observations will provide ISM metallicity measurements at z~2-6; the lower redshift bound is determined by 1216x(1+z) Angstrom at the atmospheric cutoff. We will observe afterglows brighter than 20 mag to obtain S/N>10 with an observation of 1 hour (including overheads). Based on experience with Swift rates we expect 6 such bursts in 2008B. THE TOTAL FOR THESE OBSERVATIONS IS 6 HOURS.
Short GRB studies will consist of GMOS imaging to identify the afterglow or a thermal component from sub-relativistic ejecta, followed by spectroscopy (redshift, environment) if either is found to be brighter than ~21 mag (short GRB afterglows are generally fainter than long GRB afterglows). If an afterglow brighter than 21 mag is identified elsewhere (through our other resources for example), we will immediately pursue spectroscopy. The automated imaging sequence (griz to distinguish power law afterglow from thermal component) requires 1 hour. From current Swift detection rates we estimate about 3 short bursts in 2008B, of which 1 will require spectroscopy (2 hours including overheads with GMOS/R400). THE TOTAL FOR THESE OBSERVATIONS IS 5 HOURS.
The total time request is 19.3 hours. While this is an ambitious program, it is designed specifically to make use of Gemini's unique capabilities - rapid response and large aperture - and to address the most exciting open questions in GRB physics and applications. As stressed above, we are committed to support the Gemini observations with substantial allocations of time on other small and large telescopes, as well as multiple nights of follow-up on Magellan and Keck.
As a TOO program, our request is not suitable for Band 3.

We propose to continue our survey of Kuiper Belt Objects (KBOs) in search of volatile ices, using our custom photometric system, the first of its kind. The KBOs are of particular interest in astronomy because of their extreme distance and, consequently, their cold thermal environment. It is now known that primitive ices such as methane exist on KBO surfaces which would be easily volatilized in closer, warmer solar system populations such as the asteroids. The hope is that KBO ices will ultimately provide constraints on the physical state of chemicals in the nascent solar system environment shortly after the planet forming epoch, when planet accretion was arrested due to dynamical factors.
Near-infrared study is the key to identifying KBOs that have ices on their surface, since ices are nearly neutral in the visible, but show very strong transitions in the near-infrared regime. Only in the last few years have there been sufficient numbers of bright KBOs for near-infrared study: of the ~50 KBOs brighter than V<21, more than half were discovered in the past five years. Near-infrared spectra of the very brightest have confirmed that KBOs indeed have icy surfaces and seem to appear in three types: water ice, methane ice or neutral. The 5 brightest KBOs (plus Pluto and Charon) can be divided into either water ice dominated (Charon, 2003 EL61, Orcus, Quaoar [1-5]) or methane ice dominated (Pluto, 2005 FY9, 2003 UB313 [6-9]). A few other fainter bodies that have been studied show marginal water ice detections (1999 DE9), marginal methane detections (Sedna [10]) or relatively featureless spectra (1993 SC, 1996 TS66, and Huya [11]). In addition, strong water ice has been detected on 6 of the faint family members of 2003 EL61 [12-13]. Thus, of the ~35 KBOs that are bright enough for spectral study, 13 (roughly ~1/3) show evidence for some kind of volatiles.
Despite these detections, the vast majority of KBOs remain too faint for near-infrared spectral study. Photometric surveys can reach these fainter bodies because such surveys are more efficient in terms of telescope time compared to spectroscopic studies. Unfortunately, all near-infrared photometric surveys to date have used the JHK filter set which is optimized to avoid opacity in the Earth's atmosphere and bears only weak, serendipitous correlations with ices in the Kuiper Belt [14-15]. We propose to continue our near-infrared photometric survey using custom filters optimized to provide high signal-to-noise ratio compositional information of KBO surface ices. Because methane ice and water ice absorptions occur primarily in different regions of the near infrared, selection of an optimal filter set is fairly straightforward and appears in Figure 1. We have manufactured these filters with NASA funding, and they were installed and commissioned at Gemini North and the Magellan telescopes in late 2008B.
We have completed our on-sky proof-of concept and begun our full survey which includes unknown objects. Results from the proof-of-concept appear in Figure 2. We can discern the water, methane, and solar types with over a magnitude difference between them. This is a factor of ~10 improvement in sensitivity to ices compared to previous photometric works, which in some cases show only 0.1 magnitude difference between objects of different types. Our survey is a factor 3 more sensitive than spectroscopic works as well, as discussed in the technical justification section. We estimate a conservative effective limiting magnitude to be V=21.5 from our proof-of-concept data, which will allow us to search 94 KBOs for primitive ices. Thus, in total, we propose to increase the number of objects studied from ~35 to about 94, a factor 2.5 improvement in sample size and potentially a factor 2.5 increase in the number of known KBOs with volatiles (from the current 13 to ~30).
Observations of the 36 faintest objects remaining in our sample will be split between 2010A (18 objects) and 2010B (18 objects), when we will complete the survey. Scientific products of the survey will be: (1) in 2009B, we will submit a peer-reviewed paper detailing the proof-of-concept observations with telescope time already executed; (2) in 2010B, we will submit our second peer-reviewed paper with final survey results, including the identification of the ~30 of 94 KBOs brighter than V=21.5 that have volatile surface ices. The ultimate goal of our project is to create a public catalog that will serve as a basic census of KBO surface types. In addition, we will target some of the fainter Haumea (2003 EL61) dynamical family members as they are expected to have strong water ice features. We anticipate that future spectroscopic surveys by ourselves and others will rely on this database and filter system to guide target selection, allowing efficient use of telescope time.

Limiting Magnitude and Comparison to Spectroscopy:
Our filters have been manufactured with NASA Planetary Astronomy funds, installed and commissioned for use in 2008B with NIRI/Gemini and PANIC/Magellan. Our photometric survey outperforms spectroscopic surveys primarily because (1) spectroscopic observations require additional acquisition and calibration overheads and (2) grism and slit use attenuate flux and degrade image quality.
In our experience, photometry is superior to spectroscopy for volatile detection since only a few filters are used. In a typical observing scenario at Gemini, we require no image centering overheads so we start science immediately after the slew and guider setup when doing photometry. For spectroscopic science, one has to identify the object based on its non-sidereal motion (an extra 15 minutes) before placing it in the slit (an extra 8 minutes). For a 1.5 hour observation, about the length of time before flexure causes the object to move out of the slit, this amounts to 25% extra time spent in acquisition. In addition, grism throughput in NIRI is only about 50% and slit losses further attenuate the beam by ~20%. All totaled, spectroscopic science has about 30% more overheads than photometric science. On top of this, a separate photometric calibration must be done to normalize the J and K bands, in addition to a spectroscopic telluric calibration, roughly doubling calibration time.
We are primarily limited by the faintest objects in the sample due to the steep size distribution of the KBOs. We have already done a few objects fainter than V=21.5 in 1.25 hours of telescope time to our required 0.25 magnitude accuracy, so we conservatively choose this as our faintness limit. Previous spectroscopic surveys [12-13] have been limited to about V=21 with about 2 hours on source per object, making our photometric survey >3 times more efficient than spectroscopy, as expected from the overhead calculation above.
Observing Technique:
Our technique is similar to standard near-infrared photometric surveys with the addition of a telluric standard to correct for atmospheric absorption and OH-emission. Immediately before or after each KBO observation, a solar analogue G2V standard star is observed to provide telluric correction and a reflectance reference. A photometric faint standard is also observed occasionally to monitor overall throughput. We return to the sensitive Y and J-band continuum filters between longer integrations on the ice filters to compensate for any potential photometric variation due to object rotation. Basic analysis routines are complete at this point in our survey.
Sample Size and Request:
Our faint survey limit is V=21.5 from our proof-of-concept data, making our total sample size 94 KBOs in total. We have averaged about 1.25 hours of telescope time per object to date in the faintest of the 58 objects we have observed. In this proposal we request time to observe 1/2 of the remaining 36 KBOs brighter than V=21.5, all of which have poorly known surfaces. These are the most important objects in the survey as they cannot be observed at Magellan due to faintness and have no spectroscopic measurements. In this proposal, we ask for time to observe about 1/2 of these objects (18) in 2010A. This will require about 22 hours of IQ=70 CC=50 time as we have been averaging about 1.25 hours per object for the fainter objects. We have split this request evenly between our US and Gemini Staff (GS) partners. Our target list includes the full sample of objects to allow maximum flexibility in scheduling, plus additional follow-up of a few objects that require more precise photometry. Our highest priority objects for this allocation will be objects that are (1) unobserved KBOs and (2) dynamically interesting objects such as the Haumea (2003 EL61) family members and the cold classical KBOs. The cold classical KBOs are of particular interest as they are largely too faint for spectral study [17].

1. Background
Over the past four years we have made great strides in pursuing the physics and progenitors of GRBs (particularly the short-duration bursts, t<2 sec), and in employing long GRBs as probes of the high-z universe, mainly for the study of interstellar medium enrichment at z~2-6. This work is enabled by positions from the Swift satellite and intensive ground-based follow-up, largely from Gemini. Our group's previous programs at Gemini led to the best-characterized short GRB optical afterglows [BPC05,FFP05,SBK06], strong constraints on short GRB progenitor ages and energetics [BFP07,B09], abundance measurements for GRB damped Ly-alpha systems (DLAs) [PSC07], and constrained the redshift for the first Fermi burst detected to >GeV energies [GCK09]. Most recently, we demonstrated the z>7 nature of GRB 090423, the most distant object known at z=8.26, using NIRI imaging (Fig. 1), which lead directly to the subsequent confirming spectroscopic observations from VLT [TFL09].
Here we propose a comprehensive program to address the most pressing questions in the study of GRBs, focusing on properties of short bursts, the use of GRBs as probes of star forming regions out to the highest redshifts, and the redshifts of bursts detected to GeV energies with the Fermi Large-Area Telescope (LAT). These goals will benefit from an automated Gemini trigger, providing <15 minute response to Swift GRB alerts.
2. GRBs as Probes of the High-Redshift Universe
Swift's combination of sensitivity, accuracy, and rapid alerts brought GRBs to the forefront of galaxy studies at high-z. Using Gemini in conjunction with Keck/Magellan we have obtained spectroscopy of over two dozen GRBs, allowing us to study their host ISM; Fig. 2. We have shown that GRBs probe dense and metal-enriched systems (neutral hydrogen~10^20-10^22 cm^-2 and metallicities~0.01-1 solar), thereby providing a complementary view of DLAs to that from quasars (which mostly probe the gas- and metal-deficient halos of intervening systems) [BPC06,PBF06,1,2]. The metal abundance patterns are indicative of dust depletion, and likely alpha-enhancement as expected for young starburst populations [PBF06,3,4]. GRB-DLAs are also uniquely marked by absorption from SiII and FeII fine-structure states [PBF06,4,5], likely excited by the bursts' UV radiation. The SiII lines can be studied even at low spectral resolution with GMOS, and provide a yardstick for the GRB-absorber separation.
GRB-DLAs offer the first opportunity to characterize the DLA counterpart population [BCC07,CBC07]. QSO-DLAs remain elusive due to the background glare of the quasar, but in GRB-DLAs the afterglow fades to obscurity within days. We are currently undertaking a 77-hour Spitzer program to determine the stellar masses, dust content, and obscured star formation in GRB-DLAs. Initial analysis reveals a substantial detection fraction (~30%), with typical rest-frame 1-micron luminosities of ~0.1L*. We are also obtaining Keck/Magellan rest-frame UV imaging and spectroscopy, and most detections reveal similar low luminosities and star formation rates of ~1 Msun/yr. Thus, Gemini rapid spectroscopy will be leveraged with follow-up to delineate for the first time the properties of DLA counterparts, and their relation to star formation.
As of 2009A, the potential of GRBs is now confirmed to extend beyond z>8. Our automated trigger provides optical+NIR imaging to locate bursts from beyond reionization at z>5.8 through the Lyman break (afterglows are simple power laws so photo-z's can be easily established). The discovery and study of z>6 GRBs will have four crucial ramifications. First, it will address cosmic re-ionization at currently inaccessible redshifts, allowing measurement of the IGM neutral fraction through the Ly-alpha damping wing, a measurement not feasible with quasars. Second, it will help to measure z>6 star formation and its contribution to re-ionization. Third, it will shed light on the gas content of the first galaxies. Finally, it will pinpoint z>6 galaxies for subsequent follow-up. Admittedly, z>6 GRBs are rare (three confirmed by spectroscopy beyond z=6; [6,7,BCC07,NFL09]); our automated strategy offers the best chance to catch such bursts, and a high-quality GMOS or NIRI spectrum of even one will be a watershed event.
3. The Progenitors of Short GRBs
The discovery of the first short GRB afterglows only two years ago established that they occur in elliptical and spiral galaxies and have no bright underlying supernovae [FFP05,BPC05,8,9]. These properties are consistent with the favored merger models (NS-NS, NS-BH), suggesting appreciable event rates for future gravitational wave detectors [NGF06,BFP07]. Recent observations by our group, predominantly from Gemini, show that at least 1/3 of all short GRBs occur at z~1, stretching their energy budget and requiring younger progenitor ages than initially expected; Fig.3 [BFP07,CBN08].
The key missing ingredient is an actual demonstration of merger-related physics and direct observations of the progenitors; for example, all but one of the SHB redshifts are from host galaxy associations (e.g. [BFP07]). Gravitational waves will ultimately provide the cleanest test of binary mergers, but in the meantime spectroscopy of the progenitor environment, the possible detection of sub-relativistic nucleon-rich ejecta that may accompany some bursts [10], and a determination of whether some progenitors are ejected from their hosts, will directly test progenitor models [11]. Direct redshifts can be compared with nearby galaxies to test for progenitor ejection, and will provide a measurement of the gas and metal properties in the burst environment (distinguishing a star-formation vs. old population origin). Detection of a thermal component will constrain the progenitor and energy extraction mechanism through the brightness and velocity of the sub-relativistic ejecta [10]. This program will benefit most dramatically from our rapid automated trigger.
4. Redshifts for Fermi-LAT Bursts
GRB detections by the Fermi-LAT instrument are now being reported regularly. The remarkable sensitivity of the LAT at GeV energies has allowed it to search for photon dispersion effects due to quantum gravity, and opacity effects of the extragalactic background light - not to mention investigate the nature of GRB high-energy emission processes - as long as redshifts for a significant number of bursts can been measured.

The study of short GRB progenitors and the use of long GRBs as probes of the high redshift universe rely on rapid imaging and spectroscopy response to GRB alerts. Gemini is ideal for this purpose given its large aperture, queue scheduling, and choice of instruments. Our group can best leverage and support the unique advantages of Gemini through access to small and large telescopes in both hemispheres and over a wide range of longitudes (in particular, Las Campanas/Magellan, Palomar, Keck, HET, VLA). Over the last few semesters our Gemini program led to detailed studies of short GRB afterglows and their host galaxies, and ISM studies of DLAs at z>2 (see list of references and publications).
In addition, having reached the limits of what human-mediated triggers can achieve, we have implemented an automated trigger for use at Gemini. This trigger composes and submits a Phase 2 file within minutes of a burst's detection by Swift, allowing observations to commence within 15 minutes (including slew). It filters burst alerts based on duration to trigger the appropriate observations (long/short bursts) only when the burst is immediately accessible with Gemini and when it has an accurate position (<5 arcsec) from the Swift X-ray Telescope. For bursts that are not immediately observable (>30 minutes) but are still bright enough for follow-up several hours after discovery (see below for limits), we will use fine-tuned human triggers.
This semester we expect a continued all-sky rate of about 10 GRBs/month from Swift, and one GRB/month from Fermi+LAT.

Some Seyfert (Sy) galaxies have extended emission-line regions (EELRs), seen as much as 10 kpc from the nucleus. These probe the emerging radiation in various directions, and the AGN's history through light-travel time. This program would characterize the emission in the brightest of the ~100 new detections from Galaxy Zoo, bearing on both these issues. Some of these EELRs were found as early as Haniff et al. (1988, 1991), with later study including 2D spectroscopy and HST imagery of such prominent examples as NGC 5252 (e.g. Tadhunter & Tsvetanov 1989; Haniff et al. 1991; Tsvetanov et al. 1996; Acosta- Pulido et al. 1996) and Mkn 573 (e.g. Falcke et al. 1998; Ferruit et al. 1999; Schlesinger et al. 2009; Kraemer et al. 1999). Important results from these projects included support for a geometric unification of Sy 1 and 2: the gas often traces distinct ionization cones, with Sy 1 EELRs much smaller in projection (e.g. Mulchaey et al. 1996; Schmitt et al. 2003).
New goals for study of these EELRs became apparent from the the extreme instance known as Hanny's Voorwerp (Lintott et al. 2009, Josza et al. 2008). This object (Figure 1), discovered by Dutch schoolteacher Hanny van Arkel as part of the Galaxy Zoo project (Lintott et al. 2008), is a 30-kpc cloud with the ionization levels of a narrow-line AGN, located adjacent to the massive spiral IC 2497 whose LINER nucleus is energetically far short of providing the requisite ionizing radiation. Available limits on the flux from any luminous AGN, up to 10 keV, mean that either a QSO has dropped its radiative output by a factor 1000 within 10e5 years (making the cloud an ionization echo), or it remains active but is obscured to an unprecedented degree. Either case is very interesting for our broad understanding of the AGN population. Systematic searches for EELRs can constrain the occurrence of dramatic variability, on time scales > 10e4 years, or quantify the occurrence of deeply buried AGN through detection of gas ionized by UV radiation escaping along (sparse) clear lines of sight. Choosing between these is best done from sensitive high-energy X-ray observations, such as we have recently obtained for Hanny's Voorwerp and IC 2497, or using the energy budget including far-IR data. Though the recombination time scale is not negligible and can reach ~1000 years, we can still obtain limits on AGN variability for the extended regions for which the light-travel time exceeds the recombination time scale.
With participants in the Galaxy Zoo project, we have collected a new sample of candidate EELRs from SDSS imagery, based on the finding that strong [O III] emission produces distinctive colors in the SDSS composite images and that the structures of EELRs are often quite different from the familiar spirals or rings. For some of the galaxies in the sample and most notably for UGC 7342, the SDSS data themselves show that they have highly ionized [O III] structures (Fig. 2). Therefore we are confident that in these cases we can proceed to detailed spectroscopic mapping to better characterize the spatial structure and emission strength of the ionized gas. As an example, a pattern that emerged from the data we have is that most EELRs around Sy 1s appear as ?ƒ˙purple haze?ƒ˘, a combination of H?± and [O III] in an asymmetric cloud smaller and more centered than in most Sy 2. However, large (10 kpc) ionization cones are almost exclusively seen for Sy 2s, as expected for an obscuration model, and largely seen in merging systems. This makes sense as ongoing or recent mergers can effectively place gas in the path of ionizing radiation than a single thin disk; Hanny's Voorwerp itself is part of a massive stream of H I, possibly a tidal feature as well.
In light of these findings, this proposal is to conduct a detailed study UGC 7342 which has the highest level of this [OIII] emission seen in the SDSS imaging and a large pattern of ionized gas structure. An integral field study of this target is ideally suited to address the timescale and obscuration issues. This proposal would use the spatial and spectral information from GMOS-IFU observations to characterize the structure, density, kinematics, and strength of the ionized gas emission around the nucleus and in a nearby cloud off the major-axis. Successful analysis of this pilot galaxy would pave the way to study the other strong detections in the SDSS sample with 3D spectroscopy or with X-ray data.
These observations will allow us to address several major science questions : Has this AGN brightened or faded dramatically over 10e4 ?‡Ì10e5 years? Does the density of ionized gas (used as a tracer of possible dust and molecular gas) explain why some other AGN may be so deeply obscured as to hide from existing X-ray surveys? And more generally, these observations will provide the basis for a larger study to see if it is possible that the Sy 1/2 distinction is merely one of viewing angle around obscuring material.

Sample Selection:
Sample selection was carried out by Galaxy Zoo participants as follows. After some striking examples had been posted for discussion on the project forum, we set up a systematic search for more examples similar to these. This search targeted all Seyferts from the Veron-Cetty and Veron catalog within z = 0.1 and the SDSS footprint, plus all galaxies in which the SDSS spectra indicated Seyfert or transition (possibly mixed-ionization) nuclei, totaling 18,000 systems. Each was inspected by at least 10 participants and flagged as having certain, possible, or no ionized clouds. A call for examples on the project forum has also yielded some in galaxies with unknown spectra or spectra lacking AGN signatures, potentially the most interesting of all. We inspected the outcome and removed starburst systems (to avoid false positives for which the [OIII] emission is dominated by star formation). The results recovered known instances (NGC 5252, Mkn 273) as well as another ~100 cases, some even larger and brighter than the known ones. (The logarithmic mapping of the SDSS images at high fluxes makes this roughly an equivalent-width limited search).
Spectral Range, S/N, and Resolution:
For EELRs, intense [O III] is accompanied by [NII] \lambda 6583 and [SII] \lambda 6716 at levels of around 1/3 of \lambda 5007 which can be compared to the H\alpha and H\beta levels. These ratios let us estimate the ionization parameter and the hardness of the ionizing continuum (Bennert et al. 2006) To estimate required exposure times, we use surface-brightness estimates in [O III] based on differencing SDSS images normalized to the local stellar continuum. The peak value for the nucleus is 4.0x10e15 erg/cm 2 arcsec 2 sec in this line and around 1.3x10e15 erg/cm 2 arcsec 2 sec in the cloud. We want to measure [NII], and [SII] strengths to a sufficient level (as well as H\alpha, H\beta and any other strong lines present), so we would like an average of S/N~60 per spatial resolution element in the [O III] \lambda 5007 line. The limiting factor for the spectral resolution is only the ability to resolve the two [SII] lines at rest wavelengths 6716.31\AA and 6730.68 \AA. Given that these two lines have a well known separation, with sufficient S/N, it would not be difficult to deblend them for individual measurement as long as one peak was resolved. Therefore a spectral resolution less than 15\AA/pixel would be sufficient.
The ideal wavelength range to study these lines covers at least 560nm-800nm. This also provides adequate wavelength accuracy to learn whether the dynamics of the gas follows a normal galaxy pattern or may be affected by outflows at the 100 km/s level. A 0.2" spatial resolution element, would be more than enough to spatially resolve any interesting features found in the nucleus or cloud that would show finer disturbances or structures in the gas or stellar emission (or the kinematics of either).
Observations and Need for GMOS-IFU:
The GMOS-IFU is ideally suited to observe exactly these kinds of targets. The high spatial and spectral resolution as well as the relatively generous wavelength coverage coupled withe the light gathering power of an 8m telescope allows for detailed spectroscopic mapping of these relatively faint galaxies and gas emission line regions. Not only does it allow for us to detect the strength of many different emission lines and their ratios, but it allows us to detect spatial changes in their emission strengths and kinematics. IFUs in general and specifically the GMOS-IFU are the best way to discover surprising structures in the ionized gas which long slits miss entirely and which imaging data cannot resolve spectrally.
We will use the GMOS-N IFU in 2 slit mode which has a spatial sampling of 0.2"/lens and a FOV of 5"x7" with the R150 grating (0.174nm/pixel R=631 at blaze=717nm) centered at 680nm. This gives the ideal wavelength coverage of 460nm-900nm with peak performance near the [SII] and [NII] lines.
Using the GMOS-N ITC V 4.0 and the strength of the [OIII] line in the nuclear region, we find that 20 exposures of 1800s gives a S/N=75 in the very center dropping off at the edges of the field (3" on average from center) to around S/N=20. As is customary for IFU data of galaxy cores, we will be binning the outer regions so achieve a minimum S/N of around 50 to balance between spatial resolution and S/N. A similar calculation was done for the cloud approximately 30" away which shows strong [OIII] emission in the SDSS data. For this, with 24 exposures of 1800 seconds, we achieved a S/N around 50 for the peak of the emission which drops down to around 40 at the edges of the field. Again, the field can be spatially binned with known Voronnoi adaptive binning routines to ensure a minimum S/N across the field.
In the time estimates we have also added in read-out-time, science fold changes, flats, arcs (embedded for accurate wavelength calibration), acquisition time, and time for a bright flux standard.
Overall we are asking for around 32 hours of time including all calibrations and overheads. In order to minimize this time as much as possible we need to ask for CC=50% photometric conditions as well as Sky background of 20%. We have also asked for IQ=70% but as long as the FWHM seeing is less than ~0.7" locally, the object can be observed at the typical airmasses.
Analysis:
We will use our expertise with the Gemini GMOS-IFU reduction package to reduce the data into data cubes. At this point we will use adaptive pixel binning methods developed by Cappellari & Copin (2003) to bin to a constant minimum S/N. We will then employ our experience with the very powerful GANDALF (Sarzi et al. 2006) program which simultaneously fits the stellar and gas components to make detailed ionized-gas distribution, strength, line ratios, and dynamical maps. These will provide a first ever look into the structure of this very interesting galaxy as well as provide a benchmark for future studies of similar objects.

Much of what is known about the formation and evolution of the Galaxy relies on knowledge of the chemical composition of its constituent stars. An obvious next step towards deepening that understanding is the extension of chemical composition determinations to stars belonging to other galaxies. While the past several years have seen great progress mainly in abundance studies of dwarf spheroidal satellites of the Galaxy (e.g., Koch et a. 2008, Helmi et al. 2006, Monaco et al. 2005, Shetrone et al. 2001, Venn et al. 2000), there's still a long way to go towards mapping out the metallicities and abundance patterns of stars in Local Group galaxies. This proposal is part of a larger project aiming at determining CNO abundances of giant stars from extragalactic globular clusters (GCs).
We propose to obtain high-resolution, moderately deep, NIR imaging of three M31 (GCs), using NIRI+ALTAIR. These images will be used to construct the first NIR color-magnitude diagrams for these carefully selected GCs, which will allow us to: 1) select cluster giants for future spectroscopic observations, 2) constrain GC parameters, such as metallicity and age.
The data will allow us to address a plethora of fascinating scientific questions. The CNO abundances of old GC stars in M31 can be compared to those of young supergiants (e.g., Urbaneja et al. 2005), providing a direct assessment of the global chemical evolution of that galaxy over the past 10 billion years. Moreover, combining CNO abundances with [Fe/H] estimates from integrated light spectra, which are in very good agreement with values based on analysis of individual stars (e.g., Caldwell et al. 2009, Graves & Schiavon 2008) will allow for determination of [CNO/Fe] abundance ratios, which provides constraints on the timescales of star formation in the M31 halo. Other important questions that can be addressed are: is the CN-bimodality characteristic of Galactic GC stars (e.g., Smith & Briley 2005) also found in M31 clusters? Are there important differences between CNO abundances of GCs in the Galaxy and M31, as suggested by studies of cluster integrated light? (e.g., Brodie & Huchra 1991, Burstein et al. 1984).
We focus on CNO abundances because 1) these are the most abundant metals in the universe, 2) since the nucleosynthetic origins of these three key elements are distinct, they pose different constraints on the history of star formation and chemical enrichment in galaxies, and 3) CNO abundances are obtainable from spectrum synthesis of molecular bands due to CN, OH, and CO in medium resolution spectra. We decided to focus on GC giants so as to have a handle on the stellar ages, while minimizing the contamination of our sample by foreground Galactic field stars. The choice of medium resolution spectroscopy in the NIR comes from the need of adaptive optics in order to resolve individual giants in extragalactic GCs.
In the 2009A, a pilot program (GN-2009A-Q-41) to establish the feasibility of the project was granted 6.6 hours in Band 2. We obtained medium-resolution JHK spectra of cool giants in well-known Galactic GCs, using NIRI. The spectra are currently being reduced. Preliminary results are displayed in Figures 1 and 2, where spectra of one M4 and one M71 giant are compared. The positions of strong OH and CO bands are indicated. We expect to conclude the analysis of these spectra by the end of January 2010.
There are two technical challenges to this program. The first concerns the abundance accuracies achievable from the analysis of medium resolution NIR spectra. Tests based on spectrum synthesis showed that O and C abundances with internal accuracies of ~ 0.15 dex are achievable at modest S/N (~ 30/pixel), while N abundances require S/N ~ 60/pixel for an internal accuracy of 0.3 dex. The lower N-abundance sensitivity is compensated by the much wider range of N abundances usually found in GCs (see Carretta et al. 2005, Schiavon et al. 2007). The second challenge is due to the bias introduced by internal mixing known to affect the atmospheric abundances of evolved stars. This phenomenon is fairly well understood from both theoretical and observational standpoints (e.g., Renzini & Voli 1981, Brown 1987). We can use this knowledge to account for the effect of mixing, thus estimating abundances relevant for chemical evolution studies. Moreover, direct comparison with the Galactic control sample from our 2009A program should provide a mixing-free interpretation of the data, since mixing effects should operate similarly in M31 and MW GCs.
To summarize, we propose to obtain AO-assisted NIR imaging of three carefully selected clusters from M31. These observations will be used for the construction of CMDs for the target clusters, thus allowing for a careful selection of targets for spectroscopic follow up. This program is the second step toward a more challenging forthcoming program, where we intend to push Gemini's state-of-the-art capabilities to their limits, in order to determine, for the first time, elemental abundances in individual stars from extragalactic globular clusters.
