The scientific goals laid out in this proposal will be achieved in two steps. The first is to obtain quick high-spatial resolution adaptive optics K-band imaging of 8 M31 globular clusters selected to have viable AO guide stars. Using these data we will select the 3 best clusters for follow-up stellar spectroscopy, and obtain multi-color imaging to select the spectroscopic targets. Photometry in J, H, and K bands is needed in order to allow removal of long-period variables from our planned spectroscopic sample (e.g., Frogel & Elias 1988). Target clusters were selected from the Caldwell et al. (2009) catalogue, adopting the following criteria: metallicities ranging between [Fe/H] ~ -1.0 and 0.0, old age, reddening lower than E(B-V) = 1.0, and location in relatively low-crowding regions.
The initial K-band AO imaging will be relatively fast and will serve several purposes. The primary use is to select clusters for spectroscopy which are populous but not too compact as to make resolved stellar spectroscopy impossible. This imaging will also provide valuable information on the AO performance we can expect for each cluster, which is important given the uncertainties in guide star magnitudes.
The multi-color (JH) AO imaging of the final 3 clusters will occupy most of the time requested by this proposal. These images must be deep enough that we can obtain photometry not only of our spectroscopic targets, but also enough of the RGB that we can accurately determine cluster membership. Based on previous HST NICMOS imaging of other M31 clusters, we should be able to make these determinations with measurements down to 2 magnitudes above the horizontal branch.
Using the NIRI ITC we have estimated the time required to obtain S/N=5 photometry of stars 2 mags above the HB for intermediate metallicity clusters (J=21.8, H=21.3, K=21.25) using Altair in NGS mode with the Field Lens and IQ-70%, CC-50%, BG-any, WV-any conditions. We assume an AO guide star magnitude of V~13 and a guide star separation of ~20".
The ITC predicts that the K-band imaging will only require ~5 minutes on-source per cluster. Including an equal amount of time for sky measurements and 10 minutes of overhead for setup yields a total time of 20 minutes per cluster. Imaging all 8 clusters in the K-band therefore requires 2:40.
The J- and H-band imaging needs 40 and 20 minutes respectively of on-source time. Doubling this for sky measurements and including 10 minutes for setup yields 2:10 per cluster, or 6:30 for all three clusters in the final sample.
We therefore request 9 hours to obtain K-band imaging of all 8 clusters and J- and H-band imaging of the final 3 clusters.
The observations listed contain K-band observations for all clusters, plus JH observations for three clusters, whose identities will be defined after analysis of K-band data. The JH observations were included using a "dummy" target, consisting of a duplication of the target fields defined in the K-band observation for cluster B013-G065.
Archival HST optical images are available for three of the target clusters (B338-G076, B008-G060, and B013-G065). While such multicolor photometry can be used to further constrain reddening towards the targets, as well as important cluster parameters such as metallicity and age, it is not sufficient for the goals of our project. It is very important that we remove long-period variables from our spectroscopic target candidates, and the best way to accomplish this without resorting to expensive multi-epoch observations is by use of JHK photometry (Frogel & Elias 1988). Moreover, in case any of these clusters are chosen for the spectroscopic follow-up, JHK photometry will be required, on the basis of which effective temperatures will be derived.

Observations of massive galaxies can be used to constrain models of galaxy formation. Within the hierarchical framework of cold dark matter, massive galaxies are assumed to form by a combination of gas-poor (dry) mergers of several smaller progenitors of old stars at z<=1 without star formation and additional AGN feedback (Bower et al. 2006, MNRAS 370,645; Croton et al. 2006, MNRAS 365,11). In the context of the assembly of Brightest Cluster Galaxies (BCGs), about 1/3 of present-day BCGs in galaxy clusters today are expected to have assembled half of their mass since z~0.3 (De Lucia & Blaizot 2007, MNRAS 375,2). Previous studies on BCGs used the galaxy luminosity as a proxy for the total baryonic mass of a galaxy (Bernardi et al. 2007, AJ 133,1741; von der Linden et al. 2007, MNRAS 379,867; Stott et al. 2008, MNRAS 384,1502). These BCG studies concentrated mainly on their photometric properties because acquiring spectroscopy with sufficient signal-to-noise is expensive in telescope time.
In semester 2008B, our project was initiated and got awarded with 16.5 hours in Band 3 conditions. In semester 2009A we got awarded with 23 hours in Band 2 conditions. So far, 15 galaxies have been observed. Unfortunately, our allocated time of 6 hours at GN was lost due to bad weather conditions during the semester. To accomplish our efforts, we propose for the current semester to obtain high signal-to-noise long-slit GMOS spectroscopy of the remaining 8 massive early-type galaxies at redshifts 0.12<z<0.35. In order to investigate the effects on environment and mass for these galaxies and in particular the low-luminosity galaxies in our sample, we would need total sample of 23 galaxies to be observed.
Out of 42000 possible targets from the SDSS database, we extracted 43 luminous systems with sigma>350 km/s that show a passive early-type galaxy spectrum (S/N<10 per A). Because it is not possible to deblend distant galaxies closer than about 1 arcsec with SDSS photometry alone, a large fraction of our selected systems are likely to be artificially broadened by close superpositions along the line-of-sight.
Using existing HST/ACS imaging, we found out that 47% of the sample are superpositions of two or three galaxies, so the velocity dispersion of the SDSS pipeline is incorrect. The other half (53%) consists of luminous galaxies with genuinely large velocity dispersions up to 430 km/s. These 23 systems were classified as disky (65%) and boxy (35%) ellipticals and are the most massive and densest galaxies currently know. Using a combination of colors and photometric redshifts, we found out that these objects are located either in isolated or dense environments. The galaxies define steeper size-, mass- and density-luminosity relations than the bulk of the early-type galaxy population: for their luminosities, they are the smallest, most massive and densest galaxies in the Universe. At fixed sigma, our galaxies lie parallel to the SDSS early-type galaxies which suggests that they are the large-sigma extremes of the early-type galaxy population. These results imply that massive galaxies have been formed by multiple generations of dry dissipationless merger processes involving no strong dissipation at lower redshifts of z<=1. This is demonstrated in Figure 1, which shows the Fundamental Plane (FP) for our massive galaxies. As predicted by gas-poor major merger simulations of ellipticals (Boylan-Kolchin et al. 2006, MNRAS 369,1081), our FP is preserved for all configurations of merger orbits as a consequence of the virial equilibrium. However, the projections of the FP depend on the merger orbits and favor radial orbits due to different amounts of energy loss caused by dynamical friction. This is seen through steeper Faber-Jackson and luminosity-size relations for our galaxies than for normal ellipticals.
To test the dry merger scenario for our massive galaxies in greater detail, additional high S/N GMOS spectra (S/N>40 per A) will allow us to measure the internal kinematics and stellar populations of these systems. The most recent models can discriminate beween the properties resulting from identical dry mergers and mergers with minor accretion (Hopkins et al. 2009, arXiv:0909.2039). In particular, for these two merging models, different values for the size and velocity dispersion of massive galaxies are predicted. As a bonus, we will increase our efficiency by aligning the PA of the long-slit in such a manner that we also obtain a second spectrum of close neighbouring galaxies.
Our primary goal is to derive mean stellar ages, metallicities and chemical element abundance ratios of our primary galaxies. In particular, we want to explore how the ages, metallicities and non-solar abundance ratios vary with environment. For intermediate-mass, distant early-type galaxies these parameters show a correlation with velocity dispersion (mass) which is consistent with that of local galaxies (Ziegler et al. 2005, A&A 433,519; Fritz 2007, PASP 119,590). These results suggest that since z=0.4 there is only little chemical enrichment up to the present. We will test if this effect is also seen in the most massive galaxies both in cluster and in field environments.
The stellar parameters and the chemistry of the galaxies will be derived by comparing measured Lick/IDS absorption line-strengths to the single stellar population models by Schiavon (2007, ApJS 171,146). Apart from the usually modelled alpha-elements of iron, magnesium and calcium, these models also treat nitrogen and carbon as possible alpha-elements. Both elements are important for the metal abundance and enrichment of luminous old stellar populations. Kelson et al. (2006, ApJ 653,159) suggested for intermediate-mass cluster early-type galaxies at z=0.3 a secondary phase of nitrogen enrichment. This might be even more prominent for massive galaxies as there exists a strong dependence of the nitrogen abundance with stellar luminosity (Tinsley 1979, ApJ 229,1046). With our proposed high S/N spectra we will be able to explore this interesting issue.
Further, we will test if the correlation of ages and abundances with sigma should flatten out at high-sigma values. The amount of abundance ratio can be interpreted as an indication of the duration of star formation (SF). For our massive objects we expect to measure higher abundances than those of normal ellipticals which would point to an accelerated assembly with SF occurring over a shorter time-scale. This might be accompanied by a strong central AGN activity at high redshift (z>=2) that suppresses longer SF episodes and rapidly shuts down SF after a short time period. The broad spectral wavelength coverage of GMOS allows us to construct age and metallicity indicators with different line indices (e.g. Hbeta, Hgamma, [MgFe] and C2_4668), thereby refining previous age-metallicity determinations. Further, we will be able to detect possible Hdelta_A or Hgamma_F Balmer absorption in our systems, which is believed to appear only after recent SF episodes (Worthey & Ottaviani 1997, ApJS 111,137).
As a complement, the high-quality spectra will allow us to increase the accuracy in the velocity dispersion measurements of our galaxies. From a comparison with high S/N early-type galaxy spectra at z~0.2 (Fritz et al. 2005, MNRAS 358,233) we expect to reduce the uncertainties in the internal kinematics down to ~30 km/s. This is a factor of two or more improvement over the measurement errors derived from SDSS spectra.

At redshifts z=0.12-0.35 of our galaxies, we are mainly interested in the observed wavelength range between 4700-6800 A. Grating B600_G5303 offers a sufficiently broad (~2800 A) wavelength coverage for the measurement of the line indices of our interest at these redshifts (e.g. Hdelta, Hgamma, Hbeta, Mgb, Fe5270 and Fe5335). All targets are luminous and the sample has a magnitude limit of r~17.5 mag. The luminosities of our selected targets (-22.8>Mr>-24.3) span a similar range as the brightest cluster members of our FP investigation in two rich clusters at z=0.2 (Fritz et al. 2005, MNRAS 358, 233). From this previous experience and from simulations using the GMOS ITC, we calculate that we need an integration time of 60 minutes per target under observing conditions IQ=85%, CC=70%, WV=any, BG=50%, airmass=1.5. With this setup we achieve a S/N ratio of ~40 per A in the continuum at 6300 A using the B600 grating. We estimate that for an extended source with our R-band magnitude limit, 39% of the source light will fall into the 1.0" wide slit under 85%-tile image quality. To provide an efficient elimination of cosmic ray events, our strategy is to split the exposures into 4 integrations of 900 sec each.
B600_G5307 and 1.0" slits give an instrumental resolution at our median redshift z=0.22 of 107 km/s and 131 km/s around the Fe5270 absorption line and the 4000 A break, respectively. This resolution and the final S/N warrants the measurements of accurate velocity dispersions and absorption line indices. By using 1.0" slits our instrumental resolution is also sufficient to derive the internal kinematics of the secondary objects. Figure 2 shows an image gallery of all our main targets and possible close neighbours within 25" (corresponding to 83 kpc at z=0.2) from the primary target. These other objects have not been spectroscopically observed by SDSS. In the case of dense environments, these galaxies show similar red colors (r-i)=0.5 at z=0.2 and thus are very likely accociated to the cluster/group environment as defined by our primary targets.
Each target requires an exposure time of 60 minutes (4x900 sec), plus 30 minutes of acquisition and read-out time, resulting in a total observing time of 90 minutes per target. We are asking to observe 8 targets in 2010A. Therefore, we request in total 12.0 hours. In 2008B, six galaxies (SDSSJ013431, SDSSJ171328, SDSSJ162332, SDSSJ211019, SDSSJ221414, and SDSSJ235354) have already been observed under Band 3 conditions. In 2009A, nine galaxies were observed in at GS. The remaining galaxies we are asking to observe in 2009A are listed in the table of the observations. The spectra of the six galaxies observed in 2008B have been reduced and for half of them velocity dispersion have been derived. In Figure 3 we show four galaxies which have been analyzed so far. These results have been presented as a poster presentation at the IAU Symposium 267 in Brazil, August 3-14, 2009. The full sample consists of 23 galaxies. For completeness all targets are also shown in Figure 2. The standard GMOS baseline calibrations are sufficient for our observations.

White dwarfs are the end stage of stellar evolution for the vast majority of stars - all stars less massive than 8 solar masses end their lives as cooling white dwarfs. The coolest white dwarfs can constrain the age of the Galactic disk, or even of the halo. While other methods for dating the ages of the Galactic components exist (cluster isochrone fitting, isotope decay, asteroseismology, space motions, magnetic activity, etc), cold white dwarfs are unambiguously old and their cooling rates are well understood, enabling their use as simple and accurate chronometers (e.g. Leggett et al. 1998).
White dwarf atmospheres are predominantly composed of helium and/or hydrogen. The opacity of helium is much lower than that of hydrogen, and hydrogen-rich white dwarfs of a given effective temperature (Teff) are older than their helium-rich counterparts due to the insulation provided by their atmospheres. Bergeron et al. (2001) show that the coolest known white dwarfs with Teff~4000K are ~9.5 Gyr old if hydrogen-rich and 8 Gyr old if helium-rich. These ages are consistent with the age of the local Galactic Disk. Several groups are trying to find even cooler and older white dwarfs - to confirm the age of the disk, and investigate the ages of older Galactic components.
Cool white dwarfs have recently been found in the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS). Kilic et al. (2006) use the SDSS and USNO databases to identify cool white dwarfs using a reduced proper motion (PM) diagram. The reduced PM is defined by: H = mag +5log(PM "/yr) + 5. Here the apparent magnitude and PM are used as a proxy for absolute magnitude for a sample with similar kinematics. Figure 1 shows how faint white dwarfs with significant PM can be separated from stars, subdwarfs and quasars. Kilic et al. have spectroscopically confirmed several white dwarfs this way, including seven with Teff around 4000K. Hall et al. (2008) have also identified a possible 11 Gr-old halo white dwarf in the SDSS by its proper motion. SDSS white dwarfs have also been identified by their colors. Low-temperature hydrogen-rich white dwarf atmospheres are at high pressures, and show strong pressure-induced molecular hydrogen (H2) opacity. This opacity has a broad absorption feature around 2um, which affects the H and K near-infrared bands. When Teff decreases below 4000K, the opacity can also impact the optical colors. Gates et al. (2004) and Harris et al. (2001, 2008) used this to identify and confirm 13 extremely cool white dwarfs by their unusual SDSS colors. Figure 2 shows the location of some of the known ultracool white dwarfs in color-color plots (asterisks).
Analysis of dwarfs with such cold and high-pressure atmospheres is difficult (e.g. Bergeron & Leggett 2002) but it is clear that there are now a handful of objects known with Teff<4000K and ages 9-12 Gyr (new opacities for such atmospheres are being calculated). Our group is searching for cool white dwarfs by combining the SDSS and USNO databases with the UKIRT infrared sky survey (UKIDSS, Lawrence et al. 2007), which provides photometry in the YJHK filters, 1.0 to 2.5um. These databases allow us to determine proper motion, as well as optical and near-infrared colors. Our use of three databases allows us to go ~1 magnitude fainter in g than the Kilic et al. sample and also allows us to select for hydrogen-rich dwarfs. Our selection criterion requires (1) high proper motion such that the candidates fall in the appropriate area of the reduced PM diagram (2) red gri colors implying low Teff and (3) blue JH colors implying the presence of H2 opacity.
10 hrs of 07B Gemini Christmas Director's time allowed us to followup an initial search of 340 sq. deg. of the Large Area Survey (LAS, Warren et al. 2007) component of the UKIDSS Data Release (DR) 2. All candidates were confirmed to be new white dwarfs, however they were not particularly cool, having Teff = 5500 - 6700K, and so ages of 2 - 5 Gyr (Lodieu et al. 2009). Figure 3 shows the model fits to the photometry and GMOS H-alpha line for one of these dwarfs, demonstrating the high quality both of the data and the model atmosphere analysis. It can be seen that the presence of Halpha rules out a helium-rich composition, and implies an age ~3 Gyr. We refined our search and used the DR3 release of 900 sq. deg. to followup 8 objects in 17 hours of 08B time. Figure 2 shows how we selected for cooler objects in 08B based on g-r color. Reduction of that data is ongoing; preliminary results for 4 objects suggest that one is a 4000K 10 Gyr-old white dwarf, one is a 5000K 5 Gyr-old white dwarf and the other two are cool subdwarfs. Based on their colors, we expect the remaining four objects to consist of two 4000K and two 5000K white dwarfs (blue circles in Figure 2).
1200 sq. deg. of sky are now available in DR5. We have identified eight more candidate 4000K white dwarfs all of which are accessible in 10A. Their colors (large filled circles in Figure 2) and their location in the RPM diagram (Figure 1) indicate that these are all extremely likely to be 4000K 10 Gyr-old white dwarfs. Two are bluer in the optical but also unusually blue in YJH implying the presence of CIA H2 opacity in the far-red (brown circles in Figure 2). The brightest source identified for 10A has an SDSS spectrum which shows it to be a rare cool carbon-rich white dwarf with shifted Swan bands (e.g. Schmidt et al. 1995; open red circle in Figure 2). The 10A and 08B results should add ~10 4000K white dwarfs to the very small known sample of 20. We will also have established selection criteria which the community can use in ongoing and future surveys to identify the elusive population of cold hydrogen-rich degenerate remnants of the disk and halo stellar populations.

The targets were selected from the USNO, SDSS and UKIDSS databases to have: faint RPM magnitudes of Hg>20.5 (cf. Figure 1, this implies both faint magnitudes and high proper motion), and r_AB<20.7 for observing feasability. Initially, detection at J and H was required and color cuts were applied to select for cool H-rich white dwarfs: 0.8<g-r<1.6, 0.2<r-i<0.6, 0.6<i-J<1.4, J-H<0.2 (red circles in Figure 2). We also searched for objects that were bluer in the optical but also significantly blue in zYJH, to identify those very cold or very high pressure dwarfs with CIA H2 opacity in the optical (brown circles in Figure 2); one of these has an extremely faint reduced PM of Hg=25. The candidates have been checked against published lists of white dwarfs and subdwarfs and have not previously been published (one recovered known cool white dwarf was removed from the sample). The images of the candidates have also been checked to ensure a robust identification (two close double systems were removed from the sample). A spectrum for the brightest candidate (open red circle in Figure 2) was found in the SDSS spectral database (showing it to be a previously unrecognised cool carbon-rich white dwarf), and this was removed from the sample. We have also confirmed that none of these objects are in the Gemini archive.
We will use GMOS with the R400 grating, the 0.75" slit, 2x2 binning and a central wavelength of 700nm. We have requested GMOS-S time as the targets are equatorial and the North is usually heavily oversubscribed at the target RAs. However the TAC may move us to the North if they wish. The GMOS-S ITC was used to calculate exposure times and S/N for our targets, which have r_AB=18.7-20.1. Overheads were estimated at 16 minutes setup and 2 minutes per exposure, as given in the instrument web pages. Total observation times of 0.9 to 2.6 hours in IQ70 SB50 CC70 WVany provides S/N of 15 to 30 across the 525-875 nm spectrum. This S/N and the resolution of R~1300 is necessary and sufficient to (1) rule out any non-white dwarf contaminants (e.g. subdwarfs, see Kilic et al. 2006) and (2) detect any weak Halpha present (e.g. Figure 3). If band 3 time is awarded we will relax the image quality to IQ85 and obtain S/N~10-20. This will still allow confirmation of the white dwarfs although modelling any weak hydrogen lines will be compromised. The total request is 12.4 hours for the eight targets.

With a super-massive black hole at its core, a dense cluster of stars immediately surrounding it (some of which are young, hot, and luminous), and a massive amount of interstellar gas in a wide variety of environments, the Galactic center (GC) is rich in extraordinary phenomena. Using the infrared spectrum of H3+ , we have found a vast amount of warm (T~250 K) and diffuse (n<100 cm^-3 ) gas in the Central Molecular Zone (CMZ), (Oka et al. 2005 ApJ 632, 882), the (perhaps inappropriate) name given to the central region of radius ~200 pc. Subsequently we detected gas of this density and temperature in the CMZ on sightlines toward eight bright and hot stars close to the Galactic plane and located between the center and 30 pc east of it (Goto et al. 2008 ApJ, 688, 306).
The above density and temperature regime corresponds to a previously unknown interstellar environment in the CMZ. The three environments known previously are: (1) dense molecular gas observed by radio emission of molecules, (2) hot ionized gas observed in radio recombination and atomic fine structure lines and radio-wave scattering, and (3) ultra-hot (10^7 -10^8 K) X-ray emitting plasma. Indeed no such warm and diffuse environment is known elsewhere in the Galaxy. Because the evidence for it has been seen along every sightline into the GC observed to date, we suspect it is very widespread. If so, it will greatly change the understanding of the CMZ. To test its ubiquity, however, requires observing along a much wider range of sightlines than has been done to date.
Here we propose to do just that. Such a test has been impossible until very recently, because no sources on sightlines to the CMZ that are suitable for high resolution IR spectroscopy of the ISM have been known, apart from those already observed that pass through the inner portion (r<30 pc) of the CMZ. The vast majority of bright IR sources in the GC are red giants, whose complex photospheric spectra mask the weak interstellar lines of H3+. In the past two years we have developed a procedure to identify likely GC sources with bright dust continua, by combining Spitzer GLIMPSE photometry with 2MASS photometry to exclude red giants and then obtaining low resolution K-band spectroscopy as a check (as the first step is not foolproof). To date we have discovered 10 bright dust-embedded luminous objects scattered across the GC from 100 pc east to 140 pc west. Based on these initial discoveries, we have refined our procedure and have applied for (poor weather) time at Gemini N and at the IRTF which, if granted, should result in the discovery of many more such objects, some likely before we would observe this program.
We began examining the new sightlines last summer with Phoenix, but poor weather severely limited the amount of data we collected. The few new sightlines that we did briefly observe, however, are spectacular. In Fig. 2 spectra of one H3+ line and one line of CO along two of the new sightlines are compared with spectra toward the previously observed GCS 3-2, close to the nucleus. The uppermost spectra (of GCS 3-2) in each panel are typical of all sight lines from the center to 30 pc to the east, and are composed of three sharp components, due to absorption by H3+ and CO in the three intervening spiral arms, and a broad underlying "trough" seen only in H3+. The gas producing the trough is located in the CMZ (see Oka et al. 2005 for details).
The lower two spectra, toward two of the new dust-embedded objects, have entirely different velocity profles. Particularly exciting is the bottom left spectrum, which implies a column density of H3+ much greater than on any other sight line previously observed. This object (iota in Fig. 1) is located between Sgr B1 and B2, a cloud complex that has for decades been a mecca of discovery for radio astronomers. These spectra appear to be the first look into Sgr B in the near-IR; we are unaware of any other observations of this cloud complex in the 1-5µm interval. We are preparing a short paper based on this discovery.
The H3+ spectra shown in Fig. 2 are of the R(1,1)l line, which starts from the lowest rotational level, (J ,K) = (1,1). The velocity profiles in the bottom two spectra are wildly different from what we have seen previously and defy any quick interpretation. Observations of H3+ spectral lines starting from other rotational levels - (1,0), (2,2), and especially the (3,3) metastable level - are urgently needed to determine the temperature and density and other physical and chemical properties of each cloud component. For the sightline near Sgr B which shows a particularly rich spectrum and high temperature (based on our detections of several lines of CO toward it), we will also attempt to discover H3+ in higher metastable levels.
We re-emphasize the importance of H3+ in studying the gaseous interstellar medium in general and the CMZ in particular. H3+ provides information on the ionization rate of the environment, the path length L of the cloud, and the temperature and density of the gas. The first two are unique for H3+. The latter two (T and n) can be determined from other molecules but the simplicity of the chemistry and physics of H3+ allows much more definitive analysis, especially when combined with measurements of other molecules, in particular with CO.
So far our understanding of the CMZ has been limited to sightlines near its center. The proposed observations will give us a much larger scale picture of the interstellar gas in this fascinating region.

We will observe five spectral lines of H3+: R(1, 1)l at 3.71548 µm, R(1, 1)u and R(1, 0) doublet at 3.66808 µm and 3.66852 µm, respectively, R(2, 2)l at 3.62047 µm, and R(3, 3)l at 3.53366 µm. The first four lines are acccessible using filter L2734. For some of our targets the first of the above lines has been observed. For at least one target (iota) we will also include observations of R(4,4) and R(6,6) lines, which originate in metastable levels. Observations of the R(2, 2)l and R(3, 3)l lines are crucial since they give the density and temperature of the environment, respectively. For observing the R(3, 3)l l line, we supplied the filter L2870 five years ago but because of bad weather have barely been able to use it. For observing the interstellar CO 2 - 0 absorption, we will use Phoenix with the K4308 filter. Again, some of our targets have already been observed in 2009A.
Our ten targets have been confirmed by us as suitable for ISM spectroscopy from their lack of photospheric CO absorption. Some of these stars are in or behind the CMZ from our high resolution spectra of the R(1, 1)l line of H3+ obtained as part of GS-2009A-C-6. Others may be in the foreground, but are also useful to study the velocity profiles and density distributions of spiral arms.
In order to obtain quality spectra of the weak absorption ( ~5 %) of H3+ for definitive analysis of the velocity profiles of clouds, a signal to noise ratio of 200 is needed. For observing the stronger CO lines a signal to noise ratio of 100 will suffice. Targets with typical K magnitudes of 10 and L magnitudes of 6.5. The typical estimated times of 30 minutes per L spectral region (including overheads during integration) and 25 minutes per K spectral region are double those from the ETC, but are based based on our experience with Phoenix (incl. examination of past nightlogs) . For the fainter sources, we have reduced the required signal- to-noise ratio to 100 and obtain similar integation times. Overheads are listed as 20 minutes per observation oin the web pages, but we ours have been somewhat less (15 min), perhaps because our targets are close together on the sky. Using the above values we arrive at the observing times in the table. The total on-target observing time for the ten known sourcesis 28.25 hours. It will also be necessary to obtain high S/N spectra of unreddened stars at similar air-masses to our targets, in order to ratio out the many telluric absorption lines. Assuming one standard star spectrum per 3 target spectra and somewhat shorter integrations (but similar overheads), we require an additional 8 hours. Thus our total time request for the ten sources is 36 hours.
We expect that fairly early in 2010A our Gemini Band 3/4 program will find additional dust-embedded sources, in addition to the specific ones whose observations were described above. Conservatively assuming that five such targets are available and that they resemble in brightness the ones in our current list, we will require an additional 18 hours. Hence our total request is for 54 hours. Allocations less than this will still result in a viable program.
To allow for good cancellation of sky lines the observations should not be made at high (>1.5) airmass. During May-July the GC is below this limit for 9 hours per night, and 4 nights will be required. We also can make good use of partial nights. In particular, we could take excellent advantage of second halves of nights in April or May.
IMPORTANT NOTE: Some of the time requested here duplicates time requested through a proposal solelt to the USA TAC (Oka is the PI). Should the US TAC grant X hours of time our request for staff time would be reduced to 54-X hours.

Comets and asteroids are products of binary accretion in the protoplanetary disk of the Sun. They differ primarily in the heliocentric distance (and temperature) at which they formed. By conventional definitions, asteroids are inert rocky or metallic bodies, while comets are ice-rich objects. The vast majority of asteroids are assumed to have formed at high temperatures (500 K - 1000 K) between Mars and Jupiter where they are found today. In contrast, due to their icy composition, all comets were assumed to have originated in the frigid (<50K) outer regions of the solar system. Scientifically, then, the asteroids and comets are interesting as probes of the physical conditions in the protoplanetary disk at two distinct locations. Dynamically, the Tisserand parameter (T_J) is used to discriminate the populations. This is a constant of motion in the circular, restricted three-body (Sun, Jupiter and object) problem. Asteroids have T_J > 3, Jupiter has T_J = 3 and the comets have T_J < 3 (Kresak 1982; Kosai 1992).
Recently, we discovered objects having the dynamical properties of main-belt asteroids (T_J > 3) and the physical properties of comets, including comae and tails caused by on-going mass-loss (Figure 1). We call them "main-belt comets'' (MBCs) to highlight the fact that they have properties of both main-belt asteroids and comets. Physical evidence suggests that the MBCs are true comets in the sense that they are icy bodies in which mass loss is driven by ice sublimation induced by the heat of the Sun (e.g. activity in the best characterized MBC is recurrent and long-lived, as expected for a sublimation source).
Scientific interest in the MBCs lies in their likely origin near (and as probes of conditions at) the snow-line. Dynamical work shows that they cannot be captured from the Kuiper belt or Oort cloud comet reservoirs in the modern Solar system (Fernandez et al. 2002; Levison et al. 2006), but it has been suggested that some might have been captured in a hypothetical, unstable phase in the distant past associated with drastic planetary migration (Gomes et al. 2005). The outer asteroid belt is of additional scientific interest as one of the likely source regions for the Earth's ocean water and other volatiles (Morbidelli et al. 2000).
Only four MBCs are known, one from Gemini data (Hsieh & Jewitt 2006). The most recent discovery, P/2008 R1 Garradd falls in a different region of the main-belt from the other three (Figure 2). It is distinguished by its small perihelion distance (q = 1.7 AU) and dynamically unstable orbit (lifetime of 20-30Myr) that suggests recent emplacement from the outer asteroid belt (Jewitt et al. 2009). Its small perihelion suggests that increased solar insolation drives the activity. The available evidence is consistent with the hypothesis that a large fraction (potentially *all*) outer-belt asteroids are ice-rich. If so, then other asteroids displaced inwards onto eccentric, P/Garradd-like orbits should be susceptible to thermally-induced outgassing. It is this hypothesis that we propose to test.

***Gemini South Update***
We realized that we had not accounted for the fact that new asteroids might be discovered in late 2009 / early 2010A which might be worth observing. The last 5 years have shown an average of about 10 such discoveries per year. Several new asteroid surveys are coming on-line now in both hemispheres which will likely increase the discovery rate over prevous years, so we estimate about 20 new discoveries should be available in 2010A which weren't in our originally submitted target list. Thus, we ask for another 4 hours of Gemini South time (due to the special staff call) to be added to our original time request for the South which was 1.3 hours, for 5.3 hours total. If less than the expected number of discoveries is realized, we will simply widen our search parameters slightly to gain access to more targets. We have resubmitted the Gemini South Staff time portion of this proposal.
****************************
Experimental Design:
We propose to target asteroids with P/Garradd-like orbits in search of mass-loss. The discovery of the third known MBC with Gemini in 2005 was made by employing a similar strategy of observing objects with orbits close to a previously-known MBC (133P/Elst-Pizarro). The a vs. e (semimajor axis vs. eccentricity) plane (Figure 2) shows these P/Garradd-like targets as green circles. The observational strategy is based on one that we have employed at Gemini. The scattering cross-section per unit mass of dust is much larger than the corresponding quantity for gas. Hence, the preferred diagnostic for outgassing is the presence of a dust coma or tail about the target asteroids (as in Figure 1). The measurement therefore requires fine angular resolution (to image near-nucleus dust) and large light-grasp (because the dust is faint). These characteristics make the Gemini telescopes of particular value to the science.
We will image each target asteroid using the r' filter, 1x1 binning (0.14 arcsec. pixel size) and an integration time of 2 minutes. This conveys sensitivity to coma surface brightness at the ~ 26 mag/sq arcsec level, corresponding to derived mass production rates ~0.5 kg/s. Thus, we are easily capable of detecting the activity of the weakest of the currently known MBCs, 176P, which had a tail brightness of 25.3 mag/sq arcsec. We need two consecutive integrations in order to identify the targets from their motion and to distinguish activity associated with our moving targets from faint, stationary background galaxies that might masquerade as cometary activity. The nominal slew and guider set-up time for P2 + GMOS is 6 minutes, while the CCD readout time is about 2 minutes. We will select targets near each other in the sky to further minimize the slew time, and can slew while reading out the 2nd CCD image. Therefore, we budget (integration) + (readout) + (slew and guider time) = (2 + 2) + 2 + 6 = 12 minutes per target, allowing a total of 100 targets to be imaged in our requested 20 hours. To ease scheduling concerns, we include a target list larger than our total sample size, and we have submitted this proposal separately to both Gemini North and South. We ask for a total of 20 hours split across both sites.
In the precursor survey at Gemini (on a different asteroid sample) we detected 1 MBC in about 30 targets. Our new sample should therefore yield several new MBCs, even if the incidence of mass-loss is as low as in the earlier objects (but we expect it to be higher). This would double the sample of known MBCs.
Use of Other Facilities:
The use of smaller telescopes is not feasible because of the resulting loss of sensitivity and need for longer integrations. For example, the KPNO 3.8-m would require integrations longer by a factor of 5 (in equal seeing) and by a factor ~10 given the poorer average seeing in Arizona. The corresponding observing request would be in the range 10 to 20 nights, which seems excessive.
Limited time is also available on the Magellan and MMT telescopes through NOAO. Again, we would require a disproportionate fraction of the available nights on these telescopes to reach sensitivity limits comparable to those available at Gemini.
Previous Use of Facilities Available Through NOAO:
Not applicable.

NGC 7252 is the archetype merger remnant in the local universe. This "elliptical galaxy in formation" was born through the collision of two massive gas rich spiral galaxies some 500 Myr ago (Hibbard & Mihos 1995). The merger set off a massive starburst and the result of the burst is the largest young massive star cluster (YMCs) population of any known galaxy (Miller et al. 1997), hosting 2 clusters more massive 10^7 Mo and dozens above 10^6 Mo (Maraston, Bastian et al. 2004; Bastian et al. 2006). The large number of YMCs formed during the burst and their exceptionally high masses imply that the peak star formation rate during the burst was in excess 1000 Mo/yr, dwarfing any ongoing starburst within hundreds of megaparsecs (Bastian 2008). Star clusters accurately trace the star-formation within the host galaxy, and as such they offer a unique tracer of the star formation history (SFH) of a galaxy, in this case a merger triggered starburst. We propose to obtain optical spectroscopy of the brightest 20 clusters within NGC 7252 in order to age date them, which will constrain the duration of the starburst. This will provide much needed limits for merger simulations and in turn will enhance our knowledge of galaxy evolution.
The duration of a starburst is an important quantity to measure. This, along with the intensity of the SFR, will determine what fraction of the gas within the progenitor galaxies will be turned into stars, which in turn will dominate the light of the newly born galaxy for 100s of Myr. We have placed some initial constrains in the starburst galaxy NGC 45, where through the use of the stellar cluster population we determined that the current starburst has lasted for more than 200 Myr (Bastian 2008). Additionally, determining the sites and timescales of cluster formation during a merger .are the key diagnostics in determining whether models including shock induced or density threshold star formation models are the most accurate (Barnes 2004; Chien et al. 2007)
Over the past few years, our team has been developing techniques to accurately age date stellar clusters through optical spectroscopy. We have constructed algorithms to obtain ages that are not affected by S/N (although of course low S/N tranlates to larger age uncertanties - but we have removed all systematics) and that have proved robust against photometric age dating (Trancho, Bastian et al. 2007a,b). In their seminal study, Schweizer & Seitzer (1998) obtained spectroscopy of 8 clusters in NGC 7252, and were able to measure radial velocities for all of them and in turn measure the total mass of the galaxy. However, as their data were obtained with a 4m class telescope,the S/N was only adequate to accurately age date two of the brightest clusters, W3 and W6. Both clusters have an age of 500+-100 Myr. With the proposed data, we will be able to significantly expand this work by age dating the brightest 20 clusters, therefore defining the duration of the starburst . These data will complement existing HST WFPC2 imaging, along with deep WFC3 imaging that will be obtained later this year by our team (already approved), and cutting edge numerical simulations of the merger that include cluster formation and evolution being carried out by our team (currently in progress).
Our team has considerable expertise in the use of Gemini GMOS spectroscopy of young stellar clusters and their use to trace galaxy evolution. In Trancho, Bastian et al. (2007a,b) we studied clusters in the ongoing merger/starburst NGC 3256 and in Bastian, Trancho et al. (2009) we applied similar techniques to the closest major merger, the Antennae galaxies. Additionally, in Bastian et al. (2008) and Konstantopoulos, Bastian et al. (2008,2009) we used the techniques that we developed on the spiral galaxy M51 and nearby starburst M82, respectively. Finally, in Trancho, Bastian et al. (2010, in prep) we are studying the clusters in the intergalactic debris of the multiple mergers of Stephan's Quintet, and in Konstantopoulos, Trancho, & Bastian (2010, in prep) we are investigating the massive interacting spiral NGC 6872. Since we have all of the tools in place to reduce and analyze the data, we expect to be able to publish our results within a year of data being taken.

The goals is to obtain ages, metalicities and radial velocities for globular clusters with 17< V < 21.5 using the MOS mode of GMOS. We will use the B600 grating in order to measure the spectral indices between 4000 and 6000 A.
According to the GMOS ITC a signal-to-noise of ~10 per pixel can be reached for a point source of V=21.0 with an exposure time of 4 hours (3600 sec x 4) using the following parameters: A0III spectrum, 70%-ile image quality (about 0.8"), 70%-ile cloud cover (photometric), and 70%-ile sky brightness (grey), airmass 1.5, B600 grating, 0.75" slit width, slow read mode, and binned 4x2 to critically sample the expected image quality. Grey sky brightness was used to simulate the effects of the galaxy background under the clusters, but the observations should be done under 50%-ile (dark) conditions because sky brightness severely reduces S/N in the blue. Higher S/N can be obtained against lower backgrounds. Our data on NGC3256 and NGC4038 (Trancho et al 2007a,b and Bastian et el 2009) confirm these sensitivities and have shown that we can determine useful radial velocities,ages and metallicities from spectra of this quality. For line index analyses, the spectra of several faint clusters will have to be averaged together for comparison with brighter clusters and the nucleus. We need pre-imaging in only one filter g (2X300 s) Assuming 15 minutes efficiency per setup (typical for 2009A observing) each of the two MOS fields will require about 5 hours. Therefore, we request 10 hours.

It is well known that galaxy interactions and merger events play an important role on the evolution of the galaxies and in the stellar formation history. Interactions have been sugested as the drivers of very violent events of star formation, producing some of the most luminous objects in the Universe [2]. It has been suggested that strong interactions and mergers may be also responsible for the triggering and feeding of nuclear activity, as observed in Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN). However, this issue is still controversial and poorly understood. An excess of AGN has been observed in interacting systems in comparison with isolated ones [3], but at lower luminosities (log(L) ~10-11 log(Lsun)) there is no evidence of such an AGN excess [4],[5]. This apparent controversy can be explained by selection effects [6], but such deficiency can be also due to the presence of circumnuclear star formation that masks the signature of a weak AGN [7],[8].
The study of galaxies in pairs thus provides useful insights about the resulting effects of interactions on different levels. Galaxies with small companions can be as violently disrupted as galaxy pairs of the same size, inviting questions about the nature and time scale of the interacting process. In some cases, long tails appear and condensations of matter can be observed at the end of or along the disrupted arm, proposed s candidates for the so called progenitors of Tidal Dwarf Galaxies [9],[10]. If such objects are long lived, they can act as an additional contribution to the orginal population of primordial dwarfs, therefore changing the constraints in cosmological and galaxy evolution models. The morphological similarities between these interacting pairs and merging/interacting galaxies at high redshift also indicates that expanding our detailed knowledge of this class of galaxies in the nearby Universe may provide important information for comparison studies of more distant galaxies.
The three main goals for this programme are (1) confirm that candidates are actually physical pairs by measuring the redshift of both components; (2) identify the nature of the nuclear activity in both components (AGN/Starburst) using emission line ratios; (3) study the underlying stellar population using the continuum shape and main absorption lines. As these objects are reasonably bright for an 8-m class telescope, morphological typing and bulge/disk decomposition can be performed as well, using the acquisition images.
Our sample has been selected from the Arp & Madore [1] morphological class I (interacting spirals with small companions), cross-correlating with the IRAS 60 and 100mu catalogues, to select objects in the active infrared phase. This sample is, therefore, biases towards objects presenting starformation and/or activity, but the lack of basic information (morphological types, magnitudes, redshift) for these objects make it unfeasible to start with an unbiased sample. Once the "active" sample has been obtained, the control sample can be derived from the AM I class list that do not show infrared emission.
This project was started in 2007 with "poor-weather' programme GS-2007B-Q-240. Thirteen systems (30 galaxies) were observed. Seven were confirmed as physical pairs/systems. Two objects show signs of interaction, but the companion could not be identified. The redshift of the galaxies ranged from 0.014 to 0.098. The stellar population was obtained following [15], and luminosity weighted stellar ages range from 6.4 < log(t) < 10.5. Of the 30 objects, 10 show evidence of AGN activity in the nuclear spectrum, four show no signs of emission lines, and the remaining are clearly star-forming galaxies. Fig.1 shows an example of the stellar population fitting. Not all the AGN candidates are found in interacting systems, but six of the seven confirmed systems contain at least one AGN candidate. It is crucial to note here that without the proper subtraction of the underlying stellar population, at least half of the low luminosity AGNs would have been missed. This is likely why some previous studies of similar objects [7],[13] indicate such a lower percentage of AGNs, as only the more active nuclei can be detected on top of the stellar population spectrum. Fig.2 shows a preliminary line-ratio diagramme for the objects in our sample.
For this project we selected only pairs with no confirmation as actual physical pairs in order to extend the existing samples for this class of galaxies [7],[11],[12],[13]. The results from this survey can be followed up by several different projects: more detailed chemical and kinematic studies of individual pairs [14], imaging +MOS investigation of the environment (several of these galaxies seem to be part of poor groups, with many low surface brightness galaxies or dwarf companions), higher spatial resolution IFU observations of individual objects.

These pairs are less than 3arcmin wide, so both objects can be placed in the GMOS longslit in the same pointing. Using the R150 grating, the redshift can be obtained from the bright emission lines (Halfa, Hbeta, [OIII], [OII]) and/or from prominent absorption lines such as CaII or MgI). Resolution with the R150 is enough to spectrally resolve the emission lines required for determining the activity class (AGN/Starburst), and provides the spectral coverage needed for the stellar population studies.
All three goals can be obtained from a single observation of each pair using GMOS in longslit mode with the R150 grating and 0.5arcsec slit (emission lines such as Halfa+[NII], Hbeta+ [OIII], higher H lines up to the Balmer jump, [OII], [SII]; CaII or MgI absorption lines) . In our 2007B programme, for a central magnitude ~16mag, we obtained S/N~10 in the continuum with 4x900sec under IQ=85-Any/CC=70-90/SB=80-Any conditions. A few targets (<15mag) can be observed under SB=Any. Magnitudes are more often only known for the primary galaxy, some of the candidate companions are quite faint (R>17) or simply unknown, and may require CC=50-70/SB=50 conditions. Many of these objects do not have bright guide stars available to allow observing both galaxies in a single pointing. Definition of the actual observing constraints for individual targets is left for PhaseII. We have however insured that enough targets have a 12.8mag or brigther guide star available for at least one slit PA.
To optimize inclusion in the queue, a second grating choice is also proposed, although less efficient. Using the B600/R400 gratings (almost always available), two settings centred at 480 and 590 nm rest wavelength will provide the same information as above. The increase in resolution allows for using the 1.5 or 2.0arcsec slit, reducing the slit losses on poor seeing conditions, so the exposure times remain roughly the same.
Taking in to account acquisition and overheads, the required total time to observe 20-22 pairs with the R150 setup will be 28hrs. The target list contains more candidates, in order to provide a larger pool for the queue planning.
Our group has large experience in optical stellar population, nuclear activity and star formation studies. We have also acquired very good experience with GMOS acquisition and data reduction for these studies (see previous allocation), so we can optimize the observational setup and provide quick feedback on observed targets to adapt to the weather conditions and changes in instrumental configuration.

In the unified model of active galactic nuclei (AGNs), the differences between objects of types 1 and 2 are explained by a torus of dust and gas that obscures the broad-line gas from some viewing angles while leaving it exposed from others. Various lines of evidence, notably the detection of polarized broad emission lines in type 2 objects (Antonucci & Miller 1985), support the hypothesis of anisotropic obscuration, but the chemistry, structure, and origin of the torus, as well as the true extent of its role in fuelling and unifying the various types of AGN, remain the subject of intense study.
In our most recent paper, we constructed 2 - 20 micron SEDs of Seyfert galaxies at high spatial resolution (Ramos Almeida et al. 2009). By fitting clumpy torus models to the SEDs, we could investigate the properies of the torus and their relation to unified model predictions. We found, for instance, that edge-on views of the torus are indeed more probable for type 2 Seyferts, and that much of the X-ray absorbing gas is located within the dust sublimation radius. This work also suggests that, contrary to strong unification, torus properties are intrinsically different between Seyferts of types 1 and 2: Seyfert 2s reprocess incident nuclear radiation more efficiently than type 1s, probably as a result of having a higher dust covering fraction.
Our models are fit to photometric data, but make predictions of the strength of the 10 and 20 micron silicate features for each galaxy. The paper includes 17 galaxies, and we have ground-based spectroscopy of 10 with which we can test the robustness of the models. However, the spectroscopic sample does not include some of the most interesting objects - those Sy2 galaxies in which the torus models predict the 10 micron silicate feature to appear in *emission*. This is counterintuitive; in the simplest realizations of the unified model, an edge-on view through cool dust in the torus causes a prominent absorption feature in type 2 AGNs. In type 1 AGNs, where hot dust at the inner surface of the torus is revealed, models often predict strong silicate emission (e.g., Efstathiou & Rowan-Robinson 1995; Granato & Danese 1994), depending on the torus geometry.
Rather surprising, then, has been the discovery by Spitzer of type 2 objects with silicate emission bands: notably, the average type 2 QSO (Sturm et al. 2006), and a handful of Seyferts in Shi et al. 2006. For type 1 Seyferts with silicate emission, the temperatures implied by the features suggest that the emitting dust is rather cool, ~300 K, and it has been argued that much of the silicate emission must arise in the narrow-line region (NLR) of the galaxy, rather than in the hot inner region of the torus. If this is the case, it is presumably also true for the silicate emission in the type 2 objects.
To test this hypothesis, we combined Gemini and Spitzer data on NGC 2110, the closest known type 2 object with silicate emission features, using Gemini's spatial resolution to place by far the tightest limit yet on the location of the silicate-emitting region (<32 pc; Mason et al. 2009). While this distance is still consistent with dusty NLR models (Schweitzer et al. 2008), we found that the best fitting clumpy torus models both required the edge-on torus characteristic of type 2 objects, *and* produced silicate emission at 10 and 20 microns. The data required that the torus be flatter than usually assumed, with only a few clouds along the line of sight.
At the time of writing, NGC 2110 is the only object both close and bright enough for this kind of detailed dissection to be feasible. To test the predictions of our SED modelling, and to potentially uncover more nearby, silicate-emitting type 2 AGN, we propose T-ReCS N band spectroscopy of two Seyfert 2s from the Ramos Almeida et al. sample which are predicted to have a significant silicate emission feature. Uncovering more of these objects will allow us to start a more systematic investigation of their properties and their place within unified schemes. It will also be an important validation of the models. If we do not, it will help us to understand the limitations of the modelling. The prediction of silicate emission is driven by the NIR/MIR flux ratio - are the "torus" NIR fluxes contaminated by surrounding emission, even at HST/AO spatial resolution? Or will improvements to the models, such as an intercloud medium, improve the match to the data? Whatever the result, T-ReCS spectroscopy of these potentially anomalous nuclei, at the subarcsecond spatial resolution that minimises contamination from non-torus emission, promises a step forward in our understanding of the unified model of active galaxies

The fluxes of the nuclear point sources in these galaxies have been published by Ramos Almeida et al. (2009). NGC5128 has an 8.8 micron flux density of 710 mJy, and NGC7582, 195 mJy. Both objects should be straightforward targets for T-ReCS.
The 5 sigma 30 minute sensitivity for T-ReCS N band spectroscopy is about 15 mJy at 9 microns and 25 mJy at 12 microns. In 15 minutes on-source (approx. 1.25 hours total, including acquisition), we can expect S/N ~ 25 or more over the whole band for NGC 7582, and some very nice data indeed on NGC 5128. This will be sufficient to detect the fairly strong silicate emission features predicted by Ramos Almeida et al. No special calibrations are needed for this program beyond the baseline telluric standards, so we ask for a total of 2.5 hours.
Although spatial resolution is important for this project, because both galaxies show extended emission in the MIR, we can tolerate IQ slightly worse than diffraction limited (IQ85). Clear skies are necessary and WV50 will help with telluric cancellation and useful wavelength coverage.

One century after the discovery of strong emission lines in the center of NGC1068, galactic nuclei are still mysterious places. The enormous energy output detected in many galactic nuclei is one of the key issues in the study of galaxies and their evolution, several fundamental questions remaining unsolved. Is accretion onto super-massive black holes (SMBH) just a co-evolving phenomenon or a necessary partner of the circumnuclear star formation? What is the relationship of the fueling mechanisms to galaxy evolution? What astrophysics sets the mass ratio of the gas turned into stars compared to the gas accreted by the SMBH at the observed value of ~1000? Once in the galaxy, how is gas transported from the bulge scale to the SMBH's accretion disk? We will focus in addressing the last two questions studying the best resolved AGN.
From the observational point of view, disentangling the kinematical components of galaxies is a major puzzle. Developed stages of nuclear fueling at galactic centers do not provide sufficient clues to their origin, since the morphological signatures of the triggering mechanism are smeared out on the timescale of a few orbital revolutions of the galaxy core. In particular at some active galaxies, off-axis kinematical centers and outflows are not uncommon due to minor mergers, strong barred gravitational potentials and AGN feedback. Representatives of this peculiarity are NGC3227 (Arribas & Mediavilla 1994), NGC1068 (Arribas+,1996), NGC1672 (Diaz+,1999) and M83 (Mast+,2006), among many others. In M83 the investigation of the peculiar kinematics of the central regions, led to the detection of an obscured secondary nucleus (Diaz+,2006).
Cen-A is the nearest active galaxy and the nearest evolved major merger (an elliptical galaxy with a large disk inside). It provides an unique opportunity to investigate observationally the details of the complex kinematics and dynamical evolution of these objects. The importance of measuring CenA's SMBH mass becomes evident if we consider the two present-day modes of black-hole activity: i) one associated with Seyfert galaxies and QSOs -the SMBH radiates strongly, belongs to the lower mass kind (<1E8 Msun), lives in the lower mass galaxies (<1E11 Msun), and is statistically associated with star formation; ii) the second is associated with radio galaxies -the accretion is radiatively inefficient, the mass of the SMBH is very large (>1E8), it resides in elliptical galaxies, and there is little circumnuclear star formation. The nearest active system seems not to clearly fit within any of these families, due to the transition morphology of the host NGC5128 and the apparently low mass of the SMBH. Although emission from a dusty torus around the central radio source was found by Radomski+ (2008), the MIR circumnuclear emission is coincident with the Pa_alpha knots, implying that a star-fomation disk is also present down to a few arcseconds radius (Alexander+,1999). Furthermore, Marconi+(2001) suggest that the H_2 structure shows kinematical evidence consistent with a nuclear bar fueling the AGN. The nucleus has been observed in the NIR by various teams, at low and moderate spectral resolution. The derived values for the SMBH mass have shown a decreasing trend in time: 2.0E8 (Marconi+,2001, ISAAC@VLT, R~9000, H&K-bands); 2.4-1.5E8 (Silge+,2005, GNIRS@Gemini-S, R~1600, K-band); 10-6.7E7 (Marconi+,2006, STIS@HST, R~1000, I-band); 6.1E7 (Haring+,2006, NAOS-CONICA@VLT, R~1500, H-band); 4.5E7 (Neumayer+,2007, SINFONI@VLT, R~4000, K-band). The observation of the innermost gas motion will be the clue towards converging to a definite value for the SMBH mass. The gas motions are extremely complex, as noted in the studies above. A key element towards the determination of the SMBH mass is the ability to discriminate between kinematical components close to the core. Currently the claimed rotating disk at Cen-A's core has major axis closely align with the outflow axis. Therefore any mass determination with medium resolution spectroscopy of the gaseous component seems still unreliable (see Figure 1 below, Neumayer+,2007). We aim to answer whether the gas kinematics are consistent with one or more rotating disks. The technique to achieve this is high spectral resolution. Phoenix at Gemini-S provides an unique opportunity (which might be the last since the instrument is to be removed in 2011), due to its high spectral resolution, perfectly coupled to the light gathering power and IR capabilities of the Gemini 8m telescopes.
Resolving the central kinematics would solve the gaseous disk rotation-orbit anisotropy-outflow degeneracy and greatly improve the knowledge about CenA. The Phoenix data will also allow us to apply state of the art numerical modeling to constrain the core growth and SMBH formation in one of the nearest 'elliptical' galaxies. We have already been successful in studying the dynamics of peculiar galactic nuclei and star forming regions from Gemini NIR imaging (Diaz+,2004, Dottori+,2005) and NIR 3D spectroscopy (Diaz+,2006, Blum+,2009). We are also experienced in the proposed use of long slit sequential mapping (Diaz+,1999; Winge+,1999), state of the art semi-analytical modeling (Gimeno 2007) and n-body numerical modeling (Diaz+,2000, Rodrigues, Dottori, Diaz+2009).

Dust obscuration poses serious constraints for accurate description of the kinematics via optical emission lines specially in the central regions of merging galaxies. NIR observing must be employed to accurately describe the kinematics in these regions. These observations will we done in three central wavelenghts in order to probe the behaviour of different gas species.
Using the Phoenix ITC with the photometric information of NGC5128 nucleus (Kmag=10.9, Watson+1996,AJ112,534), with 0".085~1.19pc and 1.46 km/s pixels, resolution R=50000 and S/N~15 (at the continuum level), we expect to map the Pa_beta, [FeII]1.644um and H_2(1-0)_S(1)@2.1212um line emissions (at expected S/N>50/pixel) with an average kinematical uncertainty of 1km/s. Modeled convolution of equal flux gaussian components indicates that we could separate the observed outflow (~80km/s at 0.5") from the keplerian rotation around a SMBH as small as 2E5_Msun (~10km/s at 0.5"). The second setting, centered on the H_2(1-0)_S(1) emission line, will aim to map the molecular gas kinematics and constrain the existence and strength of the possible barlike structure.
Note on the extra staff allocation required: Marconi+(2001,Apj549,915) found a strong mismatch between the photometric major axis of the [Fe II] gas disk at the HST narrow band images respect to its kinematical major axis; we want to sample the [FeII]1.644um velocity distribution and [FeII]/Pab ratio in order to reveal the nature of this putative disk. These can be used to detect the transition between pure photoionization and shock ionization due to supernovas (Rodriguez-Ardila+2004,AA425,457).
Fig.1 shows the slit arrangement over a HST K image, with the Pa_alpha contours. The orientation of the slits was chosen to match the most plausible kinematical axis. The kinematic components at the inner 1".25 will be fully mapped achieving unprecedented level of detail of the central kinematics of this galaxy. Another two positions are set along the radio jet position angle and perpendicular to it, respectively.
Sky subtraction will be done with sky exposures taken at 150" distance from the base position (well outside the galaxy body), with the PWFS2 set to 'freeze'.
The exposure times were computed with Phoenix ITC for continuum S/N~15/pixel which is sufficient for our purposes. All observations will be performed with the 0".25 slit, allowing proper Nyquist sampling of a 0".5 seeing disk (perpendicular to the slit).

While these will be some of the first observations of the structure of a galaxy nucleus done with Phoenix, the technique has been succesfully used for studying with high resolution the kinematics of H2 and FeII nebular emission gas in protoplanetary nebulae (Hrvinak+2008,ApJ688,327), Eta Car ejecta (Smith2006,Apj644,1151) and LMC starforming regions (GS-2008B-Q-81).

Super star clusters (SSCs) represent an extreme mode of star formation, and it is becoming clear that these massive clusters are abundant in galaxies with high star formation rates. As such, they play a fundamental role in the large scale star formation process, and probably in the formation of galaxies themselves. However, the physical conditions that give rise to SSCs are not well-constrained. For example, it remains unclear whether SSCs are the products of peculiar physical conditions, or they simply arise from the statistical population of the cluster mass function toward high masses. To address this point, it is important to carry out detailed studies of the environment where they are formed, including the ISM and local kinematic properties. It is particularly useful to examine young, un-evolved galaxies, where the physical conditions are believed to be pristine and other galactic evolutionary effects (eg. spiral arms density waves, mergers) have not come into play. The fundamental question is, then, whether the cluster formation arises stocastically, or it is triggered and propagates in scales of tens to a few hundred parsecs. Determining the physical conditions of the ISM around newly born SSCs is critical to answering this question. UM 461, at ~ 15 Mpc, is an extreme case of a compact HII galaxy whose integrated properties show definite evidence of youth: i) an optical spectrum dominated by strong emission lines (Kehrig et al 2004), ii) very blue UBVcolors, and the bluest VRI colors (Telles & Terlevich 1997), and iii) no evidence of an old stellar population (Westera et al 2004). Combined with its low metal content (12+log O/H = 7.7), this lack of red stars is a strong indication that this galaxy has only recently significantly begun to form stars. The main star forming knot in UM 461, where the integrated properties are derived, is composed of one single SSC (Figure 1), and our proposed observations can reveal any sub-structure if present. Therefore, it is crucial to obtain observations with the high spatial resolution in order to identify the elementary entities that constitute the starburst and determine their properties.
HII galaxies offer the unique opportunity to test ideas about the recycling of the interstellar medium, because they are simple systems as compared to other, more massive galaxies. As large part of their interstellar medium is photoionized, it is easy to derive abundances from emission lines in the optical. These abundances represent the interstellar medium as it is now, together with its possible heterogeneities. The least evolved HII galaxies, e.g. the lowest abundances ones, deserve a particular attention, because they only used up a low fraction of their gas content to turn it into stars: any injection of newly formed material represents a much higher fraction of the present abundances than at higher metallicities, and is therefore much more easily detected.
We wish to take advantage of the capacities of the IFU to map the abundances over the extension of the starburst of UM 461, on a much finer spatial grid. The selected target is particularly interesting for it consists of one of the most extreme cases of HII galaxies in the sense of its extreme compactness, low luminosity, low integrated oxygen abundance. The combination of the spatial variations of different elements thus provides some insight in the question of the recycling time of the interstellar medium, as well as on the origin of the primary nitrogen detected at low metalicities. The recycling of the nitrogen originating from AGB stars does not present severe complications - it should happen during a planetary nebula lifetime, e.g. ~ 10^4 years. The recycling of the oxygen as well as the fraction of nitrogen originating in massive stars, however, is more complicated: The explosion of supernovas creates hot bubbles of coronal gas that takes a very long time to cool down , due to the lack of emission lines in such high temperature plasma. With the help of plasma instabilities, Tenorio Tagle (1996) evaluate the cooling time to a few 10^7 years - which should be the recycling time from oxygen. Some authors (e.g. Stasinska & Izotov 2003), however, claim to have found evidence for self enrichment in oxygen of HII regions - which would imply a much quicker recycling time. The Tenorio-Tagle model for instance, implies in a very homogeneous oxygen abundance spatial repartition. Self enrichment on the other hand, is a local phenomenon, which should enhance heterogeneities in the oxygen abundance. As far as nitrogen is concerned, its enrichment should be mainly local, near the places of stellar formation, as far as the fraction originating in AGB stars, and thus cause abundances heterogeneities. The contribution from massive stars on the other hand should follow the spatial patterns of oxygen. In practice, we plan to derive abundances for each point covered by a fiber, using strong lines indicators , based on the [OIII]4959,5007+[OII]3727 / Hbeta,[NII]6583/[OII]3727, [OII]3727/[OIII]4959,5007, NII/Halpha (Pilyugin 2003).
