During 2005B (GS-2005B-Q-19 program) we observed three galaxies with full wavelength coverage (3500-7000 A) with the use of two gratings (B600 and R600). With the data we were able to evaluate the instrumental setup to achieve our scientific goals. Fig. 2 shows one fiber spectrum of UM 408. In the figure the strong and weak lines are identified and measurable. In this particular case, even the [OIII] 4363 A line is identified which will permit to determine the distribution of the effective electron temperature, an important parameter for direct determination of elemental abundances.
The excellent spatial resolution combined with the great light gathering power of GMOS-S+IFU gave us the first sight of, previously undetected, sub-structure in the star forming region of this extreme compact HII galaxy. With this type of observation we will be able to identify the elementary entities of which the starburst consists. That will give us an insight of the process of star formation at these scales. We require the Gemini telescope + GMOS-S and IFU because the spatial resolution we can reach is in the order of tens of parscec (at 15 Mpc, the 0.2arcsec fiber provide a physical resolution of < 20 pc) and because the faintness of the emission lines outside the center of the star formation region.
We wish to obtain at least [OII] 3727, [OIII] 4959, 5007, [NII] 6583, Halpha and Hbeta. We will thus have to make two observations for each galaxy, a blue one with the B600 grating centered at 435nm, a red one with the R600 grating centered at 575nm. We will derive abundances maps from strong lines indicators, R_23 (Pagel 1979) or more sofisticated methods, like P (Pilyugin 2000) for oxygen, and [NII]/[OII] to derive the N/O ratio. Halpha and Hbeta will be used to map the reddening, and eventually the spatial variations that might affect the [NII]/[OII] lines ratio. We already have three galaxies observed with two one gratings, but with more extended or multiple star clusters in their star forming regions. We wish to complete the programme by observing the most compact star forming knot in the sample as well as the most intense ionizing source. The initial proposed sample of 4 galaxies will be necessary to investigate the universality of our results with respect to the starburst morphology and environment.
To calculate the needed on-source exposure time, we assumed a typical surface brightness of 20 mag/arcsec^2 in V. To have a flux measurement error less than 10-20%, we require a minimum S/N>20 per fiber in [OII] 3727 (which is the most critical line). With the B600 grating, centered at 435nm, with CC=70%, SB=50% and IQ=70%, airmass < 1.3, we need 4x30minutes of on-source exposure per UM 461, assuming a HII region (Orion nebulae) spectrum. In summary, for B600 we require 18min (setup)+(4x30min on-source exp) + (4x2.5min readout) + (3*3min CuAr arc) + (3*2.5min Arc readout) =165min. In addition, we need a spectrophotometric standard star for flux calibration observed before and or after the science observation. This will require additional 30 min. The total time required with B600 is 195 min or 3.3 hours.
In the red (R600 grating) using the same observing constrains, we need to observe each galaxy 4x30min, in order to obtain a S/N > 10 per fibre in [NII] 6583. Then the total time with R600 is: 18 min(setup)+(4x30min on-source exp.) + (4x2.5min readout) + (3x3min CuAr arc) + (3x2.5min Arc readout)=165 min. Also we will required an observation of spectrophotometric standard stars (before or after). This require additinal 30 min. The total time requested for UM 461 with R600 is 195 min or 3.3 hours. For this project we require a total of 6.6 hours.

A large fraction of the baryonic mass of the Galaxy is contained in the bulge. Understanding its formation history is crucial before any claims can be made how the Galaxy (or galaxies in general) formed. Two main scenarios have been proposed to explain bulges of spirals [8]. In the "classical" scenario most stars originate in a short phase of Star Formation (SF) when the universe was only a few Gyr old and bulge formation may precede that of the disk. In ?pseudobulges? stars form in the disk, over an extended period of time. The bulge results from the secular evolution of the disk driven by the development of a bar or minor mergers. Hence, one expects classical bulges to be made almost exclusively of old stars, while stars in pseudobulges would have an age spread comparable to the Hubble time. Detailed chemical compositions are crucial to study the origin and evolution of stellar populations. Since different elements are synthesized in different stars by different processes, abundance ratios are sensitive to the time-scales of SF and Initial Mass Function.
So far the SF history and chemical enrichment of the bulge is traced mostly by the abundance patterns in its field population [12,20,14]. The observed high [Alpha/Fe] ratio suggests an early and very short SF period [10,4] (galactic bulge formed more rapidly than the thin, and perhaps even the thick disk [13]). [O/Fe] ratios of bulge stars with those of thin and thick disks were compared in [22,23]. Bulge ratios appeared systematically higher than disk ones, arguing against appreciable bulge contamination by migration from the thick disk. A similar consideration was put forward by [10], based on the much higher values of their [Na/Fe], [Mg/Fe] and [Al/Fe] ratios in bulge stars. While field stars give us direct information about the bulge formation mechanism, they are affected by number of uncertainties, like distance and possible age spread. Globular cluster stars offer known distance and age, a chemical homogeneity and are viable tracers of the underlying bulge population. Moreover, the most metal rich clusters are only present in the bulge direction and are fundamental calibrators for the stellar and stellar populations models. At the present moment only a few bulge/disk clusters (according to classification in [11]) have been observed with high resolution spectroscopy (examples in [15,16,21,1]).
Recently, several highly obscured, newly discovered or re-classified globular clusters have been added to the 150 objects in [5] based mainly on the large scale near or mid-infrared surveys such as 2MASS and GLIMPSE [6,7,17,3,18,19]. Their morphology, distances, ages, masses and metallicities need to be investigated in order to compare them with other galactic globular clusters and to estimate their impact on the galactic globular cluster sub-systems. Here we propose to obtain high resolution Phoenix spectroscopy of selected red giant stars of two newly discovered globular clusters: 2MASS GC02 and Mercer 5. Both are most probably located in the inner disk/bulge of the Galaxy. 2MASS GC02 is located within 10 deg from the Galactic center, being a bulge cluster according to [2]. Mercer 5 is physically located at the inner edge of the thin disk and the transition region with the bulge. (Also falls in the zone of the ?missing? globulars toward the central region of the Milky Way [9]). These objects are practically invisible at optical wavelengths. Their chemical composition has never been studied with high resolution spectroscopy. The light gathering power of Gemini South 8m telescope and the spectral resolution of Phoenix provide an unique combination to approach this problem. (Especially in the light of the expected Phoenix de-commissioning after 2010A.)
In summary: this project will derive accurate chemical abundances and [Alpha/Fe] ratios in order to trace chemical enrichment of these newly discovered and poorly studied clusters. This will allow to: (i) put them in the position-abundance plane of the inner Galaxy, extending the existing sample to the very central regions of the Milky Way; (ii) better constrain their membership in globular clusters sub-systems; (iii) provide new insight of bulge formation, using star clusters as test particles.

The clusters in our sample are heavily reddened and not observable at optical wavelengths making the near-infrared spectral range the only choice. PHOENIX at GEMINI offers a combination of large telescope (the typical magnitude range of our objects is 10-11 mag in H) and the high spectral resolution needed for accurate abundance determination. To derive Fe, C, O, Ti and N in the cluster a minimum 4 of giants per cluster needs to be observed through the H6420 filter. These 4 red giants per cluster are selected on the base of J,H,Ks SofI, NTT photometry and low resolution SofI, NTT (R~1500 A) and ISAAC (R~500 A) spectroscopy and all of them are confirmed cluster members (see for example Table 1 from [2]).
According to the Phoenix ITC, for the individulal cluster stars, assuming Teff=3600K, seeing 0.8?, airmass 1.2, slit =0.34?, the total integration time to reach S/N~60 per pixel is 5h 8min for 2MASS GC02 (4 stars, including overheads) and 5h 59min (5 stars, including overheads) for Mercer 5. For each individual giant we plan to split the integration time in individual exposures nodding on slit through an ABBA cycle. In summary the time needed is 11h 7min for both objects. Including overheads for observation of brigth radial velocity standard we are asking for 11.5 hours.
The proposed observations require standard strategy and do require only one radial velocity standard apart from the standard calibrations.
The team has extensive experience using Gemini Near-IR data and studying highly-reddened newly discovered clusters in our Galaxy.

There are two main sources for extended diffuse radio emission in cluster not associated with an AGN. They could either be radio halos or radio relics. Radio halos are extended and cluster wide steep radio sources (> 500 Mpc). Radio relics on the other hand were previously associated with an AGN. After the AGN turned off the radio plasma de-attached from the galaxy and drifted away forming a diffuse and steep radio source. It is possible that these two types of extended radio sources are related in the sense that radio relics provide the basic seed of relativistic particles needed to power a radio halo (see for example Roettiger et al.,1999 ApJ,518, 603. Therefore, they can help us to understand the late phases in the evolution of the AGNs.
Abell 13 contains a very interesting radio relic (Slee et al., 2001, AJ, 122, 1172). Most radio relics are located away from the cluster center. However this radio source is located close to the first rank galaxy and forms a subclass of these relics (Giovannini & Feretti, 2004, J. Korean Astron. Soc., 37, 323). Recently Juet et al. (2008, ApJ, 672, 138) combined new X-ray Chandra data with archival radio and optical data in order to determine the origin of this relic. They found the following main results. First, they find evidence in the X-ray data that the cluster is merging. These findings are in agreement with a bimodal distribution in the 37 galaxy velocities reported by Fadda et al. (1996, ApJ, 473, 670). Second they find a spatial coincidence between the relic and the presence of cooler X-ray gas. Juet et al (2008) propose two models for explaining these properties. One model proposes buoyancy as the driver. The second model proposes a displacement of gas and radio emission produced by a merger.
Thus, a merger is key in understanding these two models. A recent cluster-cluster merger would have produced a shock and large-scale bulk flow motions of gas. If one of these two clusters has a cooling flow or a cold region at the core, then the merger probably displaced it or destroyed it as has been seen in numerical simulations (i.e., Gomez et al 2002, ApJ, 569, 122) and on observations (Markevitch et al. 2000, ApJ, 541, 542) of cold fronts. In our case, we can assume that the cluster with the disrupted cold core had a dying AGN at its center. Then, as the merger disrupted the cooling flow or the cold center, the cold gas could have been uplifted due to buoyancy carrying with it the disrupted radio emitting plasma. It could also be that the merger separated the galaxy from the AGN emission due to the large scale flow bulk flow motion. The only way to distinguish between the models is by determining the details of the merger such as mass ratio, epoch, and viewing angle. In this way, we can derive what type of shocks and/or bulk flow motions were produced and validate the buoyancy or ram pressure models.
We have been able to do this by gathering about 60 galaxy velocities and good X-ray data (Gomez et al. 2000, ApJ, 540, 726). We propose to do the same with this cluster by gathering over 50 new velocities (Fig 1). Thus, we will combine the observed velocity distribution with the velocity distribution derived from numerical simulations of cluster mergers. In this way, we can identify the most likely simulations that reproduce the observed distribution. In addition, we refine the set of possible models by comparing the observed X-ray properties with the simulations. We intend to do the same for Abell 13.
The buoyant model for the origin of the radio relic in Abell 13 is not possible if there were large bulk flow motions (up to 4000 km/s with a mean of 1200 km/s) in the cluster. These bulk flow motions typically survive for a few Gigayears after core crossing and appear at the core of the merging clusters (Roettiger et al. 1996, ApJ, 473, 651). At these velocities the ram pressure is so high that they can bend radio jets so it is reasonable to expect that they would dominate over buoyancy forces as the main mechanisms for displacing the radio emitting plasma (buoyancy only would need a velocity of 400-500 km/s). Only head-on small mass ratio mergers ( ie. 1:1 o 1:2) produce this large bulk flow motions. So if the merger is a 1:4 or a 1:8 then the buoyancy models are the most likely candidates.

We propose to obtain over 50 new velocities for Abell 13. Figure 1 shows the intend pointing. Our targets are all brighter than r=19.5. All objects have public magnitudes and positions but we would like to verify them by obtaining short preimages in r and g.
The ITC shows that we would need 1 hour of integration to obtain spectra with S/N > 3 at the HK line for a galaxy brighter than r=19.5 The conditions are IQ=85%, CC=70%, and SB =50%. The cluster is at z=0.1 and we use 1 arcsec slits and the B600 grating.
We estimate that we would need 10 minutes of preimaging (5 in r and 5 in g). This plus the overhead would yield 15 minutes per pointing. Then we would need another 1 hour per field for spectroscopy plus 18 minutes of overhead. This would yiled 78 minutes. So per pointing we would need 93 minutes or 3 hours in total.

p1_attachments.name: Fig 1 - Low resolution UKIRT/UISTspectra of two candidate smooth-spectrum GC sources, from our first attempt to identify such sources. The spectrum at left is clearly from a dust-embedded object suitable for absorption spectroscopy of the interstellar medium, while the object at right, a highly extinguished and very cool red giant, with CO and steam bands, is unsuitable. Emission features are due at least in part to H I recombination lines in the photosphere of the A-type calibration star.

Fig 2a - Gemini South / Phoenix spectra of the H3+ R(1,1)l line at 3.715um and CO lines near 2.34um. The top spectrum of source GCS3-2, from Oka et al. (2005) shows narrow absorption lines, which have counterparts in CO (see Fig 2b), due to gas in foreground spiral arms, and a broad trough of absorption (not seen in CO) due to warm and diffuse gas in the inner few hundred parsecs of the Galaxy (see Oka et al 2005 for detailed discussion). The lower two spectra, obtained in July 2009, are of two smooth-spectrum sources identified in the UKIRT survey. The middle spectrum (same source as shown in Fig 1) contains at least four absorption components some of which are likely in foreground spiral arm material, but others of which are local to the GC. This line of sight is in the direction of the massive H II region Sgr C. The remarkable spectrum at bottom consists of ~10 discrete absorption components. Further analysis and comparison with the corresponding CO spectrum (Fig 2b) is required to determine if this line of sight, which is in the direction of the Sgr B2 molecular cloud, includes the warm and diffuse component seen toward GCS3-2 and other GC sources.
Fig 2b - Spectra of the CO 2-0 R(1) line at 2.34um for the same targets as in Fig. 2a.

(2005) shows narrow absorption lines, which have counterparts in CO (see Fig 2b), due to gas in foreground spiral arms, and a broad trough of absorption (not seen in CO) due to warm and diffuse gas in the inner few hundred parsecs of the Galaxy (see Oka et al 2005 for detailed discussion). The lower two spectra, obtained in July 2009, are of two smooth-spectrum sources identified in the UKIRT survey. The middle spectrum (same source as shown in Fig 1) contains at least four absorption components some of which are likely in foreground spiral arm material, but others of which are local to the GC. This line of sight is in the direction of the massive H II region Sgr C. The remarkable spectrum at bottom consists of ~10 discrete absorption components. Further analysis and comparison with the corresponding CO spectrum (Fig 2b) is required to determine if this line of sight, which is in the direction of the Sgr B2 molecular cloud, includes the warm and diffuse component seen toward GCS3-2 and other GC sources.
Fig 2b - Spectra of the CO 2-0 R(1) line at 2.34um for the same targets as in Fig. 2a.

p1_commons.abstract: We request poor weather time to expand our search for bright objects with featureless infrared spectra in the line of sight to the Galactic center (GC). Such objects are needed in order to more thoroughly study the interstellar environment toward and within the center. Our previous research has used high resolution spectroscopy of H3+ and CO toward known sources in the central few tens of parsecs of the Galaxy to identify a previously unknown but apparently extensive component of warm and diffuse interstellar gas. Evidence to date suggests that this component pervades the central molecular zone (CMZ), which extends ~170 pc from the center, but it is necessary to identify additional smooth-spectrum sources further from the center to use as probes to determine the gas' true extent. We have started identifying such sources based on 2MASS and GLIMPSE photometry and have already obtained some striking results both within and near the border of the CMZ. The poor weather time requested here would allow us to survey 120 candidate smooth-spectrum objects and likely will produce a host of new sightlines that can be investigated using high-resolution IR spectroscopy.
p1_commons.title: Additional probes of the Galactic center's interstellar medium

p1_commons.abstract: For over a century two classes of optical transients have been studied in detail - nova eruptions and supernova explosions, of which hundreds are known. Both classes occupy narrow ranges of luminosities around -8 and -18 mag (+/-2 mag), respectively. However, in recent years several transients have been discovered in the wide nova-SN gap and at high luminosity (M<-20mag), suggesting that a large population of new transients remains to be discovered. The origin of these events is hotly debated. They have been argued to represent massive star eruptions, deficient white dwarf thermonuclear explosions, the explosions of eta Carina-like stars, and possibly new kinds of SN mechanisms (pair-instability). The Pan-STARRS project, now in operation, provides an unprecedented opportunity to explore this sparsely-sampled phase space thanks to its depth and areal coverage. As members of the Pan-STARRS consortium we propose here TOO spectroscopy of such events to classify and characterize their origin.
p1_commons.title: Exotic Explosions and Eruptions: Exploring a New Transient Phase-Space with Pan-STARRS

p1_gemini_allocation_extensions.related_proposals_info:
We have also secured AAT time to observe with the SPIRAL IFU 100 nearby SDSS galaxies which are serving as our benchmark for comparison with the high-z Universe. Our group is unique in having access to such a sample.
We have also been trying to observe kinematics on these targets with OSIRIS on Keck (Swinburne TAC time) but have concluded that OSIRIS does not have the sensitivity to do this (see SJ).

We have ongoing photometric followup programmes on UKIRT, WHT, and NTT to obtain YJHK and z photometry. We also have a Subaru programme to obtain spectroscopy. We also have an ongoing UKIRT program to obtain parallaxes for the late-T dwarfs. Confirmed, but unpublished, T dwarfs are fed to a Keck LGS program to search for close binaries (PI: Liu, IfA).

p1_gemini_band3_extensions.consideration_text: Our observing conditions for Bands 1 and 2 are already very relaxed. We can provide more than 120 targets if more time is available.
Our observing conditions for Bands 1 and 2 are already very relaxed. We can provide more than 120 targets if more time is available.

In the event of band-3 ranking, we would make use of the typically poorer band-3 conditions by focussing on obtaining only the emission line IFU data for the nuclear region of the target galaxy. Even with IQ85 conditions, the line ratios would reveal the presence of an AGN, but with a larger associated error on its position.

As a minimum band-3 time request we would want to make at least half (the 15 brightest candidates) of our requested short triggers, and also at least 1 of the long brighter triggers (JHK). With band 3 time we would keep the same condition constraints (which fit well with the "band-3 rule of thumb" PIT instructions), and our minimum request would this be 12.5 hrs.

Good seeing, dark sky and photometric conditions are extremely important in discerning faint coma emission from the bare nucleus. We require <1.0" arcsec delivered, which is really quite close to the IQ=70% bin, which is equivalent to our default constraints.

Good seeing, dark sky and photometric conditions are extremely important in discerning faint coma emission from the bare nucleus. We require <1.0" arcsec delivered, which is really quite close to the IQ=70% bin, which is equivalent to our default constraints.
The cloud cover can be relaxed to 70% without significantly affecting the performance of ALTAIR. The minimum time requested is 4.0 hr, in the case that only one galaxy is observed.

We are asking for 7 hours from each of the USA, Gemini, and UK TACs. Each fossil group requires 7 hours of observation to reach R=20.1. If we were to get Band 3 time we would observe for only 5 hours per fossil group. This would reduce the number of galaxies/group that we could get useful spectra for but still allow us to observe enough galaxies to obtain a representative sample for each fossil group.

Although both bands would allow us to construct an SED which would provide a much stronger confirmation of the binary nature of these objects- either band worth of imaging could reveal the first identified dust structures around any of these stars. Thus our band 3 minimum is enough time to complete one band worth of imaging for each object.

The ITC gives 4.5h on target exposure for our r=18.95, Teff=15000K star and 3.5h for our 19.18, Teff=36000K star, and a total of 15h for the project, i.e., 60% longer. If we are granted Band 3, our minimum required time of 6.4h excludes the two faintest stars, but which are also the most massive candidates.
The cloud cover can be relaxed to 70% without significantly affecting the performance of ALTAIR. The minimum time requested is 4.0 hr, in the case that only one galaxy is observed.
If the proposed observation is ranked Band 3, we will relax the observing constraints to IQ=85%-ile. The science goal of both [NeII] imaging and spectroscopy can still be achieved under IQ=85%-ile.

If band 3 is awarded then we will relax the sky brightness from 50 (dark) to 80 (grey); S/N will be decreased from ~15 to ~10 at i for the faintest targets. The minimum request of 5.8 hrs would allow us to obtain one of the brighter T7.5-T8 dwarfs as a reference point, the important T8.5 W940B and one of the T9 dwarfs.

If given band 3 time we will relax our IQ constraint from IQ70 to IQ85. This will give us S/N 10-20 over the spectrum instead of 15-30. We will not be able to model any weak hydrogen lines, but we will still be able to confirm that the targets are white dwarfs. If less time than requested can be allocated we will drop the two faintest objects; the remaining 5 can be observed in 5.5 hours.

We wouldl observe only along five slit positions (along p.a.0) if allocated under band 3. These observations would be enough to disentangle the inner velocity components and constraining the SMBH mass. We would not be able to resolve the orbit anisotropy-outflow degeneracy in the outer radii of the nuclear region.

Our survey could be feasible in band 3, although the usually less favorable observing conditions would deteriorate the achievable ADI contrast, and thus less sensitivity to BDs/exoplanets. We are thus selecting the same observation parameters and integration time/target as our proposed survey. If less time is attributed, we will remove a corresponding number of targets from our list. Due to the competitive nature of this survey, we urge the TAC/ITAC to avoid if at all possible scheduling our survey in band 3. Acquiring a large sample of young stars in a timely manner is crucial for the success of this proposal, i.e. constraining BD/planet population/formation around young stars for the 10-250 AU interval.
Targets are bright (V=4-8) and can tolerate significant cloud.

We cannot relax our constraints for Band 3. In previous semesters we have observed most of the bright bodies. The bodies remaining are close to our survey limit and require unreasonable amounts of time to observe with relaxed observing constraints.

In case this proposal is ranked Band 3, we would relax the cloud cover conditions to CC70%. Even though there would be a loss of photometric accuracy, we at least would be able to use the relative photometry to select our targets for spectroscopic follow-up. Increased extinction would force us to increase exposure times to preserve photometric depth. Using the ITC we estimate that an increase of exposure times by a factor of (1.66,1.72,1.33) in bands (J,H,K) would be required in order to keep constant S/N when switching from CC50 to CC70, assuming all other conditions constant (see technical justification). In view of the needed increase in exposure time and decrease in likelihood of data collection, we would reduce our target list to one well selected cluster with previous HST imaging (thus with well known structural parameters). Taking into account the factors listed above and the overheads, the minimum time to obtain useful data for one cluster under deriorated, yet tolerable, conditions, would be 4.1 hours.

Assuming typical Band 3 observing conditions with IQ=85%, CC=70%, WV=any, BG=80%, airmass=1.5 will increase the required exposure times by a factor of about 2.5. To reach similar S/N ratios in our galaxy spectra, we would therefore need 9 integrations of 900 sec per target. In Band 3 category each target would require a total of 2.75 hours. The minimum required time for usable Band 3 allocation would be 22.0 hours, which covers all 8 galaxies of our remaining target sample.

If given band 3 time we will relax our IQ constraint from IQ70 to IQ85. This will give us S/N 10-20 over the spectrum instead of 15-30. We will not be able to model any weak hydrogen lines, but we will still be able to confirm that the targets are white dwarfs. If less time than requested can be allocated we will drop the two faintest objects; the remaining 6 can be observed in 7.2 hours.

Good seeing, dark sky and photometric conditions are extremely important in discerning faint coma emission from the bare nucleus. We require <1.0" arcsec delivered, which is really quite close to the IQ=70% bin, which is equivalent to our default constraints.

In Band 3, we will select the brightest targets, and - pending guide star availability - can probably accept IQ=Any or CC=90 conditions for some of the targets. The minimum required time is enough for about 10 pairs.
We would accept allocation in Band 4 with IQ=Any, SB=80+CC=70 or 90, or SB=Any+CC=50 or 70, in which case we would request an allocation of 50hrs, as many of the pairs will require separate observations due to guide star availability.
We can probably tolerate higher water vapour in band 3.

We would sample two gas species (through Pa_beta and H_2(1-0)_S(1)) only along five slit positions (along P.A.0) if allocated 6h under Band 3. These observations would be enough to disentangle the inner velocity components and constraining the SMBH mass. We would not be able to unveil neither the origin of the asymmetric [FeII] disk nor the orbit anisotropy-outflow degeneracy in the outer radii of the nuclear region.

In case of Band 3 allocation we will reduce the number of targets to 3 for 2MASS GC02 and 4 for Mercer 5. Minimum time required is allowing to get reliable dataset for each one of the target clusters.
We would only use one mask. The observed galaxies will help us to start to parameterize teh merger model.
